{"title_page": "Martial law in Poland", "text_new": "{{short description|Coup d'\u00e9tat}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Martial law in Poland\n| place       = {{flagicon|Poland}} [[Poland]]\n| partof      = the [[Soviet reaction to the Polish crisis of 1980\u20131981]]\n| combatant1  = {{flagicon|Polish People's Republic}} [[Polish People's Republic]]\n* [[Polish People's Army]]\n* [[Milicja_Obywatelska|Citizens' Militia (MO)]]\n* [[ZOMO]]\n* [[S\u0142u\u017cba Bezpiecze\u0144stwa|Secret Service (SB)]]\n----\n'''Supported by:''' \n{{flag|Soviet Union}} ({{small|Intelligence support and military equipment}})\n| combatant2  = {{flagicon image|}} [[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarity Movement]]\n* [[Fighting Solidarity]] <br><small>(from 1982)</small>\n* Protesters\n----\n'''Supported by:''' \n{{flag|United States}} ({{small|Financial support}})\n| casualties1 = Unknown\n| casualties2 = \n*91 killed\n*Thousands arrested\n| commander1  = [[Wojciech Jaruzelski]] \n* [[Czes\u0142aw Kiszczak]]\n| commander2  = [[Lech Wa\u0142\u0119sa]]\n*[[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Frasyniuk]]\n| image       = File:T-55A Martial law Poland.jpg\n| image_size  = 280px\n| caption     = A column of Polish [[T-55]] tanks enters the town of [[Zb\u0105szy\u0144]] while moving east towards the city of [[Pozna\u0144]], 13 December 1981\n| date        = 13 December 1981 \u2013 22 July 1983\n({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=12|day1=13|year1=1981|month2=07|day2=22|year2=1983}})\n| result      = Decisive Polish government victory\n*Crackdown on opposition\n*Protests suppressed \n*Deepened economic crisis\n*Continued resistance until 1989\n| strength1   ='''Initial strength''':<ref>https://culture.pl/en/article/the-day-poland-stood-still-memories-from-the-introduction-of-martial-law</ref>\n*80,000 soldiers\n*30,000 policemen\n*1,750 tanks\n*1,900 combat vehicles\n*9,000 cars\n| strength2   = ~ 10 million (1981)\n}}\n\n'''Martial law in Poland''' ({{lang-pl|Stan wojenny w Polsce}}) refers to the period between 13 December 1981 and 22 July 1983, when the [[authoritarian]] [[communist government]] of the [[Polish People's Republic]] drastically restricted normal life by introducing [[martial law]] and a [[military junta]] in an attempt to throttle political opposition, in particular the [[Solidarity Movement]]. Thousands of opposition activists were [[Internment|imprisoned]] without charge and as many as 91 killed.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/6175517.stm Poland marks communist crackdown], [[BBC News]], 13 December 2006</ref> Although martial law was lifted in 1983, many of the [[political prisoner]]s were not released until a general [[amnesty]] in 1986.\n\nSince the 1970s, communist Poland was in a deep [[economic recession]]. The First Secretary [[Edward Gierek]] made large incessant loans from western creditors to achieve a better economic output that instead resulted in a domestic crisis. Basic goods were being heavily [[Rationing|rationed]] which acted as a stimuli for the establishment of a first anti-communist [[trade union]] in the [[Eastern Bloc]], known as Solidarity, in 1980. Gierek, who permitted the trade union to appear per the [[Gda\u0144sk Agreement]], was dismissed from his post less than a month later under pressure from the USSR and confined to [[house arrest]]. Poland's already somewhat liberal policies concerning the opposition were worrisome for hardliners in the [[Soviet Union]], who feared that the Poles may overthrow communism and ally themselves with the [[Western Bloc]]. The Soviets were particularly uneasy as the departure of Eastern Bloc's most populous nation from [[Comecon]] would trigger further financial and economic problems that would bring an end to communist rule in Central-Eastern Europe. After a series of strikes and demonstrations by employees of chief industrial regions, Poland was directly heading towards bankruptcy. \n\nThe [[Military Council of National Salvation]] was formed by the new First Secretary of the Polish United Workers' Party, General [[Wojciech Jaruzelski]], who was determined to put an end to the demonstrations and crush the opposition by force if necessary. There is speculation whether Jaruzelski instigated martial law to prevent bloodshed if the Soviets and other [[Warsaw Pact]] countries were to enter Poland under the mutual assistance treaty, like in the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956]] and the [[invasion of Czechoslovakia in 1968]]. On 13 December 1981, Jaruzelski announced the introduction of martial law in a televised speech addressed to the entire nation. The Polish People's Army, [[Citizen's Militia]] (MO), [[ZOMO]] special units and tanks rolled onto the streets to scare off demonstrators, begin regular patrols and maintain [[curfew]]. Intercity travelling was forbidden unless a permit was granted by the authorities, food shortages intensified and censorship was placed on all media and [[Mail|post]]. The [[S\u0142u\u017cba Bezpiecze\u0144stwa|secret services (SB)]] [[wiretapped]] phones in public booths and state institutions. \n\nOn 16 December, pro-Solidarity miners organized a strike against the declaration of the martial law at the [[Wujek Coal Mine]] in the industrial city of [[Katowice]]. The ZOMO squads, nicknamed \"Communist [[Gestapo]]\" by the opposition, brutally [[Pacification of Wujek|pacified Wujek]], which resulted in the deaths of 9 miners. All other [[1982 demonstrations in Poland|demonstrations across Poland]] were met with armed force of the services, which utilized [[water cannons]], [[tear gas]], [[Baton (law enforcement)|batons]], truncheons and clubs to disperse crowds and beat protesters. Thousands were detained and some were tortured in state prisons. On 31 August 1982, in the copper-mining town of [[Lubin]], 3 people were mortally wounded by ZOMO. Until the end of the martial law on 22 July 1983, approximately 91 people were killed, though this figure varies and is still debated among historians.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/6175517.stm Poland marks communist crackdown], [[BBC News]], 13 December 2006</ref>\n\n==Prelude==\n{{main|History of Poland (1945\u20131989)}}\n===Reforms of Edward Gierek (1970-1975)===\n[[File:Photograph of President Gerald R. Ford, First Secretary Edward Gierek of Poland, and Mrs. Stanislawa Gierek Waving from the Blue Room Balcony during a State Arrival Ceremony - NARA - 7462054.jpg|thumb|right|230px|Gierek in the [[White House]] with President [[Gerald Ford]], 1974]]\nWhen [[Edward Gierek]] succeeded [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Gomu\u0142ka|Gomu\u0142ka]] as the head of state in 1970, he took decisive measures to boost economic growth and develop modern infrastructure.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=WGGaAAAAIAAJ&q=reformy+gierka+nowoczesne&dq=reformy+gierka+nowoczesne&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiHgZO8j97oAhW7xjgGHU_gAJEQ6AEIKzAA</ref> Gierek, a more [[Liberalism|liberal]] figure than his predecessor, was determined to make [[Polish People's Republic|Poland]] the wealthiest and most economically significant communist country of the [[Eastern Bloc]].<ref>https://nowahistoria.interia.pl/prl/news-edward-gierek-i-jego-koncepcja-drugiej-polski,nId,2354535,nPack,3</ref> However, these ideas prompted resistance from hardline communist leadership as the reform would effectively abandon the fundamental principles of a [[Planned economy|centrally planned]] [[Marxism|Marxist]] economy. The grip and emphasis on state-owned enterprises and state-controlled prices or trade was eventually loosened. Small private businesses began to appear and Poland recorded temporary growth in [[GDP]] and an improvement in living conditions.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=xCFDAQAAIAAJ&q=gierek+jako%C5%9B%C4%87&dq=gierek+jako%C5%9B%C4%87&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwij7ujpj97oAhXbwzgGHe2mAPoQ6AEIZTAG</ref><ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=LSSauLSn9YMC&pg=PA42&lpg=PA42&dq=gierek+marks&source=bl&ots=_2quNkfJ1B&sig=ACfU3U12haOc3udIsqtB8YB61ITcDtL61w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjzh9PQkN7oAhX54zgGHXsmBV0Q6AEwCnoECAsQKw#v=onepage&q=gierek%20marks&f=false</ref>\n\nGierek maintained close ties with the [[United States]], which he subsequently used for diplomatic and economic purposes.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=LSSauLSn9YMC&pg=PA42&lpg=PA42&dq=gierek+marks&source=bl&ots=_2quNkfJ1B&sig=ACfU3U12haOc3udIsqtB8YB61ITcDtL61w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjzh9PQkN7oAhX54zgGHXsmBV0Q6AEwCnoECAsQKw#v=onepage&q=gierek%20marks&f=false</ref> In order to continue with the reforms, large sums of money were borrowed from [[creditors]] in the [[Western Bloc]].<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=Vae1AAAAIAAJ&q=gierek+po%C5%BCyczki&dq=gierek+po%C5%BCyczki&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiDvoKVkd7oAhV0zTgGHVzLAW8Q6AEIcTAH</ref> These sequential and uninterrupted loans were primarily targeted at establishing heavy industry, mines or manufacturing facilities that would produce goods for [[export]].<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=Vae1AAAAIAAJ&q=gierek+po%C5%BCyczki&dq=gierek+po%C5%BCyczki&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiDvoKVkd7oAhV0zTgGHVzLAW8Q6AEIcTAH</ref><ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=POkSAQAAMAAJ&q=gierek+d%C5%82ug+przemysl+%C5%9Bl%C4%85sk&dq=gierek+d%C5%82ug+przemysl+%C5%9Bl%C4%85sk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjfspz0kd7oAhXewzgGHU-QApwQ6AEIazAH</ref> The projected income from the exports would then be used to pay off the [[debt]]. Apart from financing the economic sector, the money was spent on [[social housing]] and on expanding road connections, for example the first fully operational [[highway]] linking Warsaw with industrial [[Silesia]] was opened for traffic in 1976.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=vtcsAAAAMAAJ&q=gierek+warszawa+centralna+gierk%C3%B3wka&dq=gierek+warszawa+centralna+gierk%C3%B3wka&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjbiJGQkt7oAhWOwzgGHaLGBjEQ6AEIKzAA</ref> Furthermore, over 1.8 million [[plattenbau]] flats were constructed to house the growing population. Agricultural output rose by nearly 22% between 1971 and 1975, and industrial production by 10.5% annually.<ref>https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/CIA-RDP86T00608R000500200020-4.pdf</ref><ref>file:///C:/Users/User/Downloads/Harmonijny_rozwoj_czy_droga_ku_p.pdf</ref> Gierek also initiated the construction of [[Warszawa Centralna]], Europe's most modern railway station at the time.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=35o8AQAAIAAJ&q=gierek+warszawa+dworzec&dq=gierek+warszawa+dworzec&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjk1q2zkt7oAhXuzDgGHdisDfEQ6AEITjAE</ref><ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=0rk9DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT149&dq=warszawa+centralna+dworzec+w+europie&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwirx7_Gkt7oAhXOzTgGHQ9vDTEQ6AEIRTAD#v=onepage&q=warszawa%20centralna%20dworzec%20w%20europie&f=false</ref><ref>https://www.mwkz.pl/archiwum-aktualnosci-lista/1308-dworzec-centralny-wpisany-do-rejestru-zabytkow</ref><ref>https://tvn24.pl/tvnwarszawa/najnowsze/miliardy-na-budowe-brtak-powstawal-dworzec-centralny-187645</ref>\n\n===Crisis; debt, rationing and shortages (1976-1981)===\n[[File:Kartka cukier 1kg 07-76.jpg|thumb|left|140px|A ration card for sugar, 1976]]\nAs expenditures increased and debts accumulated, the West would no longer grant Poland loans. Moreover, the [[1973 oil crisis|1973]], [[June 1976 protests]] and [[1979 oil crisis|1979 oil crises]] affected the fragile economy. Due to previous GDP growth, higher income and expanded industries, the demand for certain goods and [[Consumption (economics)|consumption]] surged.<ref>https://www.wprost.pl/354447/polska-splacila-dlug-gierka-po-40-latach.html</ref><ref>https://www.forbes.pl/przywodztwo/wyscig-z-dlugiem-jak-ekipa-edward-gierka-zadluzyla-polske/z6vv26r</ref> New factories and state enterprises required imported fuel, materials and a workforce to operate production lines.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=Vae1AAAAIAAJ&q=gierek+d%C5%82ug+import&dq=gierek+d%C5%82ug+import&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjq0f7mlN7oAhVFxzgGHX2BCzcQ6AEINDAB</ref> Soon, the country started exporting locally-produced stock designated for the Polish populace, thus resulting in widespread [[shortages]].<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=9pbFBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA33&dq=gierek+d%C5%82ug+kartki+braki&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiw7OObld7oAhWN4zgGHWqMDb0Q6AEIKzAA#v=onepage&q=gierek%20d%C5%82ug%20kartki%20braki&f=false</ref> Because the remaining assets were directed at production, exports and debt repayment, the state also reduced imports to minimize expenses. \n\nIn 1976, the communist government introduced [[ration cards]] for sugar.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=JrZEAQAAIAAJ&q=gierek+d%C5%82ug+kartki+braki&dq=gierek+d%C5%82ug+kartki+braki&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiw7OObld7oAhWN4zgGHWqMDb0Q6AEIPTAC</ref> Meat, processed food and dairy followed.<ref>http://info.wyborcza.biz/szukaj/gospodarka/kwoty+cukru</ref> Confectionery, [[cocoa bean|cocoa]], coffee, rice, [[tobacco]] and other goods not produced in Poland were so heavily rationed that they were almost permanently unavailable.<ref>https://www.polskieradio.pl/39/156/Artykul/320244,Zycie-na-kartki</ref><ref>http://info.wyborcza.biz/szukaj/gospodarka/kwoty+cukru</ref> Due to the constant lack of tobacco, ordinary cigarettes became a form of new currency on the [[black market]].<ref>http://www.ippt.pan.pl/Repository/zycie_%20w_ciekawych_czasach_15_10_2012.pdf</ref> The living standards began to sharply decline; the supply of imported goods was kept to a low minimum and the county was forced to export everything it could, including coal necessary for basic heating and power plants. [[Power outage]]s were commonplace.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=ukkpAQAAIAAJ&q=gierek+wylaczenie+pr%C4%85du&dq=gierek+wylaczenie+pr%C4%85du&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjXqpe7l97oAhW3zzgGHSzyDJEQ6AEIKDAA</ref> By 1980, the debt accounted to over US$23 billion, then almost half of Poland's [[nominal GDP]].<ref>https://www.tygodnikprzeglad.pl/pawel-bozyk-zaklamywanie-prawdy-o-dlugach-gierka/</ref>        \n\n[[File:Jimmy Carter and Edward Gierek First Secretary of Poland - NARA - 177308.tif|thumb|right|230px|[[Edward Gierek]] (right) with President [[Jimmy Carter]] (left) during his state visit to Warsaw, 1977. The loans and Solidarity were among the chief topics discussed]]\n\nAt the same time, the newly-founded [[Solidarity movement]] encouraged farmers to refrain from selling agricultural products (wheat, grain, fruit and others) to the state as a sign of protest. The actual lack of goods on the market and in stores was caused by the fact that production stopped due to the strikes organized by Solidarity.<ref>http://muzhp.pl/pl/c/971/gierek-siedzial-na-wulkanie-ktory-w-koncu-eksplodowal</ref> In 1980, the national income fell by 6% compared to previous year, and in 1981 by 12%.<ref>https://wiadomosci.onet.pl/kiosk/polska-gierka/myj3y</ref> The number of exports declined by 4.2%. Mismanagement and wastefulness were abundant.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=ZQ9NDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT182&lpg=PT182&dq=gierek+marnotrawstwo&source=bl&ots=XheuY7_TIT&sig=ACfU3U0LWAGCKo33VnDTiTE5H_dTufhr5Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjupceqmd7oAhVqzjgGHaZ3ANYQ6AEwDXoECAwQKw#v=onepage&q=gierek%20marnotrawstwo&f=false</ref> \n\nOn 6 September 1980, Gierek was dismissed from his office, expelled from the Polish United Workers' Party (possibly under the pressure from the Soviet Union) and falsely charged with [[corruption]].<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=pdAbAQAAMAAJ&q=gierek+6+wrze%C5%9Bnia+1980&dq=gierek+6+wrze%C5%9Bnia+1980&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjO2sH0md7oAhWmxDgGHRovD0cQ6AEIZDAG</ref><ref>file:///C:/Users/User/Downloads/Dyskusja-wokol-ksiazki-Rozliczenia-z-ekipa-Gierka-19801984-Warszawa-6-wrzesnia-2.pdf</ref> A year later, on 10 September 1981, the Soviet authorities informed the Polish government that in connection with the prevailing situation in Poland the USSR would cut oil supply to Poland by 64% and gas by 47%.<ref>Andrzej Krajewski, \u201eGazowa p\u0119tla\u201d, Dziennik Gazeta Prawna nr 111/2016.</ref> The import of [[diesel fuel|diesel]] from the Soviet Union was terminated immediately.<ref>Andrzej Krajewski, \u201eGazowa p\u0119tla\u201d, Dziennik Gazeta Prawna nr 111/2016.</ref> This action was intended to force the Polish communist authorities to suppress the demonstrations and dissolve Solidarity.<ref>https://wiadomosci.onet.pl/nszz</ref> The situation was already dire and gradually worsened, which only fueled anti-communist sentiment. A [[civil war]] was hanging by a thread.<ref>https://www.polskieradio24.pl/80/1492/Artykul/www.polskieradio.pl/13/53/Artykul/254368</ref>\n\nIn 1981, Poland notified [[Club de Paris]] (a group of Western-European central banks) about its [[insolvency]], which caught the attention of the entire world.<ref>http://www.clubdeparis.org/en/traitements/poland-27-04-1981/en</ref>\n\n==Introduction, restrictions, patrols==\n===Secret preparations and provocation===\n[[File:Wojciech Jaruzelski.jpg|thumb|left|150px|General [[Wojciech Jaruzelski|Jaruzelski]] was determined to suppress any opposition along with the [[Solidarity Movement]]]]\nAfter the short tenure of [[Stanis\u0142aw Kania]], General and Minister of Defence [[Wojciech Jaruzelski]] was chosen as the new First Secretary. Before assuming office, Jaruzelski ordered the Polish General Staff to update plans for a nationwide martial law on 22 October 1980.<ref>''From Solidarity to Martial Law: The Polish Crisis of 1980\u20131981: A Documentary History'' by Andrzej Paczkowski, Malcolm Byrne. Central European University Press, Budapest 2007. p. xxxiii</ref> In November 1980, the [[Ministry of Internal Affairs (Poland)|Ministry of Internal Affairs]] planned to potentially facilitate thousands of oppositionists in state prisons and places of internment.<ref>https://tvn24.pl/polska/13-grudnia-2019-38-rocznica-wprowadzenia-stanu-wojennego-ra992894-2586819</ref> \n\nOn 5 December 1980, Kania spoke of the preparations relating to martial law at the [[Warsaw Pact|Warsaw Pact Summit]] in [[Moscow]].<ref>https://dzieje.pl/aktualnosci/koniec-epoki-brezniewa</ref><ref>https://www.polityka.pl/tygodnikpolityka/historia/1533463,1,stanislaw-kania---przeciwnik-stanu-wojennego.read</ref> He presented his own view of how to weaken Solidarity and insisted that a \"psychological-operational method\" would be most appropriate to prevent violence.<ref>https://przystanekhistoria.pl/pa2/teksty/57519,Czemu-stan-wojenny-wprowadzono-dopiero-w-nocy-z-12-na-13-grudnia-1981-r.html</ref> This method entailed strong [[propaganda]]<ref>https://przystanekhistoria.pl/pa2/teksty/57519,Czemu-stan-wojenny-wprowadzono-dopiero-w-nocy-z-12-na-13-grudnia-1981-r.html</ref> against the movement and deploying [[S\u0142u\u017cba Bezpiecze\u0144stwa|Secret Services (SB)]] to go undercover and infiltrate Solidarity headquarters in the hope of creating internal conflicts within the opposition. General Jaruzelski was not fully satisfied with the plan, and, in case of failure, already planned radical actions involving the army. Stanis\u0142aw Kania warned [[Brezhnev]] that an armed intervention from the Soviet side to aid Jaruzelski would be met \"with a violent reaction, or even with a national uprising\"<ref>https://wyborcza.pl/1,76842,6976876,Bedziecie_tu_mieli_powstanie__towarzyszu_Brezniew.html</ref> that would shake the politics of the Eastern Bloc.<ref>https://wyborcza.pl/1,76842,6976876,Bedziecie_tu_mieli_powstanie__towarzyszu_Brezniew.html</ref>     \n\n[[Zbigniew Brzezinski]], chief security advisor to US President [[Jimmy Carter]], stated that if the Soviet Union would undertake an armed intervention in Poland, the US would strike back in a [[riposte]] manner.<ref>https://dziennikzwiazkowy.com/historia-2/zbigniew-brzezinski-i-jego-strategia-wygrania-zimnej-wojny/</ref>  According to historian and publicist [[Paul Kengor]], the then US President [[Ronald Reagan]] considered sending American troops to Poland to scare off the Soviets.<ref>https://wyborcza.pl/1,75399,3976852.html</ref> This claim was not supported by Brzezinski nor by [[Richard Pipes]] from [[Harvard University]].<ref>https://wyborcza.pl/1,75399,3976852.html</ref> Kengor then elaborated that Reagan eventually abandoned the plan after he was convinced by his own advisors that the US army stationed across Europe is less capable and much weaker than the Soviet forces.<ref>https://wyborcza.pl/1,75399,3976852.html</ref> The United States eventually striked back with economic sanctions against Poland and the USSR.<ref>https://dziennikzwiazkowy.com/historia-2/zbigniew-brzezinski-i-jego-strategia-wygrania-zimnej-wojny/</ref> \n\n[[File:WieczorWroclawia20marca1981.jpg|thumb|right|240px|A censored regional newspaper that reported about the [[Bydgoszcz events]], in which the [[Milicja Obywatelska|Militia]] abused Solidarity members. The censorship was to prevent the slander of state services]] \n\nIn February 1981, the [[Ministry of National Defence (Poland)|Ministry of National Defence]] and Ministry of the Internal Affairs carried out a training scenario, the purpose of which was to explore how martial law will be introduced.<ref>https://pamiec.pl/pa/kalendarium-1/13389,16-lutego-1981-roku-w-Warszawie-przeprowadzono-wspolna-gre-sztabowa-MON-i-MSW-po.html</ref> The ministries agreed that martial law should be preceded by appropriate propaganda calling for its support, and the decision itself should be based on a pretext that it would bring peace and stability for the society.<ref>file:///C:/Users/User/Downloads/Ruzikowski_Stan_wojenny_w_Warszawie.pdf</ref> It was also highlighted that martial law must occur before the fully mobilized [[Fighting Solidarity]] and its allies organize a [[general strike]] that would paralyze the entire country.<ref>file:///C:/Users/User/Downloads/Ruzikowski_Stan_wojenny_w_Warszawie.pdf</ref> By March, the situation escalated after the [[Bydgoszcz events]], in which local Solidarity delegates invited for a [[National Council (Poland)|Regional National Council]] meeting in [[Bydgoszcz]] to discuss potential strikes were beaten and abused by the [[Citizens' Militia]] (MO).<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=93eUER87BmsC&pg=PA119&dq=bydgoszcz+1981&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiKnuPQo97oAhXuzzgGHdvZAzwQ6AEIMTAB#v=onepage&q=bydgoszcz%201981&f=false</ref> The event, which was to feature in newspapers as a [[provocation (legal)|provocation]], was concealed by [[censors]]. On 27 March, Solidarity organized a warning strike directed at the government, but, on 30 March, [[Lech Wa\u0142\u0119sa]] met with [[Mieczys\u0142aw Rakowski]] and a compromise was achieved.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=-FCyCDv9QswC&pg=PA43&dq=bydgoszcz+1981+rakowski+walesa&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjupIbgo97oAhUExTgGHTZcDOwQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=bydgoszcz%201981%20rakowski%20walesa&f=false</ref> The general strike was called off and the situation stabilized for a short period.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=-FCyCDv9QswC&pg=PA43&dq=bydgoszcz+1981+rakowski+walesa&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjupIbgo97oAhUExTgGHTZcDOwQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=bydgoszcz%201981%20rakowski%20walesa&f=false</ref>\n\nIn July, the Soviets increased their military presence in the military base at [[Borne Sulinowo]], where the [[Red Army]] stationed per [[Warsaw Pact]] agreement as in all other [[Eastern Bloc]] countries.<ref name=\"Ryszard Kukli\u0144ski. \u017bycie \u015bci\u015ble tajne\">{{cite book |surname=Benjamin Weiser |title=Ryszard Kukli\u0144ski. \u017bycie \u015bci\u015ble tajne |publisher=\u015awiat Ksi\u0105\u017cki |location=Warszawa |year=2005 |isbn = 83-7391-673-3}}</ref>  Without notifying the Polish authorities, the Soviets unexpectedly sent over 600 tanks to Borne Sulinowo. A month later, commander-in-chief of the Warsaw Pact, [[Viktor Kulikov]], requested that Soviet military advisors are to be placed in the Polish General Staff and assigned to nearly all Polish regiments. It is suspected that Kulikov, acting on behalf of the Soviet Union, was tasked with sending undercover [[KGB]] agents to monitor the situation in Poland from the Polish military's perspective. His request, however, was immediately denied by the Polish government.<ref name=\"Ryszard Kukli\u0144ski. \u017bycie \u015bci\u015ble tajne\">{{cite book |surname=Benjamin Weiser |title=Ryszard Kukli\u0144ski. \u017bycie \u015bci\u015ble tajne |publisher=\u015awiat Ksi\u0105\u017cki |location=Warszawa |year=2005 |isbn = 83-7391-673-3}}</ref> \n\nOver 25,000 posters announcing martial law were secretly printed in the USSR, transported to Poland by airplane and hidden in the large building housing the Ministry of Internal Affairs.<ref>[[Ryszard Terlecki]]: ''Miecz i tarcza komunizmu. Historia aparatu bezpiecze\u0144stwa w Polsce 1944-1990'', Krak\u00f3w 2007, p. 270\u2013271.</ref> The full extent of the actions undertaken by Jaruzelski to instigate martial law was not known by even some of the highest notables in the Central Committee of the [[Polish United Workers' Party]] or the Polish [[Sejm]].<ref>file:///C:/Users/User/Downloads/akt-oskarzenia-S-101-04-Zk_2%20(1).pdf</ref>\n\n===12-13 December 1981; Operations Fir and Azalea=== \n[[File:AGAD Posiedzenie Wojskowej Rady Ocalenia Narodowego.png|thumb|left|230px|The [[Military Council of National Salvation]] (WRON), which was founded on 13 December and presided over the [[military junta]]. Its Polish [[abbreviation]] \"WRONa\" means a [[crow]] bird, and members of the council were known to the opposition as evil \"Crows\"]] \nOn 12 December 1981, shortly before [[midnight]], the [[Polish Council of State]] gathered in Warsaw's [[Belweder Palace]] and approved nationwide martial law. Simultaneously, the [[Military Council of National Salvation]] (WRON - ''Wrona'' is translated as \"Crow\") was founded and its members were high-ranking generals or military officers in the [[Polish People's Army]], who were in charge of the [[military junta]]. The generals and officers later became known to the public as evil \"[[Crows]]\", in relation to the Polish name of the council. \n\nAt precisely 00:00 (12:00 a.m.), the [[ZOMO|Motorized Reserves of the Citizens' Militia]] (ZOMO) began \"Akcja Jod\u0142a\" (English: Operation [[Fir]]) and arrested the first members of Solidarity who were at close reach.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=DC9BAQAAIAAJ&q=12,9+tysiecy+miejsc+internowania+stan+wojenny&dq=12,9+tysiecy+miejsc+internowania+stan+wojenny&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj0mfrnm97oAhUTWX0KHYXQDcEQ6AEIKzAA</ref><ref>https://ipn.gov.pl/pl/aktualnosci/37976,Grzegorz-Majchrzak-Stan-wojenny-kryptonim-Jodla.html</ref> They were then placed in previously-prepared detention facilities.<ref>https://ipn.gov.pl/pl/aktualnosci/37976,Grzegorz-Majchrzak-Stan-wojenny-kryptonim-Jodla.html</ref> In total, between 70,000 and 80,000 soldiers of the People's Army and 30,000 functionaries of the Ministry of Internal Affairs (including SB, ZOMO and the Militia) were deployed for action. Around 1,750 tanks, 1,900 armoured combat vehicles, 500 militarized transport units, 9,000 cars and several [[helicopter]] [[squadron]]s were in service.<ref>''From Solidarity to Martial Law: The Polish Crisis of 1980\u20131981: A Documentary History'' by Andrzej Paczkowski, Malcolm Byrne. Central European University Press, Budapest 2007. p. xxxiii</ref><ref>https://culture.pl/en/article/the-day-poland-stood-still-memories-from-the-introduction-of-martial-law</ref><ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=Uqm1AAAAIAAJ&q=prl+stan+wojenny+1900&dq=prl+stan+wojenny+1900&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjI463A9NroAhVezjgGHVwSC34Q6AEIKDAA</ref> 25% of all units concentrated in the capital, Warsaw, or in surrounding localities.\n\nPreceding Jod\u0142a was \"Akcja Azalia\" (English: Operation [[Azalea]]), which began at around 22:30 (10:30 p.m.) on 12 December.<ref>https://www.sejm.gov.pl/Sejm9.nsf/wypowiedz.xsp?posiedzenie=2&dzien=1&wyp=190&symbol=RWYSTAPIENIA_WYP&id=351</ref><ref>https://bliskopolski.pl/leksykon/akcja-azalia/</ref> Per Azalea, the SB secret services, paramilitary troops, the Militia, ZOMO and [[Border Protection Troops]] stormed 451 [[telephone exchange|telecommunications exchange facilities]] and cut telephone lines to allegedly prevent the spread of misinformation.<ref>https://bliskopolski.pl/leksykon/akcja-azalia/</ref> However, the operation's true purpose was preventing Solidarity from contacting its branches in other cities to mobilize protesters. Radio and television stations were also besieged.<ref>https://www.sejm.gov.pl/Sejm9.nsf/wypowiedz.xsp?posiedzenie=2&dzien=1&wyp=190&symbol=RWYSTAPIENIA_WYP&id=351</ref> Any volunteers wishing to assist in the arrests were drafted into [[ORMO]].  \n\nThe [[Polskie Radio|Polish Radio]] informed about martial law being imposed at a 06:00 (6:00 a.m.) audition, and transmitted the speech made by General Jaruzelski.<ref name=\"polskieradio\">{{Cite |url = http://www.polskieradio.pl/39/156/Artykul/1318087,33-lata-temu-wprowadzono-w-Polsce-stan-wojenny |title = 33 lata temu wprowadzono w Polsce stan wojenny |date = 2014-12-13 |page = polskieradio.pl }}</ref> [[Telewizja Polska]] network and its chief news program ''[[Dziennik Telewizyjny|Dziennik]]'' (English: Journal) aired the speech in a slightly modified version.<ref name=\"Ferfecki\">{{Cite |url = http://www.tvp.info/1166664/nieznana-wersja-przemowienia-gen-jaruzelskiego |title = Nieznana wersja przem\u00f3wienia gen. Jaruzelskiego |author = Wiktor Ferfecki, Joanna Idziak |date = 2009-12-13 |page = tvp.info }}</ref> The [[Martial law in Poland#Declaration script|declaration]] was watched by millions of Polish citizens despite the early hour.\n\n===16 December 1981; Wujek Coal Mine===\n{{main|Pacification of Wujek|Wujek Coal Mine}}\n\n[[File:Stan wojenny w Polsce - 1981-1983 - 08.JPG|thumb|right|230px|[[ZOMO]] squads with [[truncheons|police batons]] preparing to disperse and beat protesters. The [[sarcasm|sarcastic]] caption reads \"outstretched hands of understanding\" or \"outstretched hands for agreement\", with batons ironically symbolizing hands]]\n\nThree days after restrictions were imposed, miners at the [[Wujek Coal Mine]] in the industrial city of [[Katowice]] began striking against the declaration of martial law by General Jaruzelski.<ref>https://ipn.gov.pl/pl/aktualnosci/38063,Pacyfikacja-kopalni-Wujek-najwieksza-zbrodnia-stanu-wojennego.html</ref> Most of the miners and workers at Wujek were allied with the Solidarity Movement, with its leaders boycotting the state industries. Furthermore, [[coal]] was a precious fuel source that was used for generating electricity and heat, but also a major export material.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=wpzeOwI67BIC&q=wujek+kopalnia+stan+wojenny+w%C4%99giel&dq=wujek+kopalnia+stan+wojenny+w%C4%99giel&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjk45mTp97oAhWSF3IKHVlSAFAQ6AEIOTAC</ref> By selling and exporting coal, the communist government obtained enough money to gradually pay off the outstanding debt.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=wpzeOwI67BIC&q=wujek+kopalnia+stan+wojenny+w%C4%99giel&dq=wujek+kopalnia+stan+wojenny+w%C4%99giel&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjk45mTp97oAhWSF3IKHVlSAFAQ6AEIOTAC</ref> However, as Solidarity boycotted the mines in Silesia and demonstrations became more frequent, the production level dropped considerably along with revenue. \n\nJaruzelski perceived this as a threat to both state security and the economy. The forces used in the thrust consisted of eight ZOMO squads supported by ORMO, seven water cannons, three regiments with infantry combat vehicles and one tank regiment.<ref>https://www.slaskie.travel/Poi/Pokaz/2781/462/pomnik-dziewieciu-z-wujka-oraz-muzeumizba-pamieci</ref> It was decided that the situation was far too serious for adopting the principles of [[morality]] to appropriately deal with the miners. Instead, the well-equipped ZOMO and army troops fired at the protesters with a \"shoot to kill\" technique.<ref>https://www.slaskie.travel/Poi/Pokaz/2781/462/pomnik-dziewieciu-z-wujka-oraz-muzeumizba-pamieci</ref> 21 were wounded, 8 were killed on the spot and 1 died in hospital, with the youngest victim being only 19 years old.<ref>https://plus.dziennikzachodni.pl/pacyfikacja-kopalni-wujek-po-30-latach-ujawnil-sie-i-mowi-widzialem-dramat-na-wujku-dlaczego-tyle-lat-milczal/ar/c3-12769448</ref> The remaining crowd was violently dispersed. The miners repeatedly fought back with their work tools and, in retaliation, wounded dozens of soldiers and militiamen.<ref>https://www.historiaposzukaj.pl/wiedza,wydarzenia,772,pacyfikacja_kopalni_wujek.html</ref> It was one of the deadliest single incidents during the martial law period.<ref>https://dzieje.pl/aktualnosci/37-lat-temu-zginelo-9-gornikow-kopalni-wujek-najwieksza-tragedia-stanu-wojennego</ref>\n\n===Gda\u0144sk, Krak\u00f3w, Lubin and continuing protests===\n{{see also|1982 demonstrations in Poland}}\n[[File:2010-07-08-gdansk-by-RalfR-05.jpg|thumb|left|221px||The former [[Polish United Workers' Party|PZPR]] headquarters in [[Gda\u0144sk]] (right). ZOMO machine-gunned demonstrators from the rooftop]]\nOn the same day as Wujek was pacified, a 30,000-strong<ref>https://13grudnia81.pl/sw/historia/mapa-regionow-nszz-sol/8390,Region-Gdanski-13-XII-1981-22-VII-1983.html</ref> demonstration was held in the northern port city of [[Gda\u0144sk]]. Clashes with ZOMO continued until 17 December and over 324 individuals were injured. The Militia used firearms and [[machine guns]] when the crowd approached the [[Polish United Workers' Party]] headquarters in Gda\u0144sk.<ref>https://regiony.rp.pl/archiwum/3499-stan-wojenny-zaskoczyl-wszystkich</ref> A short and presumably cautionary [[salvo|gun salvo]] from the building's roof hit several people and wounded 4. 1 participant was killed.<ref>https://www.gdanskstrefa.com/37-rocznica-morderstwa-antoniego-browarczyka/</ref> The southern city of [[Krak\u00f3w]] was also witnessing heavy demonstrations, with thousands marching on the street demanding an end to the martial law and communist rule.<ref>https://polskatimes.pl/orla-wrona-nie-pokona-stan-wojenny-w-polsce/ar/c15-14652107?__cf_chl_jschl_tk__=040b57120dfa209cf74313182fc0e68278da22f7-1586537913-0-AYwocIzvMBLfBRjcutP5-ozRCmsSmJsrruSWLOvamxnHGjAsusoEMGxJrlYKPZhGjRi0pTXh4WoQhQFfsIR5o9rXXeB3yAhHX2vpxRAo0j69eiFmVLHn26KvJYmfQQJUatjy94GlBqCQMag8pm7UFUOrrBT0Qmu4X7jD6T0u1teZBRhr13__6JgnUiW7EyIr94uq09ELeHoOsIw62b3rrF59Ll_cyiU7b38aYVrM2dPIkkVup4h2Y4xuM_XgyWo4sIXQ19MMbopFR7gMP-A8NNQHVbDE6aHIAJnI64rm8Gd3Bt83j7EoswA1vrASnLGzfryaliMbbmPUW0qg_331fMRzQW1CAwKhaUM9qYyi-1MX</ref>  \n\nOn the night of 29-30 April 1982, local miners in [[Wodzis\u0142aw \u015al\u0105ski]] planted a bomb and blew up a monument dedicated to [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] soldiers who liberated Poland from the Nazis in 1945.<ref>https://www.nowiny.pl/79880-bombowcy-ze-slaska-zapomniana-historia.html</ref> It was the only incident involving explosives and the caught perpetrators became subsequently known as \"Bombers from [[Silesia]]\" (Polish: \"Bombowcy ze \u015al\u0105ska\").<ref>https://www.nowiny.pl/79880-bombowcy-ze-slaska-zapomniana-historia.html</ref> The operation was a success as the monument was never reconstructed, though the bombers were sentenced and jailed soon-after. Other suspects and hundreds of other miners across Silesia were sacked and removed from their job posts, which further weakened the economy. \n\nIn May 1982, the protests convened by Solidarity were receiving less attention and the struggle against the government was evidently weakening. However, by August, the social unrest again surged. On 31 August 1982, demonstrations took place in around 66<ref>https://dzieje.pl/aktualnosci/sierpniowe-manifestacje-w-1982-r</ref> towns and cities, with at least 18 in the southwestern [[Lower Silesian Voivodeship|province of Lower Silesia]]. In [[Wroc\u0142aw]], one of main centers of Fighting Solidarity, several thousand people for many hours clashed with ZOMO units.<ref>https://nowahistoria.interia.pl/prl/news-manifestacja-we-wroclawiu-31-sierpnia-1982-roku-kiedy-zomo-u,nId,1067057</ref> One demonstrator was killed by a bullet. \n\nThe copper-mining town of [[Lubin]] also became a hotspot for Solidarity-led rallies.<ref>https://www.polskieradio.pl/39/156/Artykul/2361818,Wydarzenia-lubinskie-Krwawy-sierpien-82-w-Zaglebiu-Miedziowym</ref> On that day, the gathered people sung the Polish national anthem and chanted slurs and slogans against the communist regime, against the military junta with Jaruzelski as its head and against the Soviets. After approximately 30 minutes, the rally of 2,000<ref>https://www.polskieradio.pl/39/156/Artykul/2361818,Wydarzenia-lubinskie-Krwawy-sierpien-82-w-Zaglebiu-Miedziowym</ref> was surrounded by the Militia, armed with [[AK-47]] assault rifles. In response, agitated protesters shouted slurs such as \"pigs\", \"bandits\", \"[[Gestapo]]\", \"murderers\" and \"servants of [[Brezhnev]]\".<ref>https://www.fakt.pl/hobby/historia/zbrodnia-lubinska-co-wydarzylo-sie-w-lubinie-31-sierpnia-1982-r/k7jtr26</ref> An unsuccessful attempt was made at building a [[barricade]], but the government units were able to pass through and dispersed the first group with [[tear gas]]. When the demonstrators regrouped and formed a second wave, ZOMO opened fire and wittingly murdered 2 men. The now infuriated crowd began continuous attacks and the Militia shot several more times, injuring one more man at the back of his head. He died in hospital few days later. Reinforcements were sent from [[Legnica]]<ref>http://31sierpnia1982.pl/lubin</ref> and the new deployees were organized into so-called \"raid groups\" in [[ZSD Nysa|Nysa vans]].<ref>https://www.polskieradio.pl/39/156/Artykul/2361818,Wydarzenia-lubinskie-Krwawy-sierpien-82-w-Zaglebiu-Miedziowym</ref><ref>https://dzieje.pl/artykuly-historyczne/lubin-1982-zbrodnia-nieukarana</ref> These groups roamed the streets, often attacking casual passers-by.<ref>https://dzieje.pl/artykuly-historyczne/lubin-1982-zbrodnia-nieukarana</ref> Immediately after the protest was pacified, security forces began the destruction of any evidence to conceal the crime.<ref>https://pamiec.pl/pa/teksty/artykuly/17117,POLOWANIE-NA-LUDZI-ZBRODNIA-LUBINSKA-31-SIERPNIA-1982-ROKU.html</ref> During the night of 31 August\u20131 September, the streets were cleared, with all shells and bullets taken for analysis. On 2 September, authorities ordered the repairs of damaged buildings; broken windows were replaced and traces of bullets on the walls were covered with plaster.<ref>https://pamiec.pl/pa/teksty/artykuly/17117,POLOWANIE-NA-LUDZI-ZBRODNIA-LUBINSKA-31-SIERPNIA-1982-ROKU.html</ref> The investigation, despite consistent statements made by witnesses of the massacre, was closed.    \n\nTo avoid further escalation, on 14 November, Lech Wa\u0142\u0119sa was released from custody in a detention camp. Following his release, no major demonstration took place.<ref>https://www.fakt.pl/lech-walesa</ref>\n\n===Law, rules and censorship===\n{{main|Censorship in Communist Poland}}\n[[File:Przepustka-stan wojenny.jpg|thumb|230px|An intercity travel pass, 1981]]\n[[File:Telegr.jpg|thumb|right|230px|A censored telegram, 1982]]\nFrom the very beginning in December 1981, a strict [[curfew]] was imposed from 19:00 (7:00 p.m.) until 6 in the morning.<ref>https://bliskopolski.pl/historia-polski/stan-wojenny/zycie-codzienne/</ref> The time of curfew was later adjusted to 22:00 (10:00 p.m.)\u201306:00.<ref>https://sciaga.pl/tekst/59147-60-stan_wojenny</ref> Night walks or escapades were forbidden and street patrols were commonplace. The [[Military Council of National Salvation|WRON Military Council]] sealed off the country's borders, closed all airports<ref>https://www.rmf24.pl/raporty/raport-rocznica-wprowadzenia-stanu-wojennego/kalendarium-stanu-wojennego</ref> and road access to main cities was restricted. Special permission passes were issued for individuals in extraordinary cases.<ref>https://ipn.gov.pl/ftp/13grudnia81/czytelnia/Stan_wojenny_Teka_edukacyjna.pdf</ref> Telephone lines were disconnected, mail was subjected to renewed [[postal censorship]],<ref>https://dziennikpolski24.pl/cenzura-w-stanie-wojennym/ar/11567123</ref> all independent political organizations were criminalized and lessons in schools and universities temporarily suspended.<ref>https://wiadomosci.dziennik.pl/historia/wydarzenia/artykuly/587159,rocznia-wprowadzenie-stan-wojenny-gen-jaruzelski-13-grudnia-1981.html</ref> \n\nThe government imposed a six-day work week while the mass media, public services, healthcare services, power stations, coal mines, sea ports, railway stations, and most key factories were placed under military management, with employees having to follow military orders or face a [[court martial]]. As part of the crackdown, media and educational institutions underwent \"verification\", a process that tested each employee's attitude towards the regime and to the Solidarity movement; as a result, thousands of journalists, teachers and professors were banned from their professions. [[Military court]]s were established to bypass the normal court system, to imprison those spreading \"false information\".<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/special_report/1999/09/99/iron_curtain/timelines/poland_81.stm 1981: Martial law], [[BBC]]</ref> In an attempt to crush resistance, civilian phone lines were routinely tapped and monitored by government agents.\n\n===Synopsis===\n\nDuring the initial imposition of martial law, several dozen people were killed. Official reports during the crackdown claimed about a dozen fatalities, while a [[Sejm of the Republic of Poland|parliamentary]] commission in the years 1989\u20131991 arrived at a figure of over 90.<ref>[http://wyborcza.pl/1,77062,3787704.html Ofiary stanu wojennego i lat nast\u0119pnych do 1989] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108144638/http://wyborcza.pl/1,77062,3787704.html |date=2014-01-08 }} by Piotr Lipi\u0144ski</ref> Others were also killed and wounded during a massive second wave of demonstrations on [[August 31, 1982 demonstrations in Poland|31 August 1982]].\n\nAt the invitation of Jaruzelski, a delegation of the ruling [[Hungarian Socialist Workers' Party]] visited Poland between 27 and 29 December. The Hungarians shared with their Polish colleagues their experiences on crushing the [[1956 Hungarian revolution|\"counterrevolution\" of 1956]]. Earlier in the autumn of 1981, Polish television had broadcast a special film on the 1956 events in Hungary, showing scenes of rebels hanging security officers etc.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=wI9TUaZZeAMC&pg=PA499&dq=jaruzelski+1981+martial+law#v=onepage&q=jaruzelski%201981%20martial%20law&f=false Google Books]</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:AGAD_Gen._Wojciech_jaruzelski_13_grudnia_1981.png|Jaruzelski in a TV studio announcing the introduction of martial law\nFile:Stan wojenny obwieszczenie.jpg|The proclamation of martial law by the State Council\nFile:Stan wojenny w Polsce - 1981-1983 - 12a.JPG|Units of the [[Milicja_Obywatelska|Citizens' Militia]] and [[ZOMO]] race to disperse crowds of protesters\n</gallery>\n\n==Economic impact==\n[[File:Kartka P3 11-83.jpeg|thumb|Food, alcohol, and cigarettes [[rationing]] card]]\n\nEven after martial law was lifted, a number of restrictions remained in place for several years that drastically reduced the [[civil liberties]] of the citizenry. It also led to severe economic consequences. The ruling [[military dictatorship]] instituted major price rises (dubbed \"economic reforms\"), which resulted in a fall in real wages of 20% or more. The resulting [[economic crisis]] led to the [[rationing]] of most products and materials, including basic foodstuffs.\n\nAs a consequence of economic hardship and political repression, an exodus of Poles saw 700,000 emigrate to the West between 1981 and 1989.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=nypuJ8BARiMC&pg=PA7&lpg=PA7&dq=poland+economy+1980s&source=bl&ots=iR_fCDeyE6&sig=q2hNTHlJPvd7MOfHIhY-lEKmJsc&hl=en&ei=lLEbS6OKG8z_4Abzt4TnAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&ved=0CDIQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=poland%20economy%201980s&f=false Google Books]</ref> \nA number of international flights were even hijacked in attempts to flee the country and its economic problems. Between December 1980 and October 1983, 11 Polish flights were hijacked to [[Berlin Tempelhof Airport]] alone.<ref>[http://www.atlantic-times.com/archive_detail.php?recordID=673 A Symbol Of Allied Solidarity Will Disappear. Berlin - The Atlantic Times] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707184128/http://www.atlantic-times.com/archive_detail.php?recordID=673 |date=2011-07-07 }}</ref>\n\nAround the same time, a group calling themselves the \"Polish Revolutionary Home Army\" seized the Polish Embassy in [[Bern]], [[Switzerland]] on 6 September 1982, taking several diplomats as hostages. However this turned out to be an apparent provocation by the communist Polish secret services aiming to discredit the Solidarity movement.<ref>[http://www.start.umd.edu/start/data/tops/terrorist_organization_profile.asp?id=4206 Terrorist Organization Profile: Polish Revolutionary Home Army]</ref>\n\n==International response==\n{{Expand section|date=July 2009}}\n\nAfter the \"Wujek\" Coal Mine incident in Katowice on 23 December 1981, the [[United States]] imposed [[economic sanctions]] against the [[People's Republic of Poland]]. In 1982 the United States suspended [[most favored nation]] trade status until 1987 and vetoed Poland's application for membership in the [[International Monetary Fund]].<ref>[http://countrystudies.us/poland/92.htm Poland - The United States]</ref>\n\nPope John Paul II wrote a [https://www.nytimes.com/1981/03/29/world/pope-calls-for-justice-and-peace-in-polish-quest-for-a-settlement.html letter] to the Primate of Poland, Stefan Cardinal Wyszynski, in which he called for peace talks between the state and the workers, supporting the Poles' \"undeniable right to resolve their problems by themselves.\"\n\n==Aftermath==\n\n===Ruling of unconstitutionality===\nAfter the [[fall of Communism in Poland]] in 1989, members of a parliamentary commission determined that martial law had been imposed in clear violation of the country's [[constitution]] which had authorized the executive to declare martial law only between parliamentary sessions (at other times the decision was to be taken by the [[Sejm]]). However, the Sejm had been in session at the time when martial law was instituted. In 1992 the Sejm declared the 1981 imposition of martial law to be unlawful and unconstitutional.\n\n===Soviet intervention debate===\n{{further|Soviet reaction to the Polish Crisis of 1980-1981}}\n\nThe instigators of the martial law, such as [[Wojciech Jaruzelski]], argue that the army crackdown rescued Poland from a possibly disastrous [[military intervention]] of the [[Soviet Union]], [[East Germany]], and other [[Warsaw Pact]] countries (similar to the earlier interventions in [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956|Hungary in 1956]] and [[Prague Spring|Czechoslovakia in 1968]]).<ref>[http://www.euronews.net/2008/10/02/jaruzelski-says-martial-law-saved-poland/ Jaruzelski says martial law saved Poland], [[Euronews]], 02/10/08</ref> Public figures who supported the introduction of martial law (including some of the right-wing figures like [[J\u0119drzej Giertych]]) would also refer to that threat.\n\nIn 2009, archive documents hinted that in a conversation Jaruzelski had with [[Viktor Kulikov]], a Soviet military leader, Jaruzelski himself begged for Soviet intervention as his domestic control was deteriorating.<ref>[http://www.newpolandexpress.pl/npe_news_story-1531-jaruzelski_invited_soviet_invasion.php Newpolandexpress.pl] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009161848/http://www.newpolandexpress.pl/npe_news_story-1531-jaruzelski_invited_soviet_invasion.php |date=2011-10-09 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.rferl.org/content/Interview_Polands_Jaruzelski_Again_Denies_Seeking_Soviet_Intervention_Against_Solidarity/1902431.html Rferl.org]</ref> Jaruzelski responded by claiming the document was 'just another falsification'.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n==Declaration script==\nLed by [[General of the Army]] [[Wojciech Jaruzelski]], the [[Military Council of National Salvation]] (''Wojskowa Rada Ocalenia Narodowego'', WRON) usurped for itself powers reserved for wartime, hence the name. The plan was presented to the government of the [[Soviet Union]] before the declaration in March 1981.\n\nAppearing on Polish television at 6:00 a.m. on 13 December 1981, General Jaruzelski said:<ref>The original is available at [http://www.konflikty.pl/a,395,Czasy_najnowsze,Przemowienie_gen._Jaruzelskiego.html Konflikty.pl] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121112060937/http://www.konflikty.pl/a,395,Czasy_najnowsze,Przemowienie_gen._Jaruzelskiego.html |date=2012-11-12 }}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>Today I address myself to you as a soldier and as the head of the Polish government. I address you concerning extraordinarily important questions. Our homeland is at the edge of an abyss. The achievements of many generations and the Polish home that has been built up from the dust are about to turn into ruins. State structures are ceasing to function. Each day delivers new blows to the waning economy./.../<br>The atmosphere of conflicts, misunderstanding, hatred causes moral degradation, surpasses the limits of toleration. Strikes, the readiness to strike, actions of protest have become a norm of life. Even school youth are being drawn into this. Yesterday evening, many public buildings remained seized. The cries are voiced to physical reprisals with the 'reds', with people who have different opinions. <br>The cases of terror, threats and moral vendetta, of even direct violence are on the rise. A wave of impudent crimes, robberies and burglaries is running across the country. The underground business sharks' fortunes, already reaching millions, are growing. Chaos and demoralization have reached the magnitude of a catastrophe. People have reached the limit of psychological toleration. Many people are struck by despair. Not only days, but hours as well are bringing forth the all-national disaster./.../<br>Citizens!<br>The load of responsibility that falls on me on this dramatic moment in the Polish history is huge. It is my duty to take this responsibility - concerning the future of Poland, that my generation fought for on all the fronts of the war and for which they sacrificed the best years of their life. I declare, that today the Military Council of National Salvation has been formed. In accordance with the Constitution, the State Council has imposed martial law all over the country. I wish that everyone understood the motives of our actions. A military coup, military dictatorship is not our goal./.../<br> In longer perspective, none of Poland's problems can be solved with the use of violence. The Military Council of National Salvation does not replace constitutional organs of power. Its only purpose is to keep the legal balance of the country, to create guarantees that give a chance to restore order and discipline. This is the ultimate way to bring the country out of the crisis, to save the country from collapse./.../<br>I appeal to all the citizens. A time of heavy trials has arrived. And we have to stand those in order to prove that we are worthy of Poland.<br>Before all the Polish people and the whole world I would like to repeat the immortal words: <br>\n::'''''[[Poland Is Not Yet Lost|Poland has not yet perished, so long as we still live]]!'''''</blockquote>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cold War]]\n* [[Able Archer 83]]\n* [[Fighting Solidarity]]\n* [[Pacification of Wujek]]\n* [[Telephone tapping in the Eastern Bloc]]\n* [[Soviet reaction to the Polish Crisis of 1980-1981]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Leopold Labedz, ''Poland Under Jaruzelski: A Comprehensive Sourcebook on Poland During and After Martial Law''\n* George Sanford, ''Military Rule in Poland: The Rebuilding of Communist Power, 1981\u20131983''\n{{Portal|Poland|History|Communism|War|1980s}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Martial law in Poland}}\n* [http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB211/index.htm Solidarity and Martial Law in Poland: 25 Years Later], [[National Security Archive]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110112170636/http://www.onwar.com/aced/chrono/c1900s/yr80/fpoland1981.htm Martial Law in Poland 1981-1983]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080105033603/http://www.tenetour.com/history9.php Martial Law in Poland]\n* [http://www.videofact.com/english/stanwoj2.htm Martial Law in Poland 1981]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dKhITm9-5TU Video of Jaruzelski declaring martial law], [[Telewizja Polska|TVP]]/[[YouTube]]\n* [http://www.pbase.com/zyziza/martial_law_in_poland Photo Gallery by zyziza at pbase.com]\n\n{{History of the People's Republic of Poland}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martial Law In Poland}}\n[[Category:1980s coups d'\u00e9tat and coup attempts]]\n[[Category:1981 in Poland]]\n[[Category:1981 in politics]]\n[[Category:1982 in Poland]]\n[[Category:1982 in politics]]\n[[Category:1983 in Poland]]\n[[Category:1983 in politics]]\n[[Category:Anti-communism in Poland]]\n[[Category:Communism in Poland]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1981]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1982]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1983]]\n[[Category:Emergency laws]]\n[[Category:Martial law|Poland]]\n[[Category:Military coups in Poland]]\n[[Category:Military dictatorships|Poland]]\n[[Category:Poland\u2013Soviet Union relations]]\n[[Category:Solidarity (Polish trade union)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Coup d'\u00e9tat}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Martial law in Poland\n| place       = {{flagicon|Poland}} [[Poland]]\n| partof      = the [[Soviet reaction to the Polish crisis of 1980\u20131981]]\n| combatant1  = {{flagicon|Polish People's Republic}} [[Polish People's Republic]]\n* [[Polish People's Army]]\n* [[Milicja_Obywatelska|Citizens' Militia (MO)]]\n* [[ZOMO]]\n* [[S\u0142u\u017cba Bezpiecze\u0144stwa|Secret Service (SB)]]\n----\n'''Supported by:''' \n{{flag|Soviet Union}} ({{small|Intelligence support and military equipment}})\n| combatant2  = {{flagicon image|}} [[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarity Movement]]\n* [[Fighting Solidarity]] <br><small>(from 1982)</small>\n* Protesters\n----\n'''Supported by:''' \n{{flag|United States}} ({{small|Financial support}})\n| casualties1 = Unknown\n| casualties2 = \n*91 killed\n*Thousands arrested\n| commander1  = [[Wojciech Jaruzelski]] \n* [[Czes\u0142aw Kiszczak]]\n| commander2  = [[Lech Wa\u0142\u0119sa]]\n*[[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Frasyniuk]]\n| image       = File:T-55A Martial law Poland.jpg\n| image_size  = 280px\n| caption     = A column of Polish [[T-55]] tanks enters the town of [[Zb\u0105szy\u0144]] while moving east towards the city of [[Pozna\u0144]], 13 December 1981\n| date        = 13 December 1981 \u2013 22 July 1983\n({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=12|day1=13|year1=1981|month2=07|day2=22|year2=1983}})\n| result      = Decisive Polish government victory\n*Crackdown on opposition\n*Protests suppressed \n*Deepened economic crisis\n*Continued resistance until 1989\n| strength1   ='''Initial strength''':<ref>https://culture.pl/en/article/the-day-poland-stood-still-memories-from-the-introduction-of-martial-law</ref>\n*80,000 soldiers\n*30,000 policemen\n*1,750 tanks\n*1,900 combat vehicles\n*9,000 cars\n| strength2   = ~ 10 million (1981)\n}}\n\n'''Martial law in Poland''' ({{lang-pl|Stan wojenny w Polsce}}) refers to the period between 13 December 1981 and 22 July 1983, when the [[authoritarian]] [[communist government]] of the [[Polish People's Republic]] drastically restricted normal life by introducing [[martial law]] and a [[military junta]] in an attempt to throttle political opposition, in particular the [[Solidarity Movement]]. Thousands of opposition activists were [[Internment|imprisoned]] without charge and as many as 91 killed.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/6175517.stm Poland marks communist crackdown], [[BBC News]], 13 December 2006</ref> Although martial law was lifted in 1983, many of the [[political prisoner]]s were not released until a general [[amnesty]] in 1986.\n\nSince the 1970s, communist Poland was in a deep [[economic recession]]. The First Secretary [[Edward Gierek]] made large incessant loans from western creditors to achieve a better economic output that instead resulted in a domestic crisis. Basic goods were being heavily [[Rationing|rationed]] which acted as a stimuli for the establishment of a first anti-communist [[trade union]] in the [[Eastern Bloc]], known as Solidarity, in 1980. Gierek, who permitted the trade union to appear per the [[Gda\u0144sk Agreement]], was dismissed from his post less than a month later under pressure from the USSR and confined to [[house arrest]]. Poland's already somewhat liberal policies concerning the opposition were worrisome for hardliners in the [[Soviet Union]], who feared that the Poles may overthrow communism and ally themselves with the [[Western Bloc]]. The Soviets were particularly uneasy as the departure of Eastern Bloc's most populous nation from [[Comecon]] would trigger further financial and economic problems that would bring an end to communist rule in Central-Eastern Europe. After a series of strikes and demonstrations by employees of chief industrial regions, Poland was directly heading towards bankruptcy. \n\nThe [[Military Council of National Salvation]] was formed by the new First Secretary of the Polish United Workers' Party, General [[Wojciech Jaruzelski]], who was determined to put an end to the demonstrations and crush the opposition by force if necessary. There is speculation whether Jaruzelski instigated martial law to prevent bloodshed if the Soviets and other [[Warsaw Pact]] countries were to enter Poland under the mutual assistance treaty, like in the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956]] and the [[invasion of Czechoslovakia in 1968]]. On 13 December 1981, Jaruzelski announced the introduction of martial law in a televised speech addressed to the entire nation. The Polish People's Army, [[Citizen's Militia]] (MO), [[ZOMO]] special units and tanks rolled onto the streets to scare off demonstrators, begin regular patrols and maintain [[curfew]]. Intercity travelling was forbidden unless a permit was granted by the authorities, food shortages intensified and censorship was placed on all media and [[Mail|post]]. The [[S\u0142u\u017cba Bezpiecze\u0144stwa|secret services (SB)]] [[wiretapped]] phones in public booths and state institutions. \n\nOn 16 December, pro-Solidarity miners organized a strike against the declaration of the martial law at the [[Wujek Coal Mine]] in the industrial city of [[Katowice]]. The ZOMO squads, nicknamed \"Communist [[Gestapo]]\" by the opposition, brutally [[Pacification of Wujek|pacified Wujek]], which resulted in the deaths of 9 miners. All other [[1982 demonstrations in Poland|demonstrations across Poland]] were met with armed force of the services, which utilized [[water cannons]], [[tear gas]], [[Baton (law enforcement)|batons]], truncheons and clubs to disperse crowds and beat protesters. Thousands were detained and some were tortured in state prisons. On 31 August 1982, in the copper-mining town of [[Lubin]], 3 people were mortally wounded by ZOMO. Until the end of the martial law on 22 July 1983, approximately 91 people were killed, though this figure varies and is still debated among historians.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/6175517.stm Poland marks communist crackdown], [[BBC News]], 13 December 2006</ref>\n\n==Prelude==\n{{main|History of Poland (1945\u20131989)}}\n===Reforms of Edward Gierek (1970-1975)===\n[[File:Photograph of President Gerald R. Ford, First Secretary Edward Gierek of Poland, and Mrs. Stanislawa Gierek Waving from the Blue Room Balcony during a State Arrival Ceremony - NARA - 7462054.jpg|thumb|right|230px|Gierek in the [[White House]] with President [[Gerald Ford]], 1974]]\nWhen [[Edward Gierek]] succeeded [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Gomu\u0142ka|Gomu\u0142ka]] as the head of state in 1970, he took decisive measures to boost economic growth and develop modern infrastructure.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=WGGaAAAAIAAJ&q=reformy+gierka+nowoczesne&dq=reformy+gierka+nowoczesne&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiHgZO8j97oAhW7xjgGHU_gAJEQ6AEIKzAA</ref> Gierek, a more [[Liberalism|liberal]] figure than his predecessor, was determined to make [[Polish People's Republic|Poland]] the wealthiest and most economically significant communist country of the [[Eastern Bloc]].<ref>https://nowahistoria.interia.pl/prl/news-edward-gierek-i-jego-koncepcja-drugiej-polski,nId,2354535,nPack,3</ref> However, these ideas prompted resistance from hardline communist leadership as the reform would effectively abandon the fundamental principles of a [[Planned economy|centrally planned]] [[Marxism|Marxist]] economy. The grip and emphasis on state-owned enterprises and state-controlled prices or trade was eventually loosened. Small private businesses began to appear and Poland recorded temporary growth in [[GDP]] and an improvement in living conditions.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=xCFDAQAAIAAJ&q=gierek+jako%C5%9B%C4%87&dq=gierek+jako%C5%9B%C4%87&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwij7ujpj97oAhXbwzgGHe2mAPoQ6AEIZTAG</ref><ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=LSSauLSn9YMC&pg=PA42&lpg=PA42&dq=gierek+marks&source=bl&ots=_2quNkfJ1B&sig=ACfU3U12haOc3udIsqtB8YB61ITcDtL61w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjzh9PQkN7oAhX54zgGHXsmBV0Q6AEwCnoECAsQKw#v=onepage&q=gierek%20marks&f=false</ref>\n\nGierek maintained close ties with the [[United States]], which he subsequently used for diplomatic and economic purposes.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=LSSauLSn9YMC&pg=PA42&lpg=PA42&dq=gierek+marks&source=bl&ots=_2quNkfJ1B&sig=ACfU3U12haOc3udIsqtB8YB61ITcDtL61w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjzh9PQkN7oAhX54zgGHXsmBV0Q6AEwCnoECAsQKw#v=onepage&q=gierek%20marks&f=false</ref> In order to continue with the reforms, large sums of money were borrowed from [[creditors]] in the [[Western Bloc]].<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=Vae1AAAAIAAJ&q=gierek+po%C5%BCyczki&dq=gierek+po%C5%BCyczki&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiDvoKVkd7oAhV0zTgGHVzLAW8Q6AEIcTAH</ref> These sequential and uninterrupted loans were primarily targeted at establishing heavy industry, mines or manufacturing facilities that would produce goods for [[export]].<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=Vae1AAAAIAAJ&q=gierek+po%C5%BCyczki&dq=gierek+po%C5%BCyczki&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiDvoKVkd7oAhV0zTgGHVzLAW8Q6AEIcTAH</ref><ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=POkSAQAAMAAJ&q=gierek+d%C5%82ug+przemysl+%C5%9Bl%C4%85sk&dq=gierek+d%C5%82ug+przemysl+%C5%9Bl%C4%85sk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjfspz0kd7oAhXewzgGHU-QApwQ6AEIazAH</ref> The projected income from the exports would then be used to pay off the [[debt]]. Apart from financing the economic sector, the money was spent on [[social housing]] and on expanding road connections, for example the first fully operational [[highway]] linking Warsaw with industrial [[Silesia]] was opened for traffic in 1976.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=vtcsAAAAMAAJ&q=gierek+warszawa+centralna+gierk%C3%B3wka&dq=gierek+warszawa+centralna+gierk%C3%B3wka&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjbiJGQkt7oAhWOwzgGHaLGBjEQ6AEIKzAA</ref> Furthermore, over 1.8 million [[plattenbau]] flats were constructed to house the growing population. Agricultural output rose by nearly 22% between 1971 and 1975, and industrial production by 10.5% annually.<ref>https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/CIA-RDP86T00608R000500200020-4.pdf</ref><ref>file:///C:/Users/User/Downloads/Harmonijny_rozwoj_czy_droga_ku_p.pdf</ref> Gierek also initiated the construction of [[Warszawa Centralna]], Europe's most modern railway station at the time.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=35o8AQAAIAAJ&q=gierek+warszawa+dworzec&dq=gierek+warszawa+dworzec&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjk1q2zkt7oAhXuzDgGHdisDfEQ6AEITjAE</ref><ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=0rk9DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT149&dq=warszawa+centralna+dworzec+w+europie&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwirx7_Gkt7oAhXOzTgGHQ9vDTEQ6AEIRTAD#v=onepage&q=warszawa%20centralna%20dworzec%20w%20europie&f=false</ref><ref>https://www.mwkz.pl/archiwum-aktualnosci-lista/1308-dworzec-centralny-wpisany-do-rejestru-zabytkow</ref><ref>https://tvn24.pl/tvnwarszawa/najnowsze/miliardy-na-budowe-brtak-powstawal-dworzec-centralny-187645</ref>\n\n===Crisis; debt, rationing and shortages (1976-1981)===\n[[File:Kartka cukier 1kg 07-76.jpg|thumb|left|140px|A ration card for sugar, 1976]]\nAs expenditures increased and debts accumulated, the West would no longer grant Poland loans. Moreover, the [[1973 oil crisis|1973]], [[June 1976 protests]] and [[1979 oil crisis|1979 oil crises]] affected the fragile economy. Due to previous GDP growth, higher income and expanded industries, the demand for certain goods and [[Consumption (economics)|consumption]] surged.<ref>https://www.wprost.pl/354447/polska-splacila-dlug-gierka-po-40-latach.html</ref><ref>https://www.forbes.pl/przywodztwo/wyscig-z-dlugiem-jak-ekipa-edward-gierka-zadluzyla-polske/z6vv26r</ref> New factories and state enterprises required imported fuel, materials and a workforce to operate production lines.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=Vae1AAAAIAAJ&q=gierek+d%C5%82ug+import&dq=gierek+d%C5%82ug+import&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjq0f7mlN7oAhVFxzgGHX2BCzcQ6AEINDAB</ref> Soon, the country started exporting locally-produced stock designated for the Polish populace, thus resulting in widespread [[shortages]].<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=9pbFBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA33&dq=gierek+d%C5%82ug+kartki+braki&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiw7OObld7oAhWN4zgGHWqMDb0Q6AEIKzAA#v=onepage&q=gierek%20d%C5%82ug%20kartki%20braki&f=false</ref> Because the remaining assets were directed at production, exports and debt repayment, the state also reduced imports to minimize expenses. \n\nIn 1976, the communist government introduced [[ration cards]] for sugar.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=JrZEAQAAIAAJ&q=gierek+d%C5%82ug+kartki+braki&dq=gierek+d%C5%82ug+kartki+braki&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiw7OObld7oAhWN4zgGHWqMDb0Q6AEIPTAC</ref> Meat, processed food and dairy followed.<ref>http://info.wyborcza.biz/szukaj/gospodarka/kwoty+cukru</ref> Confectionery, [[cocoa bean|cocoa]], coffee, rice, [[tobacco]] and other goods not produced in Poland were so heavily rationed that they were almost permanently unavailable.<ref>https://www.polskieradio.pl/39/156/Artykul/320244,Zycie-na-kartki</ref><ref>http://info.wyborcza.biz/szukaj/gospodarka/kwoty+cukru</ref> Due to the constant lack of tobacco, ordinary cigarettes became a form of new currency on the [[black market]].<ref>http://www.ippt.pan.pl/Repository/zycie_%20w_ciekawych_czasach_15_10_2012.pdf</ref> The living standards began to sharply decline; the supply of imported goods was kept to a low minimum and the county was forced to export everything it could, including coal necessary for basic heating and power plants. [[Power outage]]s were commonplace.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=ukkpAQAAIAAJ&q=gierek+wylaczenie+pr%C4%85du&dq=gierek+wylaczenie+pr%C4%85du&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjXqpe7l97oAhW3zzgGHSzyDJEQ6AEIKDAA</ref> By 1980, the debt accounted to over US$23 billion, then almost half of Poland's [[nominal GDP]].<ref>https://www.tygodnikprzeglad.pl/pawel-bozyk-zaklamywanie-prawdy-o-dlugach-gierka/</ref>        \n\n[[File:Jimmy Carter and Edward Gierek First Secretary of Poland - NARA - 177308.tif|thumb|right|230px|[[Edward Gierek]] (right) with President [[Jimmy Carter]] (left) during his state visit to Warsaw, 1977. The loans and Solidarity were among the chief topics discussed]]\n\nAt the same time, the newly-founded [[Solidarity movement]] encouraged farmers to refrain from selling agricultural products (wheat, grain, fruit and others) to the state as a sign of protest. The actual lack of goods on the market and in stores was caused by the fact that production stopped due to the strikes organized by Solidarity.<ref>http://muzhp.pl/pl/c/971/gierek-siedzial-na-wulkanie-ktory-w-koncu-eksplodowal</ref> In 1980, the national income fell by 6% compared to previous year, and in 1981 by 12%.<ref>https://wiadomosci.onet.pl/kiosk/polska-gierka/myj3y</ref> The number of exports declined by 4.2%. Mismanagement and wastefulness were abundant.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=ZQ9NDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT182&lpg=PT182&dq=gierek+marnotrawstwo&source=bl&ots=XheuY7_TIT&sig=ACfU3U0LWAGCKo33VnDTiTE5H_dTufhr5Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjupceqmd7oAhVqzjgGHaZ3ANYQ6AEwDXoECAwQKw#v=onepage&q=gierek%20marnotrawstwo&f=false</ref> \n\nOn 6 September 1980, Gierek was dismissed from his office, expelled from the Polish United Workers' Party (possibly under the pressure from the Soviet Union) and falsely charged with [[corruption]].<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=pdAbAQAAMAAJ&q=gierek+6+wrze%C5%9Bnia+1980&dq=gierek+6+wrze%C5%9Bnia+1980&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjO2sH0md7oAhWmxDgGHRovD0cQ6AEIZDAG</ref><ref>file:///C:/Users/User/Downloads/Dyskusja-wokol-ksiazki-Rozliczenia-z-ekipa-Gierka-19801984-Warszawa-6-wrzesnia-2.pdf</ref> A year later, on 10 September 1981, the Soviet authorities informed the Polish government that in connection with the prevailing situation in Poland the USSR would cut oil supply to Poland by 64% and gas by 47%.<ref>Andrzej Krajewski, \u201eGazowa p\u0119tla\u201d, Dziennik Gazeta Prawna nr 111/2016.</ref> The import of [[diesel fuel|diesel]] from the Soviet Union was terminated immediately.<ref>Andrzej Krajewski, \u201eGazowa p\u0119tla\u201d, Dziennik Gazeta Prawna nr 111/2016.</ref> This action was intended to force the Polish communist authorities to suppress the demonstrations and dissolve Solidarity.<ref>https://wiadomosci.onet.pl/nszz</ref> The situation was already dire and gradually worsened, which only fueled anti-communist sentiment. A [[civil war]] was hanging by a thread.<ref>https://www.polskieradio24.pl/80/1492/Artykul/www.polskieradio.pl/13/53/Artykul/254368</ref>\n\nIn 1981, Poland notified [[Club de Paris]] (a group of Western-European central banks) about its [[insolvency]], which caught the attention of the entire world.<ref>http://www.clubdeparis.org/en/traitements/poland-27-04-1981/en</ref>\n\n==Introduction, restrictions, patrols==\n===Secret preparations and provocation===\n[[File:Wojciech Jaruzelski.jpg|thumb|left|150px|General [[Wojciech Jaruzelski|Jaruzelski]] was determined to suppress any opposition along with the [[Solidarity Movement]]]]\nAfter the short tenure of [[Stanis\u0142aw Kania]], General and Minister of Defence [[Wojciech Jaruzelski]] was chosen as the new First Secretary. Before assuming office, Jaruzelski ordered the Polish General Staff to update plans for a nationwide martial law on 22 October 1980.<ref>''From Solidarity to Martial Law: The Polish Crisis of 1980\u20131981: A Documentary History'' by Andrzej Paczkowski, Malcolm Byrne. Central European University Press, Budapest 2007. p. xxxiii</ref> In November 1980, the [[Ministry of Internal Affairs (Poland)|Ministry of Internal Affairs]] planned to potentially facilitate thousands of oppositionists in state prisons and places of internment.<ref>https://tvn24.pl/polska/13-grudnia-2019-38-rocznica-wprowadzenia-stanu-wojennego-ra992894-2586819</ref> \n\nOn 5 December 1980, Kania spoke of the preparations relating to martial law at the [[Warsaw Pact|Warsaw Pact Summit]] in [[Moscow]].<ref>https://dzieje.pl/aktualnosci/koniec-epoki-brezniewa</ref><ref>https://www.polityka.pl/tygodnikpolityka/historia/1533463,1,stanislaw-kania---przeciwnik-stanu-wojennego.read</ref> He presented his own view of how to weaken Solidarity and insisted that a \"psychological-operational method\" would be most appropriate to prevent violence.<ref>https://przystanekhistoria.pl/pa2/teksty/57519,Czemu-stan-wojenny-wprowadzono-dopiero-w-nocy-z-12-na-13-grudnia-1981-r.html</ref> This method entailed strong [[propaganda]]<ref>https://przystanekhistoria.pl/pa2/teksty/57519,Czemu-stan-wojenny-wprowadzono-dopiero-w-nocy-z-12-na-13-grudnia-1981-r.html</ref> against the movement and deploying [[S\u0142u\u017cba Bezpiecze\u0144stwa|Secret Services (SB)]] to go undercover and infiltrate Solidarity headquarters in the hope of creating internal conflicts within the opposition. General Jaruzelski was not fully satisfied with the plan, and, in case of failure, already planned radical actions involving the army. Stanis\u0142aw Kania warned [[Brezhnev]] that an armed intervention from the Soviet side to aid Jaruzelski would be met \"with a violent reaction, or even with a national uprising\"<ref>https://wyborcza.pl/1,76842,6976876,Bedziecie_tu_mieli_powstanie__towarzyszu_Brezniew.html</ref> that would shake the politics of the Eastern Bloc.<ref>https://wyborcza.pl/1,76842,6976876,Bedziecie_tu_mieli_powstanie__towarzyszu_Brezniew.html</ref>     \n\n[[Zbigniew Brzezinski]], chief security advisor to US President [[Jimmy Carter]], stated that if the Soviet Union would undertake an armed intervention in Poland, the US would strike back in a [[riposte]] manner.<ref>https://dziennikzwiazkowy.com/historia-2/zbigniew-brzezinski-i-jego-strategia-wygrania-zimnej-wojny/</ref>  According to historian and publicist [[Paul Kengor]], the then US President [[Ronald Reagan]] considered sending American troops to Poland to scare off the Soviets.<ref>https://wyborcza.pl/1,75399,3976852.html</ref> This claim was not supported by Brzezinski nor by [[Richard Pipes]] from [[Harvard University]].<ref>https://wyborcza.pl/1,75399,3976852.html</ref> Kengor then elaborated that Reagan eventually abandoned the plan after he was convinced by his own advisors that the US army stationed across Europe is less capable and much weaker than the Soviet forces.<ref>https://wyborcza.pl/1,75399,3976852.html</ref> The United States eventually striked back with economic sanctions against Poland and the USSR.<ref>https://dziennikzwiazkowy.com/historia-2/zbigniew-brzezinski-i-jego-strategia-wygrania-zimnej-wojny/</ref> \n\n[[File:WieczorWroclawia20marca1981.jpg|thumb|right|240px|A censored regional newspaper that reported about the [[Bydgoszcz events]], in which the [[Milicja Obywatelska|Militia]] abused Solidarity members. The censorship was to prevent the slander of state services]] \n\nIn February 1981, the [[Ministry of National Defence (Poland)|Ministry of National Defence]] and Ministry of the Internal Affairs carried out a training scenario, the purpose of which was to explore how martial law will be introduced.<ref>https://pamiec.pl/pa/kalendarium-1/13389,16-lutego-1981-roku-w-Warszawie-przeprowadzono-wspolna-gre-sztabowa-MON-i-MSW-po.html</ref> The ministries agreed that martial law should be preceded by appropriate propaganda calling for its support, and the decision itself should be based on a pretext that it would bring peace and stability for the society.<ref>file:///C:/Users/User/Downloads/Ruzikowski_Stan_wojenny_w_Warszawie.pdf</ref> It was also highlighted that martial law must occur before the fully mobilized [[Fighting Solidarity]] and its allies organize a [[general strike]] that would paralyze the entire country.<ref>file:///C:/Users/User/Downloads/Ruzikowski_Stan_wojenny_w_Warszawie.pdf</ref> By March, the situation escalated after the [[Bydgoszcz events]], in which local Solidarity delegates invited for a [[National Council (Poland)|Regional National Council]] meeting in [[Bydgoszcz]] to discuss potential strikes were beaten and abused by the [[Citizens' Militia]] (MO).<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=93eUER87BmsC&pg=PA119&dq=bydgoszcz+1981&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiKnuPQo97oAhXuzzgGHdvZAzwQ6AEIMTAB#v=onepage&q=bydgoszcz%201981&f=false</ref> The event, which was to feature in newspapers as a [[provocation (legal)|provocation]], was concealed by [[censors]]. On 27 March, Solidarity organized a warning strike directed at the government, but, on 30 March, [[Lech Wa\u0142\u0119sa]] met with [[Mieczys\u0142aw Rakowski]] and a compromise was achieved.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=-FCyCDv9QswC&pg=PA43&dq=bydgoszcz+1981+rakowski+walesa&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjupIbgo97oAhUExTgGHTZcDOwQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=bydgoszcz%201981%20rakowski%20walesa&f=false</ref> The general strike was called off and the situation stabilized for a short period.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=-FCyCDv9QswC&pg=PA43&dq=bydgoszcz+1981+rakowski+walesa&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjupIbgo97oAhUExTgGHTZcDOwQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=bydgoszcz%201981%20rakowski%20walesa&f=false</ref>\n\nIn July, the Soviets increased their military presence in the military base at [[Borne Sulinowo]], where the [[Red Army]] stationed per [[Warsaw Pact]] agreement as in all other [[Eastern Bloc]] countries.<ref name=\"Ryszard Kukli\u0144ski. \u017bycie \u015bci\u015ble tajne\">{{cite book |surname=Benjamin Weiser |title=Ryszard Kukli\u0144ski. \u017bycie \u015bci\u015ble tajne |publisher=\u015awiat Ksi\u0105\u017cki |location=Warszawa |year=2005 |isbn = 83-7391-673-3}}</ref>  Without notifying the Polish authorities, the Soviets unexpectedly sent over 600 tanks to Borne Sulinowo. A month later, commander-in-chief of the Warsaw Pact, [[Viktor Kulikov]], requested that Soviet military advisors are to be placed in the Polish General Staff and assigned to nearly all Polish regiments. It is suspected that Kulikov, acting on behalf of the Soviet Union, was tasked with sending undercover [[KGB]] agents to monitor the situation in Poland from the Polish military's perspective. His request, however, was immediately denied by the Polish government.<ref name=\"Ryszard Kukli\u0144ski. \u017bycie \u015bci\u015ble tajne\">{{cite book |surname=Benjamin Weiser |title=Ryszard Kukli\u0144ski. \u017bycie \u015bci\u015ble tajne |publisher=\u015awiat Ksi\u0105\u017cki |location=Warszawa |year=2005 |isbn = 83-7391-673-3}}</ref> \n\nOver 25,000 posters announcing martial law were secretly printed in the USSR, transported to Poland by airplane and hidden in the large building housing the Ministry of Internal Affairs.<ref>[[Ryszard Terlecki]]: ''Miecz i tarcza komunizmu. Historia aparatu bezpiecze\u0144stwa w Polsce 1944-1990'', Krak\u00f3w 2007, p. 270\u2013271.</ref> The full extent of the actions undertaken by Jaruzelski to instigate martial law was not known by even some of the highest notables in the Central Committee of the [[Polish United Workers' Party]] or the Polish [[Sejm]].<ref>file:///C:/Users/User/Downloads/akt-oskarzenia-S-101-04-Zk_2%20(1).pdf</ref>\n\n===12-13 December 1981; Operations Fir and Azalea=== \n[[File:AGAD Posiedzenie Wojskowej Rady Ocalenia Narodowego.png|thumb|left|230px|The [[Military Council of National Salvation]] (WRON), which was founded on 13 December and presided over the [[military junta]]. Its Polish [[abbreviation]] \"WRONa\" means a [[crow]] bird, and members of the council were known to the opposition as evil \"Crows\"]] \nOn 12 December 1981, shortly before [[midnight]], the [[Polish Council of State]] gathered in Warsaw's [[Belweder Palace]] and approved nationwide martial law. Simultaneously, the [[Military Council of National Salvation]] (WRON - ''Wrona'' is translated as \"Crow\") was founded and its members were high-ranking generals or military officers in the [[Polish People's Army]], who were in charge of the [[military junta]]. The generals and officers later became known to the public as evil \"[[Crows]]\", in relation to the Polish name of the council. \n\nAt precisely 00:00 (12:00 a.m.), the [[ZOMO|Motorized Reserves of the Citizens' Militia]] (ZOMO) began \"Akcja Jod\u0142a\" (English: Operation [[Fir]]) and arrested the first members of Solidarity who were at close reach.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=DC9BAQAAIAAJ&q=12,9+tysiecy+miejsc+internowania+stan+wojenny&dq=12,9+tysiecy+miejsc+internowania+stan+wojenny&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj0mfrnm97oAhUTWX0KHYXQDcEQ6AEIKzAA</ref><ref>https://ipn.gov.pl/pl/aktualnosci/37976,Grzegorz-Majchrzak-Stan-wojenny-kryptonim-Jodla.html</ref> They were then placed in previously-prepared detention facilities.<ref>https://ipn.gov.pl/pl/aktualnosci/37976,Grzegorz-Majchrzak-Stan-wojenny-kryptonim-Jodla.html</ref> In total, between 70,000 and 80,000 soldiers of the People's Army and 30,000 functionaries of the Ministry of Internal Affairs (including SB, ZOMO and the Militia) were deployed for action. Around 1,750 tanks, 1,900 armoured combat vehicles, 500 militarized transport units, 9,000 cars and several [[helicopter]] [[squadron]]s were in service.<ref>''From Solidarity to Martial Law: The Polish Crisis of 1980\u20131981: A Documentary History'' by Andrzej Paczkowski, Malcolm Byrne. Central European University Press, Budapest 2007. p. xxxiii</ref><ref>https://culture.pl/en/article/the-day-poland-stood-still-memories-from-the-introduction-of-martial-law</ref><ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=Uqm1AAAAIAAJ&q=prl+stan+wojenny+1900&dq=prl+stan+wojenny+1900&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjI463A9NroAhVezjgGHVwSC34Q6AEIKDAA</ref> 25% of all units concentrated in the capital, Warsaw, or in surrounding localities.\n\nPreceding Jod\u0142a was \"Akcja Azalia\" (English: Operation [[Azalea]]), which began at around 22:30 (10:30 p.m.) on 12 December.<ref>https://www.sejm.gov.pl/Sejm9.nsf/wypowiedz.xsp?posiedzenie=2&dzien=1&wyp=190&symbol=RWYSTAPIENIA_WYP&id=351</ref><ref>https://bliskopolski.pl/leksykon/akcja-azalia/</ref> Per Azalea, the SB secret services, paramilitary troops, the Militia, ZOMO and [[Border Protection Troops]] stormed 451 [[telephone exchange|telecommunications exchange facilities]] and cut telephone lines to allegedly prevent the spread of misinformation.<ref>https://bliskopolski.pl/leksykon/akcja-azalia/</ref> However, the operation's true purpose was preventing Solidarity from contacting its branches in other cities to mobilize protesters. Radio and television stations were also besieged.<ref>https://www.sejm.gov.pl/Sejm9.nsf/wypowiedz.xsp?posiedzenie=2&dzien=1&wyp=190&symbol=RWYSTAPIENIA_WYP&id=351</ref> Any volunteers wishing to assist in the arrests were drafted into [[ORMO]].  \n\nThe [[Polskie Radio|Polish Radio]] informed about martial law being imposed at a 06:00 (6:00 a.m.) audition, and transmitted the speech made by General Jaruzelski.<ref name=\"polskieradio\">{{Cite |url = http://www.polskieradio.pl/39/156/Artykul/1318087,33-lata-temu-wprowadzono-w-Polsce-stan-wojenny |title = 33 lata temu wprowadzono w Polsce stan wojenny |date = 2014-12-13 |page = polskieradio.pl }}</ref> [[Telewizja Polska]] network and its chief news program ''[[Dziennik Telewizyjny|Dziennik]]'' (English: Journal) aired the speech in a slightly modified version.<ref name=\"Ferfecki\">{{Cite |url = http://www.tvp.info/1166664/nieznana-wersja-przemowienia-gen-jaruzelskiego |title = Nieznana wersja przem\u00f3wienia gen. Jaruzelskiego |author = Wiktor Ferfecki, Joanna Idziak |date = 2009-12-13 |page = tvp.info }}</ref> The [[Martial law in Poland#Declaration script|declaration]] was watched by millions of Polish citizens despite the early hour.\n\n===16 December 1981; Wujek Coal Mine===\n{{main|Pacification of Wujek|Wujek Coal Mine}}\n\n[[File:Stan wojenny w Polsce - 1981-1983 - 08.JPG|thumb|right|230px|[[ZOMO]] squads with [[truncheons|police batons]] preparing to disperse and beat protesters. The [[sarcasm|sarcastic]] caption reads \"outstretched hands of understanding\" or \"outstretched hands for agreement\", with batons ironically symbolizing hands]]\n\nThree days after restrictions were imposed, miners at the [[Wujek Coal Mine]] in the industrial city of [[Katowice]] began striking against the declaration of martial law by General Jaruzelski.<ref>https://ipn.gov.pl/pl/aktualnosci/38063,Pacyfikacja-kopalni-Wujek-najwieksza-zbrodnia-stanu-wojennego.html</ref> Most of the miners and workers at Wujek were allied with the Solidarity Movement, with its leaders boycotting the state industries. Furthermore, [[coal]] was a precious fuel source that was used for generating electricity and heat, but also a major export material.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=wpzeOwI67BIC&q=wujek+kopalnia+stan+wojenny+w%C4%99giel&dq=wujek+kopalnia+stan+wojenny+w%C4%99giel&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjk45mTp97oAhWSF3IKHVlSAFAQ6AEIOTAC</ref> By selling and exporting coal, the communist government obtained enough money to gradually pay off the outstanding debt.<ref>https://books.google.com.au/books?id=wpzeOwI67BIC&q=wujek+kopalnia+stan+wojenny+w%C4%99giel&dq=wujek+kopalnia+stan+wojenny+w%C4%99giel&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjk45mTp97oAhWSF3IKHVlSAFAQ6AEIOTAC</ref> However, as Solidarity boycotted the mines in Silesia and demonstrations became more frequent, the production level dropped considerably along with revenue. \n\nJaruzelski perceived this as a threat to both state security and the economy. The forces used in the thrust consisted of eight ZOMO squads supported by ORMO, seven water cannons, three regiments with infantry combat vehicles and one tank regiment.<ref>https://www.slaskie.travel/Poi/Pokaz/2781/462/pomnik-dziewieciu-z-wujka-oraz-muzeumizba-pamieci</ref> It was decided that the situation was far too serious for adopting the principles of [[morality]] to appropriately deal with the miners. Instead, the well-equipped ZOMO and army troops fired at the protesters with a \"shoot to kill\" technique.<ref>https://www.slaskie.travel/Poi/Pokaz/2781/462/pomnik-dziewieciu-z-wujka-oraz-muzeumizba-pamieci</ref> 21 were wounded, 8 were killed on the spot and 1 died in hospital, with the youngest victim being only 19 years old.<ref>https://plus.dziennikzachodni.pl/pacyfikacja-kopalni-wujek-po-30-latach-ujawnil-sie-i-mowi-widzialem-dramat-na-wujku-dlaczego-tyle-lat-milczal/ar/c3-12769448</ref> The remaining crowd was violently dispersed. The miners repeatedly fought back with their work tools and, in retaliation, wounded dozens of soldiers and militiamen.<ref>https://www.historiaposzukaj.pl/wiedza,wydarzenia,772,pacyfikacja_kopalni_wujek.html</ref> It was one of the deadliest single incidents during the martial law period.<ref>https://dzieje.pl/aktualnosci/37-lat-temu-zginelo-9-gornikow-kopalni-wujek-najwieksza-tragedia-stanu-wojennego</ref>\n\n===Gda\u0144sk, Krak\u00f3w, Lubin and continuing protests===\n{{see also|1982 demonstrations in Poland}}\n[[File:2010-07-08-gdansk-by-RalfR-05.jpg|thumb|left|221px||The former [[Polish United Workers' Party|PZPR]] headquarters in [[Gda\u0144sk]] (right). ZOMO machine-gunned demonstrators from the rooftop]]\nOn the same day as Wujek was pacified, a 30,000-strong<ref>https://13grudnia81.pl/sw/historia/mapa-regionow-nszz-sol/8390,Region-Gdanski-13-XII-1981-22-VII-1983.html</ref> demonstration was held in the northern port city of [[Gda\u0144sk]]. Clashes with ZOMO continued until 17 December and over 324 individuals were injured. The Militia used firearms and [[machine guns]] when the crowd approached the [[Polish United Workers' Party]] headquarters in Gda\u0144sk.<ref>https://regiony.rp.pl/archiwum/3499-stan-wojenny-zaskoczyl-wszystkich</ref> A short and presumably cautionary [[salvo|gun salvo]] from the building's roof hit several people and wounded 4. 1 participant was killed.<ref>https://www.gdanskstrefa.com/37-rocznica-morderstwa-antoniego-browarczyka/</ref> The southern city of [[Krak\u00f3w]] was also witnessing heavy demonstrations, with thousands marching on the street demanding an end to the martial law and communist rule.<ref>https://polskatimes.pl/orla-wrona-nie-pokona-stan-wojenny-w-polsce/ar/c15-14652107?__cf_chl_jschl_tk__=040b57120dfa209cf74313182fc0e68278da22f7-1586537913-0-AYwocIzvMBLfBRjcutP5-ozRCmsSmJsrruSWLOvamxnHGjAsusoEMGxJrlYKPZhGjRi0pTXh4WoQhQFfsIR5o9rXXeB3yAhHX2vpxRAo0j69eiFmVLHn26KvJYmfQQJUatjy94GlBqCQMag8pm7UFUOrrBT0Qmu4X7jD6T0u1teZBRhr13__6JgnUiW7EyIr94uq09ELeHoOsIw62b3rrF59Ll_cyiU7b38aYVrM2dPIkkVup4h2Y4xuM_XgyWo4sIXQ19MMbopFR7gMP-A8NNQHVbDE6aHIAJnI64rm8Gd3Bt83j7EoswA1vrASnLGzfryaliMbbmPUW0qg_331fMRzQW1CAwKhaUM9qYyi-1MX</ref>  \n\nOn the night of 29-30 April 1982, local miners in [[Wodzis\u0142aw \u015al\u0105ski]] planted a bomb and blew up a monument dedicated to [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] soldiers who liberated Poland from the Nazis in 1945.<ref>https://www.nowiny.pl/79880-bombowcy-ze-slaska-zapomniana-historia.html</ref> It was the only incident involving explosives and the caught perpetrators became subsequently known as \"Bombers from [[Silesia]]\" (Polish: \"Bombowcy ze \u015al\u0105ska\").<ref>https://www.nowiny.pl/79880-bombowcy-ze-slaska-zapomniana-historia.html</ref> The operation was a success as the monument was never reconstructed, though the bombers were sentenced and jailed soon-after. Other suspects and hundreds of other miners across Silesia were sacked and removed from their job posts, which further weakened the economy. \n\nIn May 1982, the protests convened by Solidarity were receiving less attention and the struggle against the government was evidently weakening. However, by August, the social unrest again surged. On 31 August 1982, demonstrations took place in around 66<ref>https://dzieje.pl/aktualnosci/sierpniowe-manifestacje-w-1982-r</ref> towns and cities, with at least 18 in the southwestern [[Lower Silesian Voivodeship|province of Lower Silesia]]. In [[Wroc\u0142aw]], one of main centers of Fighting Solidarity, several thousand people for many hours clashed with ZOMO units.<ref>https://nowahistoria.interia.pl/prl/news-manifestacja-we-wroclawiu-31-sierpnia-1982-roku-kiedy-zomo-u,nId,1067057</ref> One demonstrator was killed by a bullet. \n\nThe copper-mining town of [[Lubin]] also became a hotspot for Solidarity-led rallies.<ref>https://www.polskieradio.pl/39/156/Artykul/2361818,Wydarzenia-lubinskie-Krwawy-sierpien-82-w-Zaglebiu-Miedziowym</ref> On that day, the gathered people sung the Polish national anthem and chanted slurs and slogans against the communist regime, against the military junta with Jaruzelski as its head and against the Soviets. After approximately 30 minutes, the rally of 2,000<ref>https://www.polskieradio.pl/39/156/Artykul/2361818,Wydarzenia-lubinskie-Krwawy-sierpien-82-w-Zaglebiu-Miedziowym</ref> was surrounded by the Militia, armed with [[AK-47]] assault rifles. In response, agitated protesters shouted slurs such as \"pigs\", \"bandits\", \"[[Gestapo]]\", \"murderers\" and \"servants of [[Brezhnev]]\".<ref>https://www.fakt.pl/hobby/historia/zbrodnia-lubinska-co-wydarzylo-sie-w-lubinie-31-sierpnia-1982-r/k7jtr26</ref> An unsuccessful attempt was made at building a [[barricade]], but the government units were able to pass through and dispersed the first group with [[tear gas]]. When the demonstrators regrouped and formed a second wave, ZOMO opened fire and wittingly murdered 2 men. The now infuriated crowd began continuous attacks and the Militia shot several more times, injuring one more man at the back of his head. He died in hospital few days later. Reinforcements were sent from [[Legnica]]<ref>http://31sierpnia1982.pl/lubin</ref> and the new deployees were organized into so-called \"raid groups\" in [[ZSD Nysa|Nysa vans]].<ref>https://www.polskieradio.pl/39/156/Artykul/2361818,Wydarzenia-lubinskie-Krwawy-sierpien-82-w-Zaglebiu-Miedziowym</ref><ref>https://dzieje.pl/artykuly-historyczne/lubin-1982-zbrodnia-nieukarana</ref> These groups roamed the streets, often attacking casual passers-by.<ref>https://dzieje.pl/artykuly-historyczne/lubin-1982-zbrodnia-nieukarana</ref> Immediately after the protest was pacified, security forces began the destruction of any evidence to conceal the crime.<ref>https://pamiec.pl/pa/teksty/artykuly/17117,POLOWANIE-NA-LUDZI-ZBRODNIA-LUBINSKA-31-SIERPNIA-1982-ROKU.html</ref> During the night of 31 August\u20131 September, the streets were cleared, with all shells and bullets taken for analysis. On 2 September, authorities ordered the repairs of damaged buildings; broken windows were replaced and traces of bullets on the walls were covered with plaster.<ref>https://pamiec.pl/pa/teksty/artykuly/17117,POLOWANIE-NA-LUDZI-ZBRODNIA-LUBINSKA-31-SIERPNIA-1982-ROKU.html</ref> The investigation, despite consistent statements made by witnesses of the massacre, was closed.    \n\nTo avoid further escalation, on 14 November, Lech Wa\u0142\u0119sa was released from custody in a detention camp. Following his release, no major demonstration took place.<ref>https://www.fakt.pl/lech-walesa</ref>\n\n===Law, rules and censorship===\n{{main|Censorship in Communist Poland}}\n[[File:Przepustka-stan wojenny.jpg|thumb|230px|An intercity travel pass, 1981]]\n[[File:Telegr.jpg|thumb|right|230px|A censored telegram, 1982]]\nFrom the very beginning in December 1981, a strict [[curfew]] was imposed from 19:00 (7:00 p.m.) until 6 in the morning.<ref>https://bliskopolski.pl/historia-polski/stan-wojenny/zycie-codzienne/</ref> The time of curfew was later adjusted to 22:00 (10:00 p.m.)\u201306:00.<ref>https://sciaga.pl/tekst/59147-60-stan_wojenny</ref> Night walks or escapades were forbidden and street patrols were commonplace. The [[Military Council of National Salvation|WRON Military Council]] sealed off the country's borders, closed all airports<ref>https://www.rmf24.pl/raporty/raport-rocznica-wprowadzenia-stanu-wojennego/kalendarium-stanu-wojennego</ref> and road access to main cities was restricted. Special permission passes were issued for individuals in extraordinary cases.<ref>https://ipn.gov.pl/ftp/13grudnia81/czytelnia/Stan_wojenny_Teka_edukacyjna.pdf</ref> Telephone lines were disconnected, mail was subjected to renewed [[postal censorship]],<ref>https://dziennikpolski24.pl/cenzura-w-stanie-wojennym/ar/11567123</ref> all independent political organizations were criminalized and lessons in schools and universities temporarily suspended.<ref>https://wiadomosci.dziennik.pl/historia/wydarzenia/artykuly/587159,rocznia-wprowadzenie-stan-wojenny-gen-jaruzelski-13-grudnia-1981.html</ref> \n\nThe government imposed a six-day work week while the mass media, public services, healthcare services, power stations, coal mines, sea ports, railway stations, and most key factories were placed under military management, with employees having to follow military orders or face a [[court martial]]. As part of the crackdown, media and educational institutions underwent \"verification\", a process that tested each employee's attitude towards the regime and to the Solidarity movement; as a result, thousands of journalists, teachers and professors were banned from their professions. [[Military court]]s were established to bypass the normal court system, to imprison those spreading \"false information\".<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/special_report/1999/09/99/iron_curtain/timelines/poland_81.stm 1981: Martial law], [[BBC]]</ref> In an attempt to crush resistance, civilian phone lines were routinely tapped and monitored by government agents.\n\n===Synopsis===\n\nDuring the initial imposition of martial law, several dozen people were killed. Official reports during the crackdown claimed about a dozen fatalities, while a [[Sejm of the Republic of Poland|parliamentary]] commission in the years 1989\u20131991 arrived at a figure of over 90.<ref>[http://wyborcza.pl/1,77062,3787704.html Ofiary stanu wojennego i lat nast\u0119pnych do 1989] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108144638/http://wyborcza.pl/1,77062,3787704.html |date=2014-01-08 }} by Piotr Lipi\u0144ski</ref> Others were also killed and wounded during a massive second wave of demonstrations on [[August 31, 1982 demonstrations in Poland|31 August 1982]].\n\nAt the invitation of Jaruzelski, a delegation of the ruling [[Hungarian Socialist Workers' Party]] visited Poland between 27 and 29 December. The Hungarians shared with their Polish colleagues their experiences on crushing the [[1956 Hungarian revolution|\"counterrevolution\" of 1956]]. Earlier in the autumn of 1981, Polish television had broadcast a special film on the 1956 events in Hungary, showing scenes of rebels hanging security officers etc.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=wI9TUaZZeAMC&pg=PA499&dq=jaruzelski+1981+martial+law#v=onepage&q=jaruzelski%201981%20martial%20law&f=false Google Books]</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:AGAD_Gen._Wojciech_jaruzelski_13_grudnia_1981.png|Jaruzelski in a TV studio announcing the introduction of martial law\nFile:Stan wojenny obwieszczenie.jpg|The proclamation of martial law by the State Council\nFile:Stan wojenny w Polsce - 1981-1983 - 12a.JPG|Units of the [[Milicja_Obywatelska|Citizens' Militia]] and [[ZOMO]] race to disperse crowds of protesters\n</gallery>\n\n==Economic impact==\n[[File:Kartka P3 11-83.jpeg|thumb|Food, alcohol, and cigarettes [[rationing]] card]]\n\nEven after martial law was lifted, a number of restrictions remained in place for several years that drastically reduced the [[civil liberties]] of the citizenry. It also led to severe economic consequences. The ruling [[military dictatorship]] instituted major price rises (dubbed \"economic reforms\"), which resulted in a fall in real wages of 20% or more. The resulting [[economic crisis]] led to the [[rationing]] of most products and materials, including basic foodstuffs.\n\nAs a consequence of economic hardship and political repression, an exodus of Poles saw 700,000 emigrate to the West between 1981 and 1989.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=nypuJ8BARiMC&pg=PA7&lpg=PA7&dq=poland+economy+1980s&source=bl&ots=iR_fCDeyE6&sig=q2hNTHlJPvd7MOfHIhY-lEKmJsc&hl=en&ei=lLEbS6OKG8z_4Abzt4TnAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&ved=0CDIQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=poland%20economy%201980s&f=false Google Books]</ref> \nA number of international flights were even hijacked in attempts to flee the country and its economic problems. Between December 1980 and October 1983, 11 Polish flights were hijacked to [[Berlin Tempelhof Airport]] alone.<ref>[http://www.atlantic-times.com/archive_detail.php?recordID=673 A Symbol Of Allied Solidarity Will Disappear. Berlin - The Atlantic Times] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707184128/http://www.atlantic-times.com/archive_detail.php?recordID=673 |date=2011-07-07 }}</ref>\n\nAround the same time, a group calling themselves the \"Polish Revolutionary Home Army\" seized the Polish Embassy in [[Bern]], [[Switzerland]] on 6 September 1982, taking several diplomats as hostages. However this turned out to be an apparent provocation by the communist Polish secret services aiming to discredit the Solidarity movement.<ref>[http://www.start.umd.edu/start/data/tops/terrorist_organization_profile.asp?id=4206 Terrorist Organization Profile: Polish Revolutionary Home Army]</ref>\n\n==International response==\n{{Expand section|date=July 2009}}\n\nAfter the \"Wujek\" Coal Mine incident in Katowice on 23 December 1981, the [[United States]] imposed [[economic sanctions]] against the [[People's Republic of Poland]]. In 1982 the United States suspended [[most favored nation]] trade status until 1987 and vetoed Poland's application for membership in the [[International Monetary Fund]].<ref>[http://countrystudies.us/poland/92.htm Poland - The United States]</ref>\n\nPope John Paul II wrote a [https://www.nytimes.com/1981/03/29/world/pope-calls-for-justice-and-peace-in-polish-quest-for-a-settlement.html letter] to the Primate of Poland, Stefan Cardinal Wyszynski, in which he called for peace talks between the state and the workers, supporting the Poles' \"undeniable right to resolve their problems by themselves.\"\n\n==Aftermath==\n\n===Ruling of unconstitutionality===\nAfter the [[fall of Communism in Poland]] in 1989, members of a parliamentary commission determined that martial law had been imposed in clear violation of the country's [[constitution]] which had authorized the executive to declare martial law only between parliamentary sessions (at other times the decision was to be taken by the [[Sejm]]). However, the Sejm had been in session at the time when martial law was instituted. In 1992 the Sejm declared the 1981 imposition of martial law to be unlawful and unconstitutional.\n\n===Soviet intervention debate===\n{{further|Soviet reaction to the Polish Crisis of 1980-1981}}\n\nThe instigators of the martial law, such as [[Wojciech Jaruzelski]], argue that the army crackdown rescued Poland from a possibly disastrous [[military intervention]] of the [[Soviet Union]], [[East Germany]], and other [[Warsaw Pact]] countries (similar to the earlier interventions in [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956|Hungary in 1956]] and [[Prague Spring|Czechoslovakia in 1968]]).<ref>[http://www.euronews.net/2008/10/02/jaruzelski-says-martial-law-saved-poland/ Jaruzelski says martial law saved Poland], [[Euronews]], 02/10/08</ref> Public figures who supported the introduction of martial law (including some of the right-wing figures like [[J\u0119drzej Giertych]]) would also refer to that threat.\n\nIn 2009, archive documents hinted that in a conversation Jaruzelski had with [[Viktor Kulikov]], a Soviet military leader, Jaruzelski himself begged for Soviet intervention as his domestic control was deteriorating.<ref>[http://www.newpolandexpress.pl/npe_news_story-1531-jaruzelski_invited_soviet_invasion.php Newpolandexpress.pl] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009161848/http://www.newpolandexpress.pl/npe_news_story-1531-jaruzelski_invited_soviet_invasion.php |date=2011-10-09 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.rferl.org/content/Interview_Polands_Jaruzelski_Again_Denies_Seeking_Soviet_Intervention_Against_Solidarity/1902431.html Rferl.org]</ref> Jaruzelski responded by claiming the document was 'just another falsification'.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n==Declaration script==\nLed by [[General of the Army]] [[Wojciech Jaruzelski]], the [[Military Council of National Salvation]] (''Wojskowa Rada Ocalenia Narodowego'', WRON) usurped for itself powers reserved for wartime, hence the name. The plan was presented to the government of the [[Soviet Union]] before the declaration in March 1981.\n\nAppearing on Polish television at 6:00 a.m. on 13 December 1981, General Jaruzelski said:<ref>The original is available at [http://www.konflikty.pl/a,395,Czasy_najnowsze,Przemowienie_gen._Jaruzelskiego.html Konflikty.pl] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121112060937/http://www.konflikty.pl/a,395,Czasy_najnowsze,Przemowienie_gen._Jaruzelskiego.html |date=2012-11-12 }}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>Today I address myself to you as a soldier and as the head of the Polish government. I address you concerning extraordinarily important questions. Our homeland is at the edge of an abyss. The achievements of many generations and the Polish home that has been built up from the dust are about to turn into ruins. State structures are ceasing to function. Each day delivers new blows to the waning economy./.../<br>The atmosphere of conflicts, misunderstanding, hatred causes moral degradation, surpasses the limits of toleration. Strikes, the readiness to strike, actions of protest have become a norm of life. Even school youth are being drawn into this. Yesterday evening, many public buildings remained seized. The cries are voiced to physical reprisals with the 'reds', with people who have different opinions. <br>The cases of terror, threats and moral vendetta, of even direct violence are on the rise. A wave of impudent crimes, robberies and burglaries is running across the country. The underground business sharks' fortunes, already reaching millions, are growing. Chaos and demoralization have reached the magnitude of a catastrophe. People have reached the limit of psychological toleration. Many people are struck by despair. Not only days, but hours as well are bringing forth the all-national disaster./.../<br>Citizens!<br>The load of responsibility that falls on me on this dramatic moment in the Polish history is huge. It is my duty to take this responsibility - concerning the future of Poland, that my generation fought for on all the fronts of the war and for which they sacrificed the best years of their life. I declare, that today the Military Council of National Salvation has been formed. In accordance with the Constitution, the State Council has imposed martial law all over the country. I wish that everyone understood the motives of our actions. A military coup, military dictatorship is not our goal./.../<br> In longer perspective, none of Poland's problems can be solved with the use of violence. The Military Council of National Salvation does not replace constitutional organs of power. Its only purpose is to keep the legal balance of the country, to create guarantees that give a chance to restore order and discipline. This is the ultimate way to bring the country out of the crisis, to save the country from collapse./.../<br>I appeal to all the citizens. A time of heavy trials has arrived. And we have to stand those in order to prove that we are worthy of Poland.<br>Before all the Polish people and the whole world I would like to repeat the immortal words: <br>\n::'''''[[Poland Is Not Yet Lost|Poland has not yet perished, so long as we still live]]!'''''</blockquote>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Able Archer 83]]\n* [[Fighting Solidarity]]\n* [[Pacification of Wujek]]\n* [[Polish 1970 protests]]\n* [[Pozna\u0144 1956 protests]]\n* [[Romanian Revolution]], 1989\n* [[Soviet reaction to the Polish Crisis of 1980-1981]]\n* [[Telephone tapping in the Eastern Bloc]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Leopold Labedz, ''Poland Under Jaruzelski: A Comprehensive Sourcebook on Poland During and After Martial Law''\n* George Sanford, ''Military Rule in Poland: The Rebuilding of Communist Power, 1981\u20131983''\n{{Portal|Poland|History|Communism|War|1980s}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Martial law in Poland}}\n* [http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB211/index.htm Solidarity and Martial Law in Poland: 25 Years Later], [[National Security Archive]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110112170636/http://www.onwar.com/aced/chrono/c1900s/yr80/fpoland1981.htm Martial Law in Poland 1981-1983]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080105033603/http://www.tenetour.com/history9.php Martial Law in Poland]\n* [http://www.videofact.com/english/stanwoj2.htm Martial Law in Poland 1981]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dKhITm9-5TU Video of Jaruzelski declaring martial law], [[Telewizja Polska|TVP]]/[[YouTube]]\n* [http://www.pbase.com/zyziza/martial_law_in_poland Photo Gallery by zyziza at pbase.com]\n\n{{History of the People's Republic of Poland}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martial Law In Poland}}\n[[Category:1980s coups d'\u00e9tat and coup attempts]]\n[[Category:1981 in Poland]]\n[[Category:1981 in politics]]\n[[Category:1982 in Poland]]\n[[Category:1982 in politics]]\n[[Category:1983 in Poland]]\n[[Category:1983 in politics]]\n[[Category:Anti-communism in Poland]]\n[[Category:Communism in Poland]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1981]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1982]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1983]]\n[[Category:Emergency laws]]\n[[Category:Martial law|Poland]]\n[[Category:Military coups in Poland]]\n[[Category:Military dictatorships|Poland]]\n[[Category:Poland\u2013Soviet Union relations]]\n[[Category:Solidarity (Polish trade union)]]\n", "name_user": "Oliszydlowski", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:removed directly unrelated links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martial_law_in_Poland"}
