Football|Fox]], [[Fox Sports 1|FS1]]), [[ESPN|ESPN Family]] ([[ESPN College Football on ABC|ABC]], [[ESPN College Football|ESPN]], [[ESPN2]], [[ESPNU College Football|ESPNU]]), and [[Pac-12 Network]]s\n| top_scorer       = \n| top_scorer_link  =\n| conf1            = North\n| conf1_champ      = [[2015 Stanford Cardinal football team|Stanford Cardinal]]\n| conf1_runner-up  = [[2015 Oregon Ducks football team|Oregon Ducks]]\n| conf2            = South\n| conf2_champ      = [[2015 USC Trojans football team|USC Trojans]]<br />[[2015 Utah Utes football team|Utah Utes]]\n| conf2_runner-up  = [[2015 UCLA Bruins football team|UCLA Bruins]]\n| finals           = Pac-12 Championship\n| finals_link      = 2015 Pac-12 Football Championship Game\n| finals_champ     = [[2015 Stanford Cardinal football team|Stanford Cardinal]]\n| finals_runner-up = [[2015 USC Trojans football team|USC Trojans]]\n| finals_MVP       = [[Christian McCaffrey]], [[Running back|RB]]\n| finals_MVP_link  =\n| seasonslist      = \n| seasonslistnames = Football\n| prevseason_year  = [[2014 Pac-12 Conference football season|2014]]\n| nextseason_year  = [[2016 Pac-12 Conference football season|2016]]\n}}\n{{2015 Pac-12 football standings}}\nThe '''2015 Pac-12 Conference football season''' was the fifth season for the conference as a twelve-team league. The season began on September 3, 2015 with a trio of games, [[2015 Arizona Wildcats football team|Arizona]] hosting [[2015 UTSA Roadrunners football team|UTSA]], [[2015 Utah Utes football team|Utah]] hosting [[2015 Michigan Wolverines football team|Michigan]], and [[2015 Hawaii Rainbow Warriors football team|Hawaii]] hosting [[2015 Colorado Buffaloes football team|Colorado]]. The final game was the [[2015 Pac-12 Football Championship Game|Pac-12 Championship Game]] at [[Levi's Stadium]] on December 5, 2015, with [[ESPN]] televising the game.\n\n==Previous season==\nOregon, the North Division Champions, defeated Arizona, the South Division Champions, 51\u201313 to claim their second conference title and the chance to play in the [[College Football Playoff]] (CFP) semifinal game at the [[2015 Rose Bowl|Rose Bowl]], where they defeated Florida State 59\u201320, advancing to their second-ever national championship game (the first-ever [[2015 College Football Playoff National Championship|CFP National Championship Game]]), where they were defeated by the Ohio Buckeyes, 42\u201320.\n\nA record nine conference teams played in a post-season bowl game, with six winning. Arizona, the South Division Champion, was also a bowl game loser, losing to Boise State 38\u201330 in the [[2014 Fiesta Bowl (December)|Fiesta Bowl]]. Bowl game winners were: Arizona State defeated Duke 36-31 in the [[2014 Sun Bowl|Sun Bowl]], Stanford defeated Maryland 45\u201321 in the [[2014 Foster Farms Bowl|Foster Farms Bowl]], UCLA defeated Kansas State 40-35 in the [[2015 Alamo Bowl|Alamo Bowl]], USC defeated Nebraska 45\u201342 in the [[2014 Holiday Bowl|Holiday Bowl]], and Utah defeated Colorado State 45\u201310 in the [[2014 Las Vegas Bowl|Las Vegas Bowl]].\n\n==Pre-season==\n2015 Pac-12 Spring Football and number of signees on signing day:\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-1-of-2}}\n'''North Division''' \t\n* California: March 9 \u2013 April 18 with 24 signees\n* Oregon: March 31 \u2013 May 2 with 22 signees\n* Oregon State: March 3 \u2013 April 18 with 22 signees\n* Stanford: Feb. 23 \u2013 April 11 with 22 signees\n* Washington: March 30 \u2013 April 25 with 24 signees\n* Washington State: March 12 \u2013 April 28 with 24 signees\n{{Col-2-of-2}}\n'''South Division''' \n* Arizona: March 4  \u2013 April 10 with 25 signees\n* Arizona State: March 16 \u2013 April 10 with 22 signees\n* Colorado: Feb. 13 \u2013 March 15 with 19 signees\n* UCLA: March 31 \u2013 April 25, 2015 with 18 signees\n* USC: March 3 \u2013 April 11 with 24 signees\n* Utah: March 24 \u2013 April 25 with 20 signees\n{{Col-end}}\n\n===Pac-12 Media===\n2015 Pac-12 Media Day was held at [[Warner Bros.]] in [[Burbank, California]] on July 30\u201331, 2015.\n\n====Preseason polls====\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-1-of-2}}\n'''North Division'''\n*1. [[Oregon Ducks football|Oregon]] (37), 262 pts\n*2. [[Stanford Cardinal football|Stanford]] (8), 232 pts\n*3. [[California Golden Bears football|California]], 174 pts\n*4. [[Washington Huskies football|Washington]], 129 pts\n*5. [[Washington State Cougars football|Washington State]], 89 pts\n*6. [[Oregon State Beavers football|Oregon State]], 60 pts\n{{Col-2-of-2}}\t\n\n'''South Division'''\n*1. [[USC Trojans football|USC]] (32), 254 pts\n*2. [[Arizona State Sun Devils football|Arizona State]] (7), 200 pts\n*3. [[UCLA Bruins football|UCLA]] (6), 180 pts\n*4. [[Arizona Wildcats football|Arizona]], 155 pts\n*5. [[Utah Utes football|Utah]], 105 pts\n*6. [[Colorado Buffaloes football|Colorado]], 46 pts\n{{Col-end}}\n*''' Predicted Pac-12 Championship Game Winner''': USC (21) was picked to win the Pac-12 Championship over Oregon (17) for the first time since 2012.  Others receiving votes were ASU (3), UCLA (2), and Stanford (1).\n\n===Recruiting classes===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Rankings\n! Team\n! ESPN<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insider.espn.go.com/college-sports/football/recruiting/classrankings?action=login |title=Football Class Rankings - ESPN |publisher=Insider.espn.go.com |date= |accessdate=2015-04-04}}</ref>\n! Rivals<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/ncaa/football/recruiting/teamrank/2015/all/all |title=Yahoo Sports: Rivals.com 2015 Team Recruiting Rankings |publisher=Sports.yahoo.com |date=2011-04-20 |accessdate=2015-04-04}}</ref>\n! Scout<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://recruiting.scout.com/a.z?s=73&p=9&c=14&yr=2015|title = 2015|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150313054824/http://recruiting.scout.com/a.z?s=73&p=9&c=14&yr=2015|archivedate=2015-03-13}}</ref>\n! 24/7<ref>{{cite web|url=https://247sports.com/Season/2015-Football/CompositeTeamRa