bsence-alcohol-treatment | quote =  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first1=Gary |last1=Klein |first2=Lindsey |last2=Thiry |title=USC places Coach Steve Sarkisian on leave; Clay Helton interim coach |url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/usc/uscnow/la-sp-usc-steve-sarkisian-on-leave-20151011-story.html |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=October 11, 2015 |accessdate=October 11, 2015}}</ref>\n* October 30, 2015 \u2013 USC Athletic Director [[Pat Haden]] resigned from the [[College Football Playoff]] Selection Committee\n* November 30, 2015 \u2013 [[Clay Helton]] was named USC's permanent head coach.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Pac-12 Conference football navbox}}\n{{2015 NCAA Division I FBS football season navbox}}\n\n[[Category:2015 Pac-12 Conference football season|*]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePrevious season:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 36-31 \u2192 36\u201331 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2015_Pac-12_Conference_football_season"}
{"title_page": "I Got Rhythm", "text_new": "{{about|the song|the album by Teddy Wilson|I Got Rhythm (album)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name      = I Got Rhythm\n| cover     =\n| alt       =\n| type      =\n| written   =\n| published = 1930\n| writer    =\n| composer  = [[George Gershwin]]\n| lyricist  = [[Ira Gershwin]]\n}}\n\n\"'''I Got Rhythm'''\" is a piece composed by [[George Gershwin]] with lyrics by [[Ira Gershwin]] and published in 1930, which became a [[jazz standard]].  Its chord progression, known as the \"[[rhythm changes]]\", is the foundation for many other popular jazz tunes such as [[Charlie Parker]]'s and [[Dizzy Gillespie]]'s [[bebop]] standard [[Anthropology (composition)|\"Anthropology (Thrivin' on a Riff)\"]].\n\n== Composition ==\nThe song came from the musical ''[[Girl Crazy]]'' which also includes two other hit songs, \"[[Embraceable You]]\" and \"[[But Not for Me (song)|But Not for Me]]\", and has been sung by many jazz singers since. It was originally written as a slow song for ''[[Treasure Girl]]'' (1928) and found another, faster setting in ''Girl Crazy''. [[Ethel Merman]] sang the song in the original [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production and Broadway lore holds that [[George Gershwin]], after seeing her opening reviews, warned her never to take a singing lesson.\n\nThe piece was originally penned in the key of D{{music|flat}} major. The song melody uses four notes of the five-note [[pentatonic scale]], first rising, then falling. A rhythmic interest in the song is that the tune keeps behind the main pulse, with the three \"I got...\" phrases [[Syncopation|syncopated]], appearing one beat behind in the first bar, while the fourth phase \"Who could...\" rushes in to the song. The song's chorus is in a 34-bar [[AABA form]].<ref>Covach, John (2005), \"Form in Rock Music: A Primer\", in Stein, Deborah, ''Engaging Music: Essays in Music Analysis'', New York: Oxford University Press, p.70, {{ISBN|0-19-517010-5}} .</ref> Its chord progression (although often reduced to a standard 32-bar structure, for the sake of improvised solos), is known as the \"[[rhythm changes]]\", and is the foundation for many other popular jazz tunes. The song was used as the theme in Gershwin's last concert piece for piano and orchestra, the ''[[Variations on \"I Got Rhythm\"]]'', written in 1934. The song has become symbolic of the Gershwins, of swing, and of the 1920s.\n\nAs usual, George Gershwin wrote the melody first and gave it to Ira to set, but Ira found it an unusually hard melody for which to create lyrics. He experimented for two weeks with the rhyme scheme he felt the music called for, sets of triple rhymes, but found that the heavy rhyming \"seemed at best to give a pleasant and jingly Mother Goose quality to a tune which should throw its weight around more.\" Finally he began to experiment with leaving most of the lines unrhymed. \"This approach felt stronger,\" he wrote, \"and I finally arrived at the present refrain, with only 'more-door' and 'mind him-find him' the rhymes.\" He added that this approach \"was a bit daring for me who usually depended on rhyme insurance.\"<ref name=\"occasions\">{{cite book | last=Gershwin | first=Ira | title=Lyrics on Several Occasions | edition=First | location=New York | publisher=Knopf | year=1959 | oclc=538209}}</ref>\n\nIra also wrote that although the phrase \"who could ask for anything more?\" is repeated four times in the song, he decided not to make it the title because \"somehow the first line of the refrain sounded more arresting and provocative.\"<ref name=\"occasions\"/>\n\n== History ==\nThe song was included in the Gershwin brothers' 1931 Broadway musical. ''[[Of Thee I Sing]]''.<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Of_Thee_I_Sing</ref>\n\nAn instrumental arrangement for piano and orchestra appears in the 1945 ''[[Hollywood Victory Caravan]]''.<ref>''Hollywood Victory Caravan and Bond Rallies'', in ''Hollywood Goes to War:  Collector's Edition'', 2004 pressing, Diamond Entertainment, Disk 1.</ref>\n\nThe song is featured in the 1951 musical film ''[[An American in Paris (film)|An American in Paris]]''. [[Gene Kelly]] sang the song and [[Tap dance|tap-danced]], while French-speaking children whom he had just taught a few words of English shouted the words \"I got\" each time they appeared in the lyrics. This version finished at #32 in [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Songs]] survey of top tunes in American cinema.\n\nIt is also featured in the film ''[[Mr. Holland's Opus]]'', during a scene in which students are trying out for a Gershwin revue.\n\nAlso featured in the movie \"My Girl\", during a dinner scene when the grandmother sang it, oblivious of the others.\n\nA complete list of notable singers who have recorded this song would take up several pages. The most popular versions are those of [[The Happenings]] (#3 on the US charts in 1967<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/esearch/searchResult.jsp?keyword=%22see+you+in+september%22&x=0&y=0&exposeNavigation=true&an=bbcom \"See You in September\"], ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. Accessed October 3, 2007.</ref>), [[Judy Garland]], [[Ethel Merman]], [[Ella Fitzgerald]], and more recently, [[Jodi Benson]].\n\nIt is a very popular [[jazz standard]]. Many songs use its chord progression, such as [[Duke Ellington]]'s \"[[Cotton Tail]]\". [[Charlie Parker]] alone based many songs on its chord progression, e.g. \"[[Moose the Mooche]]\". [[Gary Larson]] referenced the song in the [[Far Side]].\n\nIn 1939, ''I Got Rhythm'' was arranged and orchestrated by [[Bruce Chase]] for a premiere performance by the Kansas Philharmonic, now the [[Kansas City Symphony]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1368&dat=19840411&id=XnoWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PhIEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3362,1882543 |title=\"Violinist Arranges Laughter at Symphony:\" '&#39;The Milwaukee Sentinel'&#39;, April 11, 1984 |publisher=News.google.com |date=1984-04-11 |accessdate=2012-02-23}}</ref>\n\nA version of the song set to a disco beat was recorded by Ethel Merman for her ''[[The Ethel Merman Disco Album|Ethel Merman Disco Album]]'' in 1979.<ref>''The Ethel Merman Disco Album'', Track 7. 1979 recording reissued on CD in 2002 by Universal Music Enterprises, a division of UMG Recordings, Inc.</ref>\n\nIn 1992 the show [[Crazy for You (musical)|Crazy for You]] had it song by [[Jodi Benson]].http://www.londontheatres.co.uk/novello-theatre/crazy-for-you/\n\nAnother version of the song was arranged for solo guitar by Ton Van Bergeyk. It appears on the album ''Black and Tan Fantasy''. [[Mike Oldfield]] and [[Wendy Roberts]] performed a version on Oldfield's ''[[Platinum (Mike Oldfield album)|Platinum album]]''.\n\nThe song was satirized in an episode of ''[[The Muppet Show]]'' where [[Rowlf the Dog|Rowlf]] and [[Fozzie Bear|Fozzie]] attempt to perform it but Fozzie is unable to keep in tempo. To compensate Rowlf has him change the lyrics to \"I don't got Rhythm\".<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=32j8M5G1f8o</ref>\n\nThe song was satirized in an episode of ''[[Draft:Lulu's World|Lulu's World]]'' where Stanley the [[Mouse]] sings and tap dances in the theater in Mouseville.\n\nThe song has appeared in several film versions of ''Girl Crazy'':\n*[[Girl Crazy (1932 film)|''Girl Crazy'' (1932)]], performed by [[Kitty Kelly]]\n*[[Girl Crazy (1943 film)|''Girl Crazy'' (1943)]], performed by [[Judy Garland]] and [[Mickey Rooney]] with [[Six Hits and a Miss]], The Music Maids and [[Tommy Dorsey]] with his Orchestra\n*''[[When the Boys Meet the Girls]]'' (1965), performed by [[Harve Presnell]] and [[Connie Francis]]\n\n== Other recordings ==\n* [[Louis Armstrong]] \u2013 1931<ref name=\"standards\">{{cite book |last1=Gioia |first1=Ted |title=The Jazz Standards: A Guide to the Repertoire |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York City |isbn=978-0-19-993739-4 |pages=167\u2013169}}</ref>\n* [[Casa Loma Orchestra]] \u2013 1933<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Duke Ellington]]<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* Esquire All Stars (Louis Armstrong, [[Roy Eldridge]], [[Art Tatum]]) \u2013 1944<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[George Gershwin]] \u2013 1931<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Stephane Grappelli]] and [[McCoy Tyner]] \u2013 ''One on One'' (1990)<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Benny Goodman]] \u2013 1938<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[The Happenings]]<ref name=\"standards\" /> \u2013 ''Psycle'' (1967)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehappenings.com/discography.html |title=The Happenings Official Website - Discography |website=Thehappenings.com |accessdate=2016-10-01}}</ref>\n* Jazz at the Philharmonic ([[Coleman Hawkins]], [[Charlie Parker]], [[Lester Young]]) \u2013 1946\n* [[Ethel Merman]]<ref name=\"standards\" /> \u2013 including a disco version for ''[[The Ethel Merman Disco Album]]'' (1979)<ref name=\"front\">{{Cite AV media notes |title=Front Row Center: The Broadway Gold Box, 1935 \u2013 1988 |others=Ethel Merman |year=1996  |publisher=Broadway Gold/MCA Classics |id=11353}}</ref>\n* Metronome All Stars ([[Count Basie]], [[Benny Carter]], [[Benny Goodman]]) \u2013 1942<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Thelonious Monk]]<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Red Nichols]]<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Charlie Parker]]<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[The Puppini Sisters]] \u2013 ''[[Hollywood (The Puppini Sisters album)|Hollywood]]'' (2011)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/hollywood-mw0002241670 |title=Hollywood |website=AllMusic|access-date=2017-10-24}}</ref>\n* [[Willie \"The Lion\" Smith]] \u2013 1949<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Ethel Waters]]<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Bing Crosby]] included the song in his 1976 album [[At My Time of Life]].<ref>{{cite web |title=discogs.com |url=https://www.discogs.com/Bing-Crosby-At-My-Time-Of-Life/master/1276893 |website=discogs.com |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n*Stanley the Mouse \u2013 [[Draft:Lulu's World (season 4)|2004]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of 1930s jazz standards]]\n*[[Thirty-two-bar form]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n*Greenberg, Rodney (1998). ''George Gershwin''. Phaidon Press. {{ISBN|0-7148-3504-8}}.\n*Gershwin, George (1996). ''The Complete Gershwin Keyboard Works''. Warner Brothers Publications.  {{ISBN|978-1-57623-743-4}}.\n\n== External links ==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|ella-fitzgerald|i-got-rhythm}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Girl Crazy}}\n{{George Gershwin}}\n\n[[Category:1930 songs]]\n[[Category:1930s jazz standards]]\n[[Category:1967 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs with music by George Gershwin]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Ira Gershwin]]\n[[Category:Songs from Girl Crazy]]\n[[Category:Ella Fitzgerald songs]]\n[[Category:Barbra Streisand songs]]\n[[Category:Jazz compositions in B-flat major]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the song|the album by Teddy Wilson|I Got Rhythm (album)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name      = I Got Rhythm\n| cover     =\n| alt       =\n| type      =\n| written   =\n| published = 1930\n| writer    =\n| composer  = [[George Gershwin]]\n| lyricist  = [[Ira Gershwin]]\n}}\n\n\"'''I Got Rhythm'''\" is a piece composed by [[George Gershwin]] with lyrics by [[Ira Gershwin]] and published in 1930, which became a [[jazz standard]].  Its chord progression, known as the \"[[rhythm changes]]\", is the foundation for many other popular jazz tunes such as [[Charlie Parker]]'s and [[Dizzy Gillespie]]'s [[bebop]] standard [[Anthropology (composition)|\"Anthropology (Thrivin' on a Riff)\"]].\n\n== Composition ==\nThe song came from the musical ''[[Girl Crazy]]'' which also includes two other hit songs, \"[[Embraceable You]]\" and \"[[But Not for Me (song)|But Not for Me]]\", and has been sung by many jazz singers since. It was originally written as a slow song for ''[[Treasure Girl]]'' (1928) and found another, faster setting in ''Girl Crazy''. [[Ethel Merman]] sang the song in the original [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production and Broadway lore holds that [[George Gershwin]], after seeing her opening reviews, warned her never to take a singing lesson.\n\nThe piece was originally penned in the key of D{{music|flat}} major. The song melody uses four notes of the five-note [[pentatonic scale]], first rising, then falling. A rhythmic interest in the song is that the tune keeps behind the main pulse, with the three \"I got...\" phrases [[Syncopation|syncopated]], appearing one beat behind in the first bar, while the fourth phase \"Who could...\" rushes in to the song. The song's chorus is in a 34-bar [[AABA form]].<ref>Covach, John (2005), \"Form in Rock Music: A Primer\", in Stein, Deborah, ''Engaging Music: Essays in Music Analysis'', New York: Oxford University Press, p.70, {{ISBN|0-19-517010-5}} .</ref> Its chord progression (although often reduced to a standard 32-bar structure, for the sake of improvised solos), is known as the \"[[rhythm changes]]\", and is the foundation for many other popular jazz tunes. The song was used as the theme in Gershwin's last concert piece for piano and orchestra, the ''[[Variations on \"I Got Rhythm\"]]'', written in 1934. The song has become symbolic of the Gershwins, of swing, and of the 1920s.\n\nAs usual, George Gershwin wrote the melody first and gave it to Ira to set, but Ira found it an unusually hard melody for which to create lyrics. He experimented for two weeks with the rhyme scheme he felt the music called for, sets of triple rhymes, but found that the heavy rhyming \"seemed at best to give a pleasant and jingly Mother Goose quality to a tune which should throw its weight around more.\" Finally he began to experiment with leaving most of the lines unrhymed. \"This approach felt stronger,\" he wrote, \"and I finally arrived at the present refrain, with only 'more-door' and 'mind him-find him' the rhymes.\" He added that this approach \"was a bit daring for me who usually depended on rhyme insurance.\"<ref name=\"occasions\">{{cite book | last=Gershwin | first=Ira | title=Lyrics on Several Occasions | edition=First | location=New York | publisher=Knopf | year=1959 | oclc=538209}}</ref>\n\nIra also wrote that although the phrase \"who could ask for anything more?\" is repeated four times in the song, he decided not to make it the title because \"somehow the first line of the refrain sounded more arresting and provocative.\"<ref name=\"occasions\"/>\n\n== History ==\nThe song was included in the Gershwin brothers' 1931 Broadway musical. ''[[Of Thee I Sing]]''.<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Of_Thee_I_Sing</ref>\n\nAn instrumental arrangement for piano and orchestra appears in the 1945 ''[[Hollywood Victory Caravan]]''.<ref>''Hollywood Victory Caravan and Bond Rallies'', in ''Hollywood Goes to War:  Collector's Edition'', 2004 pressing, Diamond Entertainment, Disk 1.</ref>\n\nThe song is featured in the 1951 musical film ''[[An American in Paris (film)|An American in Paris]]''. [[Gene Kelly]] sang the song and [[Tap dance|tap-danced]], while French-speaking children whom he had just taught a few words of English shouted the words \"I got\" each time they appeared in the lyrics. This version finished at #32 in [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Songs]] survey of top tunes in American cinema.\n\nIt is also featured in the film ''[[Mr. Holland's Opus]]'', during a scene in which students are trying out for a Gershwin revue.\n\nAlso featured in the movie \"My Girl\", during a dinner scene when the grandmother sang it, oblivious of the others.\n\nA complete list of notable singers who have recorded this song would take up several pages. The most popular versions are those of [[The Happenings]] (#3 on the US charts in 1967<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/esearch/searchResult.jsp?keyword=%22see+you+in+september%22&x=0&y=0&exposeNavigation=true&an=bbcom \"See You in September\"], ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. Accessed October 3, 2007.</ref>), [[Judy Garland]], [[Ethel Merman]], [[Ella Fitzgerald]], and more recently, [[Jodi Benson]].\n\nIt is a very popular [[jazz standard]]. Many songs use its chord progression, such as [[Duke Ellington]]'s \"[[Cotton Tail]]\". [[Charlie Parker]] alone based many songs on its chord progression, e.g. \"[[Moose the Mooche]]\". [[Gary Larson]] referenced the song in the [[Far Side]].\n\nIn 1939, ''I Got Rhythm'' was arranged and orchestrated by [[Bruce Chase]] for a premiere performance by the Kansas Philharmonic, now the [[Kansas City Symphony]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1368&dat=19840411&id=XnoWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PhIEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3362,1882543 |title=\"Violinist Arranges Laughter at Symphony:\" '&#39;The Milwaukee Sentinel'&#39;, April 11, 1984 |publisher=News.google.com |date=1984-04-11 |accessdate=2012-02-23}}</ref>\n\nA version of the song set to a disco beat was recorded by Ethel Merman for her ''[[The Ethel Merman Disco Album|Ethel Merman Disco Album]]'' in 1979.<ref>''The Ethel Merman Disco Album'', Track 7. 1979 recording reissued on CD in 2002 by Universal Music Enterprises, a division of UMG Recordings, Inc.</ref>\n\nIn 1992 the show [[Crazy for You (musical)|Crazy for You]] had it song by [[Jodi Benson]].http://www.londontheatres.co.uk/novello-theatre/crazy-for-you/\n\nAnother version of the song was arranged for solo guitar by Ton Van Bergeyk. It appears on the album ''Black and Tan Fantasy''. [[Mike Oldfield]] and [[Wendy Roberts]] performed a version on Oldfield's ''[[Platinum (Mike Oldfield album)|Platinum album]]''.\n\nThe song was satirized in an episode of ''[[The Muppet Show]]'' where [[Rowlf the Dog|Rowlf]] and [[Fozzie Bear|Fozzie]] attempt to perform it but Fozzie is unable to keep in tempo. To compensate Rowlf has him change the lyrics to \"I don't got Rhythm\".<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=32j8M5G1f8o</ref>\n\nThe song has appeared in several film versions of ''Girl Crazy'':\n*[[Girl Crazy (1932 film)|''Girl Crazy'' (1932)]], performed by [[Kitty Kelly]]\n*[[Girl Crazy (1943 film)|''Girl Crazy'' (1943)]], performed by [[Judy Garland]] and [[Mickey Rooney]] with [[Six Hits and a Miss]], The Music Maids and [[Tommy Dorsey]] with his Orchestra\n*''[[When the Boys Meet the Girls]]'' (1965), performed by [[Harve Presnell]] and [[Connie Francis]]\n\n== Other recordings ==\n* [[Louis Armstrong]] \u2013 1931<ref name=\"standards\">{{cite book |last1=Gioia |first1=Ted |title=The Jazz Standards: A Guide to the Repertoire |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York City |isbn=978-0-19-993739-4 |pages=167\u2013169}}</ref>\n* [[Casa Loma Orchestra]] \u2013 1933<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Duke Ellington]]<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* Esquire All Stars (Louis Armstrong, [[Roy Eldridge]], [[Art Tatum]]) \u2013 1944<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[George Gershwin]] \u2013 1931<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Stephane Grappelli]] and [[McCoy Tyner]] \u2013 ''One on One'' (1990)<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Benny Goodman]] \u2013 1938<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[The Happenings]]<ref name=\"standards\" /> \u2013 ''Psycle'' (1967)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehappenings.com/discography.html |title=The Happenings Official Website - Discography |website=Thehappenings.com |accessdate=2016-10-01}}</ref>\n* Jazz at the Philharmonic ([[Coleman Hawkins]], [[Charlie Parker]], [[Lester Young]]) \u2013 1946\n* [[Ethel Merman]]<ref name=\"standards\" /> \u2013 including a disco version for ''[[The Ethel Merman Disco Album]]'' (1979)<ref name=\"front\">{{Cite AV media notes |title=Front Row Center: The Broadway Gold Box, 1935 \u2013 1988 |others=Ethel Merman |year=1996  |publisher=Broadway Gold/MCA Classics |id=11353}}</ref>\n* Metronome All Stars ([[Count Basie]], [[Benny Carter]], [[Benny Goodman]]) \u2013 1942<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Thelonious Monk]]<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Red Nichols]]<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Charlie Parker]]<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[The Puppini Sisters]] \u2013 ''[[Hollywood (The Puppini Sisters album)|Hollywood]]'' (2011)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/hollywood-mw0002241670 |title=Hollywood |website=AllMusic|access-date=2017-10-24}}</ref>\n* [[Willie \"The Lion\" Smith]] \u2013 1949<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Ethel Waters]]<ref name=\"standards\" />\n* [[Bing Crosby]] included the song in his 1976 album [[At My Time of Life]].<ref>{{cite web |title=discogs.com |url=https://www.discogs.com/Bing-Crosby-At-My-Time-Of-Life/master/1276893 |website=discogs.com |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of 1930s jazz standards]]\n*[[Thirty-two-bar form]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n*Greenberg, Rodney (1998). ''George Gershwin''. Phaidon Press. {{ISBN|0-7148-3504-8}}.\n*Gershwin, George (1996). ''The Complete Gershwin Keyboard Works''. Warner Brothers Publications.  {{ISBN|978-1-57623-743-4}}.\n\n== External links ==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|ella-fitzgerald|i-got-rhythm}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Girl Crazy}}\n{{George Gershwin}}\n\n[[Category:1930 songs]]\n[[Category:1930s jazz standards]]\n[[Category:1967 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs with music by George Gershwin]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Ira Gershwin]]\n[[Category:Songs from Girl Crazy]]\n[[Category:Ella Fitzgerald songs]]\n[[Category:Barbra Streisand songs]]\n[[Category:Jazz compositions in B-flat major]]\n", "name_user": "Alexis5653", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eComposition)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I_Got_Rhythm"}
{"title_page": "Kerala Mukkuvar", "text_new": "{{Short description|A maritime Malayali caste found chiefly on the Malabar coast of India}}\n{{Infobox caste|caste_name=Mukkuvar|languages=[[Malayalam language|Malayalam]]|religions=[[Hinduism]], [[Christianity]], [[Islam]]|related=[[Sri Lankan Mukkuvar]], [[Mogaveera]]|subdivisions=<ref>{{Cite book|last=Singh|first=Virendra Prakash|title=Community and Caste in Tradition|date=1992|publisher=Commonwealth Publishers|year=|isbn=978-81-7169-242-2|location=|pages=33|language=en}}</ref>\n{{unbulleted list\n | Northern division: Nalillakkar \u2013 Ponillam, Chembillam, Karillam, Kachillam\n | Southern division: Munillakkar \u2013 Chembillam, Karillam, Kachillam\n  }}}}\n'''Mukkuvar''' is a [[Malayali]] [[caste]] found in the [[India|Indian]] state of [[Kerala]]. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Ram|first=Kalpana|title=Mukkuvar Women: Gender, Hegemony, and Capitalist Transformation in a South Indian Fishing Community|date=1992|publisher=Kali for Women|year=|isbn=978-81-85107-46-2|location=|pages=2|language=en}}</ref> They are mostly found on the littoral regions of the [[Malabar Coast]] and are traditionally occupied in [[fishing]] and [[seafaring]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Ramaiah|first=T. G.|title=Role of Exclusive Credit Linkage Programme for Occupational Dynamics Among Fisherwomen: A Study in Andhra Pradesh and Tamil Nadu States|date=2013|publisher=National Institute of Rural Development, Ministry of Rural Development, Government of India|year=|isbn=978-81-85542-89-8|location=|pages=14|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe caste name proposes several etymology theories. One view holds that the name ''Mukkuvar'' is derived from the [[Dravidian languages|Dravidian]] term ''muluku'' or ''mukku'' meaning \"to dive\", suggesting their traditional occupation in diving for [[Pearl|pearls]] and [[seashell]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=McGilvray|first=Dennis B.|title=Tamils and Moors: caste and matriclan structure in eastern Sri Lanka|date=1974|publisher=University of Chicago|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=23\u201325|language=en}}</ref> Other titles used by the community are ''Kukankulam, Murkukan'' and ''Mukkiyar''.<ref name=\"dbm1982p64\">{{Cite book|last=McGilvray|first=Dennis B.|title=Crucible of Conflict: Tamil and Muslim Society on the East Coast of Sri Lanka|publisher=Duke University Press|year=2008|isbn=978-0822389187|location=|page=60, 61, 64, 77|pages=|authorlink=Dennis B. McGilvray}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Holmes|first=Walter Robert|title=Jaffna, Sri Lanka 1980|date=1980|publisher=Christian Institute for the Study of Religion and Society of Jaffna College|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=219}}</ref> Their titles Kukankulam (Kukan clan) and Murkukan (foremost Kukan) are literary references to ''Kukan,'' the mariner who ferried Hindu god [[Rama]] across [[Ganges]] from [[Ayodhya]] whose descendant they claim.<ref name=\"dbm1982p59\">{{Cite book|last=McGilvray|first=Dennis B.|title=Caste Ideology and Interaction|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1982|isbn=9780521241458|location=|page=59, 60, 68|pages=}}</ref>\n\nThe Mukkuvars are divided into [[Exogamy|exogamous]] clans known as ''llam'' meaning \"house\". The Mukkuvars of Northern Malabar are known as ''Nalillakkar'' (meaning \"of the four illams\") constituted of the clans known as ''Ponillam'' (from ''pon'' meaning \"gold\"), ''Chembillam'' (from ''chembu'' meaning \"copper\"), ''Karillam'' and ''Kachillam''. The Mukkuvars of Southern Malabar have only three clans, with the absence of Ponillam, and are therefore known as ''Munillakar'' (meaning \"of the three illams\").<ref>{{Cite book|last=Singh|first=Virendra Prakash|title=Community and Caste in Tradition|date=1992|publisher=Commonwealth Publishers|year=|isbn=978-81-7169-242-2|location=|pages=33|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Saraswati|first=Baidyanath|title=Life-style and Ecology|date=1998|publisher=Indira Gandhi Centre for the Arts [and] D.K. Printworld|year=|isbn=978-81-246-0103-7|location=|pages=178|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Early history ===\nThe Mukkuvars of [[Kerala]] contribute their origin to [[Sri Lanka]] from where they migrated to Kerala. As suggested by their name, where they probably involved in diving for pealrs and conch.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"dbm1982p59\" />\n\n== References ==\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|A maritime Malayali caste found chiefly on the Malabar coast of India}}\n{{Infobox caste|caste_name=Mukkuvar|languages=[[Malayalam language|Malayalam]]|religions=[[Hinduism]], [[Christianity]], [[Islam]]|related=[[Sri Lankan Mukkuvar]], [[Mogaveera]]|subdivisions=<ref>{{Cite book|last=Singh|first=Virendra Prakash|title=Community and Caste in Tradition|date=1992|publisher=Commonwealth Publishers|year=|isbn=978-81-7169-242-2|location=|pages=33|language=en}}</ref>\n{{unbulleted list\n | Northern division: Nalillakkar \u2013 Ponillam, Chembillam, Karillam, Kachillam\n | Southern division: Munillakkar \u2013 Chembillam, Karillam, Kachillam\n  }}}}\n'''Mukkuvar''' is a [[Malayali]] [[caste]] found in the [[India|Indian]] state of [[Kerala]]. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Ram|first=Kalpana|title=Mukkuvar Women: Gender, Hegemony, and Capitalist Transformation in a South Indian Fishing Community|date=1992|publisher=Kali for Women|year=|isbn=978-81-85107-46-2|location=|pages=2|language=en}}</ref> They are mostly found on the littoral regions of the [[Malabar Coast]] and are traditionally occupied in [[fishing]] and [[seafaring]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Ramaiah|first=T. G.|title=Role of Exclusive Credit Linkage Programme for Occupational Dynamics Among Fisherwomen: A Study in Andhra Pradesh and Tamil Nadu States|date=2013|publisher=National Institute of Rural Development, Ministry of Rural Development, Government of India|year=|isbn=978-81-85542-89-8|location=|pages=14|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe caste name proposes several etymology theories. One view holds that the name ''Mukkuvar'' is derived from the [[Dravidian languages|Dravidian]] term ''muluku'' or ''mukku'' meaning \"to dive\", suggesting their traditional occupation in diving for [[Pearl|pearls]] and [[seashell]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=McGilvray|first=Dennis B.|title=Tamils and Moors: caste and matriclan structure in eastern Sri Lanka|date=1974|publisher=University of Chicago|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=23\u201325|language=en}}</ref> Other titles used by the community are ''Kukankulam, Murkukan'' and ''Mukkiyar''.<ref name=\"dbm1982p64\">{{Cite book|last=McGilvray|first=Dennis B.|title=Crucible of Conflict: Tamil and Muslim Society on the East Coast of Sri Lanka|publisher=Duke University Press|year=2008|isbn=978-0822389187|location=|page=60, 61, 64, 77|pages=|authorlink=Dennis B. McGilvray}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Holmes|first=Walter Robert|title=Jaffna, Sri Lanka 1980|date=1980|publisher=Christian Institute for the Study of Religion and Society of Jaffna College|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=219}}</ref> Their titles Kukankulam (Kukan clan) and Murkukan (foremost Kukan) are literary references to ''Kukan,'' the mariner who ferried Hindu god [[Rama]] across [[Ganges]] from [[Ayodhya]] whose descendant they claim.<ref name=\"dbm1982p59\">{{Cite book|last=McGilvray|first=Dennis B.|title=Caste Ideology and Interaction|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1982|isbn=9780521241458|location=|page=59, 60, 68|pages=}}</ref>\n\nThe Mukkuvars are divided into [[Exogamy|exogamous]] clans known as ''llam'' meaning \"house\". The Mukkuvars of Northern Malabar are are known as ''Nalillakkar'' (meaning \"of the four illams\") constituted of the clans known as ''Ponillam'' (from ''pon'' meaning \"gold\"), ''Chembillam'' (from ''chembu'' meaning \"copper\"), ''Karillam'' and ''Kachillam''. The Mukkuvars of Southern Malabar have only three clans, with the absence of Ponillam, and are therefore known as ''Munillakar'' (meaning \"of the three illams\").<ref>{{Cite book|last=Singh|first=Virendra Prakash|title=Community and Caste in Tradition|date=1992|publisher=Commonwealth Publishers|year=|isbn=978-81-7169-242-2|location=|pages=33|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Saraswati|first=Baidyanath|title=Life-style and Ecology|date=1998|publisher=Indira Gandhi Centre for the Arts [and] D.K. Printworld|year=|isbn=978-81-246-0103-7|location=|pages=178|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Early history ===\nThe Mukkuvars of [[Kerala]] contribute their origin to [[Sri Lanka]] from where they migrated to Kerala. As suggested by their name, where they probably involved in diving for pealrs and conch.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"dbm1982p59\" />\n\n== References ==\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kerala_Mukkuvar"}
{"title_page": "A Soldier's Heart", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = A Soldier's Heart\n| image                    = ASoldiersHeartTitleCard.jpg\n| caption                  = Title card\n| genre                    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Drama (film and television)|Drama]]\n* [[Action film|Action]]\n* [[Military fiction]]\n}}\n| creator                  = [[Charo Santos-Concio]]\n| developer                = \n| writer                   = {{Plainlist|\n* Jerry B. Gracio\n* [[Carlo Katigbak]]\n* Chie Floresca\n* Chino Nicanor\n* April L. Jalandra\n}}\n| director                 = Richard V. Somes\n| creative_director        = \n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Gerald Anderson]]\n* [[Carlo Aquino]]\n* [[Vin Abrenica]]\n* [[Elmo Magalona]]\n* [[Jerome Ponce]]\n* [[Yves Flores]]\n* [[Nash Aguas]]\n* [[Sue Ramirez]]\n}}\n| opentheme          = \n| composer           = \n| country            = [[Philippines]]\n| language           = [[Filipino language|Filipino]]\n| num_seasons        = 1<!--Only increment as a new season premieres, per the documentation of the template!-->\n| num_episodes       = 40<!--As of March 13, 2020--><!--Please do not update the episode count daily, the episodes will be updated WEEKLY so that only a single edit is necessary-->\n| list_episodes      = List of A Soldier's Heart episodes\n| executive_producer = Marielle de Guzman-Navarro\n| producer           = \n| cinematography     = \n| editor             = {{ubl|Joy C. Buenaventura|Dennis A. Salgado}}\n| runtime            = \n| location           = [[Philippines]]\n| company            = RCD Narratives\n| distributor        = \n| network            = [[ABS-CBN (TV network)|ABS-CBN]]\n| picture_format     = [[480i]] ([[SDTV]]) <br> [[1080i]] ([[HDTV]])\n| first_aired        = {{Start date|2020|1|20}}\n| last_aired         = {{End date|2020|3|13}} ''({{small|on-hiatus}})''\n| preceded_by        = \n| related            = \n| website            = http://asoldiersheart.abs-cbn.com/\n}}\n\n'''''A Soldier's Heart''''' is a 2020 [[Philippine television drama|Philippine drama]] [[television series]] starring [[Gerald Anderson]], [[Carlo Aquino]], [[Vin Abrenica]], [[Elmo Magalona]], [[Jerome Ponce]], [[Yves Flores]], [[Nash Aguas]] and [[Sue Ramirez]]. The series premiered on [[ABS-CBN (TV network)|ABS-CBN]]'s ''Primetime Bida'' evening block and worldwide via [[The Filipino Channel]] on January 20, 2020, replacing ''[[The Killer Bride]]''.<!-- Do not add grammar anymore --><!-- No reference is needed here if the content is already sourced in the body of the article per WP:CITELEAD! -->\n\n==Synopsis==\nThe series primarily focuses on the soldiers of the [[4th Infantry Division (Philippines)|4th Infantry Division]] of the [[Philippine Army]] and their actions during combat. Through multiple perspectives, the story focuses on these soldiers, mainly: Alex Marasigan ([[Gerald Anderson]]), an IT expert who quits his desk job and joins because just like his brother, he wants to serve the country, Abraham \"Abe\" Kamlun ([[Carlo Aquino]]), a Tausug Muslim man, who, despite his family's opposition of the move, joins the Army nonetheless, and Michael Mendoza ([[Nash Aguas]]), a boy who joins the Army to provide for his family. \n\nThe series also focuses on their [[Moro]] [[separatist]] adversaries, led by Saal Alhuraji ([[Sid Lucero]]), also known by his [[nom de guerre]] ''Abdul Waajid'', who seeks to avenge his father who was killed by the military.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n{{multiple image\n|direction = vertical\n|align = right\n|image1 = Gerald Anderson by Ronn Tan, April 2010.png\n|caption1 = Gerald Anderson portrays Alex Marasigan.\n|width1 = 150\n|image2 = Elmo Magalona.jpg\n|caption2 = Elmo Magalona portrays Jethro Mondejar.\n|width2 = 150\n|image3 = Yves Flores.jpg\n|caption3 = Yves Flores portrays Benjie Arguelles.\n|width3 = 150\n|image4 = Nash-Aguas.jpg\n|caption4 = Nash Aguas portrays Michael Mendoza.\n|width4 = 150\n|image5 = Ariel solo.jpg\n|caption5 = Ariel Rivera portrays Victor Mondejar.\n|width5 = 150\n}}\n===Main===\n* [[Gerald Anderson]]<ref name=\"Cast\">{{cite web|url=https://starcinema.abs-cbn.com/2019/7/24/news/cast-ng-a-soldiers-heart-ipinakilala-na-51186|title=Cast ng ''A Soldier's Heart'', ipinakilala na!|website=ABS-CBN Entertainment|date=July 24, 2019|accessdate=November 5, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Training\">{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/pilipino-star-ngayon/showbiz/2019/08/11/1942453/sumabak-sa-scout-ranger-training-gerald-kumain-na-nakadapa-habang-nasa-putikan|title=Sumabak sa Scout Ranger training, Gerald kumain na nakadapa habang nasa putikan!|website=Philippine Star|date=August 11, 2019|accessdate=November 5, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Brotherhood\">{{cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DA83eI2g0ec|title=A Soldier's Heart: The Brotherhood Teaser|website=ABS-CBN Entertainment|date=January 9, 2020|accessdate=January 20, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ASHCast\">{{cite web|url=https://www.abs-cbn.com/newsroom/news-releases/2020/1/17/a-soldiers-heart-shows-sacrifice-loyal-brother?lang=en|title=''A Soldier's Heart'' shows sacrifice, loyal brotherhood of soldiers|work=ABS-CBN Corporate|date=January 17, 2020|accessdate=January 20, 2020}}</ref> as Pvt. Alexander \"Alex\" Marasigan / Hakeem Alhuraji\n* [[Carlo Aquino]]<ref name=\"Cast\"/><ref name=\"Brotherhood\"/><ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Pvt. Abraham \"Abe\" Kamlun\n* [[Vin Abrenica]]<ref name=\"Cast\"/><ref name=\"Brotherhood\"/><ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as 1st Lt. Elmer Marasigan\n* [[Elmo Magalona]]<ref name=\"Cast\"/><ref name=\"Brotherhood\"/><ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as 1st Lt. Jethro Mondejar\n* [[Jerome Ponce]]<ref name=\"Cast\"/><ref name=\"Brotherhood\"/><ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Pvt. Philip \"Phil\" Panganiban\n* [[Yves Flores]]<ref name=\"Cast\"/><ref name=\"Brotherhood\"/><ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Pvt. Benjamin \"Benjie\" Arguelles\n* [[Nash Aguas]]<ref name=\"Cast\"/><ref name=\"Brotherhood\"/><ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Pvt. Michael \"Striker\" Mendoza\n* [[Sue Ramirez]]<ref name=\"Brotherhood\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://showbizchika.net/sue-ramirez-and-gerald-anderson-gear-up-for-upcoming-series-a-soldiers-heart/|title=Sue Ramirez and Gerald Anderson gear up for upcoming series ''A Soldier's Heart''|website=Showbiz Chika}}</ref><ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as 2nd Lt. Lourdes \"Lourd\" Bacalso\n\n===Supporting===\n* [[Sid Lucero]]<ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Saal Alhuraji/Abdul Waajid\n* [[Ariel Rivera]]<ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as BGen. Victor C. Mondejar\n* [[Rommel Padilla]]<ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as BGen. Dante G. Marasigan\n* [[Irma Adlawan]]<ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Yasmin Alhuraji/Amara\n* [[Raymond Bagatsing]]<ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Col. Melicio Adriano\n* [[Mickey Ferriols]]<ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Minda Marasigan\n* [[Mon Confiado]]<ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Maj. Raul R. Lucente\n* [[Nikki Valdez]]<ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Fatima Alhuraji\n* [[Matt Evans]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/07/31/19/with-star-magic-return-matt-evans-feels-his-prayers-were-answered|title=With Star Magic return, Matt Evans feels his prayers were answered|website=ABS-CBN News|date=July 31, 2019|accessdate=November 10, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Rasheed Amad\n* Nor Domingo<ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Col. Virgilio I. Fontiveros\n* Angelo Ilagan as Pvt. Gregorio \"Gorio\" Salud\n* Isay Alvarez<ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Maysam Kamlun\n* Jun Hidalgo as Ahmed Kamlun\n* [[Claire Ruiz]] as Grace Alfonso \n* Royce Cabrera as Pvt. Andy Alfonso \n;Introducing\n* Charlie Dizon as Isabel Gezali<!--stiop adding two spelling for Isabel. It doesn't make sense for one to be a first name and the other a nickname when they are uttered the same way-->\n* Patrick Quiroz<ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Amir Majul\n\n===Guests===\n* Kiko Matos as Akir \n* Zeppi Borromeo as Nassir \n* [[Roxanne Guinoo]] as Mrs. Arguelles \n* [[Pen Medina]] as Mr. Panganiban\n* Ruby Ruiz \n* John Vincent Servilla as Chino Villaverde\n* Kokoy de Jesus\n* Lorenzo Martinez\n* [[Simon Ibarra]]\n* [[Mercedes Cabral]]\n* Bing Davao as [[Secretary of National Defense (Philippines)|Defense Secretary]]\n* [[Mari Kaimo]] as [[President of the Philippines|President]]\n* Richard Quan as Gov. Amer Gezali\n* Sammie Rimando as Chloe Gezali\n* Jerry O'Hara as \n* Levi Ignacio as Congressman Shakiri\n* Marco Masa as young Saal\n* Vash Paras as young Hakeem/Alex\n* [[Ketchup Eusebio]]<ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Cpl. Olan Arguelles\n* [[Lito Pimentel]] as Yosef Alhuraji\n* [[Boom Labrusca]]\n* Arnold Reyes as Pinong\n* Teroy de Guzman as Abdul Waajid\n* Minco Fabregas as Jamal\n\n==Broadcast==\nThe series airs on ABS-CBN's ''Primetime Bida'' evening block and worldwide on The Filipino Channel at 9:20 PM (PST).\n\nOn March 16, 2020, the show was put on hiatus due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines|2019-20 Wuhan coronavirus pandemic]]. It's timeslot was temporarily filled by ''[[Wildflower (TV series)|Wildflower]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pep.ph/guide/tv/150320/abs-cbn-wildflower-gma-7-my-husband-lover-new-primetime-line-up-a724-20200323|title=ABS-CBN's Wildflower goes head-to-head with GMA-7's My Husband's Lover in new primetime line-up|last=Anarcon|first=James Patrick|publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal|PEP]]|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> and ''[[iWant#List of original programs|iWant Originals]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/03/14/20/read-abs-cbn-statement-on-special-primetime-programming-amid-metro-manila-quarantine|title=READ: ABS-CBN statement on special primetime programming amid Metro Manila quarantine|publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]]|date=March 14, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> until May 2020, when the quarantine is scheduled to end.\n\n==Reception==\n===Ratings===\n{{Infobox Kantar rating\n| timeslot        = 9:15PM\n| pilot_rating    = 19.8%\n| pilot_date      = {{dts|2020|1|20}}\n| pilot_ref       = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abs-cbn.com/newsroom/tv-ratings/2020/1/22/national-tv-ratings-january-20-21-2020?lang=en|title=National TV Ratings (January 20\u201321, 2020)|work=ABS-CBN Corporate|date=January 22, 2020|accessdate=January 22, 2020}}</ref>\n| finale_rating   = TBD\n| finale_date     = \n| finale_ref      =\n| peak_rating     = TBD <!-- If you add a high rating when the series ends. -->\n| peak_date       =\n| peak_ref        =\n| average_rating  = TBD\n| average_ref     =\n}}\n\n===Controversies===\n====Depiction of Butuan City====\nThe show came under fire early in the show's run for its perceived \"unrealistic\" and \"offensive\" depiction of [[Butuan City]].<ref name=\"PilotBlues\">{{cite news|url=https://amp.rappler.com/entertainment/news/250004-a-soldiers-heart-shows-unreal-depiction-butuan-city-says-agusan-congressman|title=A Soldier\u2019s Heart\u2019 shows \u2018unreal depiction\u2019 of Butuan City, says Agusan del Norte rep|publisher=[[Rappler]]|date=January 23, 2020|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> The scene in question was from the show's pilot episode showing the bombing of a market in the city.<ref name=\"PilotBlues\"/> In a statement, Agusan del Norte 1st District Representative [[Lawrence Fortun]]  asked ABS-CBN \u201cto immediately air an appropriate disclaimer, review and reconsider the content and story elements of the teleserye in order not to further besmirch the reputation of our historic city.\u201d<ref name=\"PilotBlues\"/>\n\nABS-CBN, for its part, apologized on January 23, 2020. Its statement read:  \u201cABS-CBN would like to apologize to Agusan Del Norte Rep. Lawrence Fortun and the people of Butuan City if the scenes in the TV series \u2018A Soldier\u2019s Heart\u2019 have offended them. While the incident portrayed in the series was fictitious, there was mention of the city name.\u201d\n\n\u201cWe would like to assure them that there was no deliberate intention to portray Butuan City negatively in the show. We acknowledge that Butuan is one of the most beautiful and peaceful cities in the country,\u201d it added.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/amp/entertainment/01/23/20/abs-cbn-sorry-after-butuan-solon-complains-against-a-soldiers-heart|title=ABS-CBN sorry after Butuan solon complains against 'A Soldier\u2019s Heart'|publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]]|date=January 23, 2020|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn January 24, 2020, ABS-CBN executives headed by Cory Vidanes and Laurenti Dyogi met with Fortun to further clear the issue. After said meeting, Fortun noted that aside from airing specific disclaimers, ABS-CBN has removed all production elements, scenes, and references that may be offensive to Butuan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pep.ph/guide/tv/148970/abs-cbn-removes-offensive-butuan-scenes-from-a-soldier-s-heart-a771-20200127|title=ABS-CBN removes \"offensive\" Butuan scenes from A Soldier's Heart|publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal|PEP]]|first=Mari-An|last=Santos|date=January 26, 2020|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of programs broadcast by ABS-CBN]]\n* [[List of ABS-CBN drama series]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://asoldiersheart.abs-cbn.com/}}\n\n{{ABS-CBN (current and upcoming original programming)}}\n{{ABS-CBN drama series}}\n\n[[Category:ABS-CBN drama series]]\n[[Category:Philippine drama television series]]\n[[Category:Philippine military television series]]\n[[Category:2020 Philippine television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Filipino-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in the Philippines]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = A Soldier's Heart\n| image                    = ASoldiersHeartTitleCard.jpg\n| caption                  = Title card\n| genre                    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Drama (film and television)|Drama]]\n* [[Action film|Action]]\n* [[Military fiction]]\n}}\n| creator                  = [[Charo Santos-Concio]]\n| developer                = \n| writer                   = {{Plainlist|\n* Jerry B. Gracio\n* [[Carlo Katigbak]]\n* Chie Floresca\n* Chino Nicanor\n* April L. Jalandra\n}}\n| director                 = Richard V. Somes\n| creative_director        = \n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Gerald Anderson]]\n* [[Carlo Aquino]]\n* [[Vin Abrenica]]\n* [[Elmo Magalona]]\n* [[Jerome Ponce]]\n* [[Yves Flores]]\n* [[Nash Aguas]]\n* [[Sue Ramirez]]\n}}\n| opentheme          = \n| composer           = \n| country            = [[Philippines]]\n| language           = [[Filipino language|Filipino]]\n| num_seasons        = 1<!--Only increment as a new season premieres, per the documentation of the template!-->\n| num_episodes       = 40<!--As of March 13, 2020--><!--Please do not update the episode count daily, the episodes will be updated WEEKLY so that only a single edit is necessary-->\n| list_episodes      = List of A Soldier's Heart episodes\n| executive_producer = Marielle de Guzman-Navarro\n| producer           = \n| cinematography     = \n| editor             = {{ubl|Joy C. Buenaventura|Dennis A. Salgado}}\n| runtime            = \n| location           = [[Philippines]]\n| company            = RCD Narratives\n| distributor        = \n| network            = [[ABS-CBN (TV network)|ABS-CBN]]\n| picture_format     = [[480i]] ([[SDTV]]) <br> [[1080i]] ([[HDTV]])\n| first_aired        = {{Start date|2020|1|20}}\n| last_aired         = {{End date|2020|3|13}} ''({{small|on-hiatus}})''\n| preceded_by        = \n| related            = \n| website            = http://asoldiersheart.abs-cbn.com/\n}}\n\n'''''A Soldier's Heart''''' is a 2020 [[Philippine television drama|Philippine drama]] [[television series]] starring [[Gerald Anderson]], [[Carlo Aquino]], [[Vin Abrenica]], [[Elmo Magalona]], [[Jerome Ponce]], [[Yves Flores]], [[Nash Aguas]] and [[Sue Ramirez]]. The series premiered on [[ABS-CBN (TV network)|ABS-CBN]]'s ''Primetime Bida'' evening block and worldwide via [[The Filipino Channel]] on January 20, 2020, replacing ''[[The Killer Bride]]''.<!-- Do not add grammar anymore --><!-- No reference is needed here if the content is already sourced in the body of the article per WP:CITELEAD! -->\n\n==Synopsis==\nThe series primarily focuses on the soldiers of the [[4th Infantry Division (Philippines)|4th Infantry Division]] of the [[Philippine Army]] and their actions during combat. Through multiple perspectives, the story focuses on these soldiers, mainly: Alex Marasigan ([[Gerald Anderson]]), an IT expert who quits his desk job and joins because just like his brother, he wants to serve the country, Abraham \"Abe\" Kamlun ([[Carlo Aquino]]), a Tausug Muslim man, who, despite his family's opposition of the move, joins the Army nonetheless, and Michael Mendoza ([[Nash Aguas]]), a boy who joins the Army to provide for his family. \n\nThe series also focuses on their [[Moro]] [[separatist]] adversaries, led by Saal Alhuraji ([[Sid Lucero]]), also known by his [[nom de guerre]] ''Abdul Waajid'', who seeks to avenge his father who was killed by the military.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n{{multiple image\n|direction = vertical\n|align = right\n|image1 = Gerald Anderson by Ronn Tan, April 2010.png\n|caption1 = Gerald Anderson portrays Alex Marasigan.\n|width1 = 150\n|image2 = Elmo Magalona.jpg\n|caption2 = Elmo Magalona portrays Jethro Mondejar.\n|width2 = 150\n|image3 = Yves Flores.jpg\n|caption3 = Yves Flores portrays Benjie Arguelles.\n|width3 = 150\n|image4 = Nash-Aguas.jpg\n|caption4 = Nash Aguas portrays Michael Mendoza.\n|width4 = 150\n|image5 = Ariel solo.jpg\n|caption5 = Ariel Rivera portrays Victor Mondejar.\n|width5 = 150\n}}\n===Main===\n* [[Gerald Anderson]]<ref name=\"Cast\">{{cite web|url=https://starcinema.abs-cbn.com/2019/7/24/news/cast-ng-a-soldiers-heart-ipinakilala-na-51186|title=Cast ng ''A Soldier's Heart'', ipinakilala na!|website=ABS-CBN Entertainment|date=July 24, 2019|accessdate=November 5, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Training\">{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/pilipino-star-ngayon/showbiz/2019/08/11/1942453/sumabak-sa-scout-ranger-training-gerald-kumain-na-nakadapa-habang-nasa-putikan|title=Sumabak sa Scout Ranger training, Gerald kumain na nakadapa habang nasa putikan!|website=Philippine Star|date=August 11, 2019|accessdate=November 5, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Brotherhood\">{{cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DA83eI2g0ec|title=A Soldier's Heart: The Brotherhood Teaser|website=ABS-CBN Entertainment|date=January 9, 2020|accessdate=January 20, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ASHCast\">{{cite web|url=https://www.abs-cbn.com/newsroom/news-releases/2020/1/17/a-soldiers-heart-shows-sacrifice-loyal-brother?lang=en|title=''A Soldier's Heart'' shows sacrifice, loyal brotherhood of soldiers|work=ABS-CBN Corporate|date=January 17, 2020|accessdate=January 20, 2020}}</ref> as Pvt. Alexander \"Alex\" Marasigan / Hakeem Alhuraji\n* [[Carlo Aquino]]<ref name=\"Cast\"/><ref name=\"Brotherhood\"/><ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Pvt. Abraham \"Abe\" Kamlun\n* [[Vin Abrenica]]<ref name=\"Cast\"/><ref name=\"Brotherhood\"/><ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as 1st Lt. Elmer Marasigan\n* [[Elmo Magalona]]<ref name=\"Cast\"/><ref name=\"Brotherhood\"/><ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as 1st Lt. Jethro Mondejar\n* [[Jerome Ponce]]<ref name=\"Cast\"/><ref name=\"Brotherhood\"/><ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Pvt. Philip \"Phil\" Panganiban\n* [[Yves Flores]]<ref name=\"Cast\"/><ref name=\"Brotherhood\"/><ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Pvt. Benjamin \"Benjie\" Arguelles\n* [[Nash Aguas]]<ref name=\"Cast\"/><ref name=\"Brotherhood\"/><ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Pvt. Michael \"Striker\" Mendoza\n* [[Sue Ramirez]]<ref name=\"Brotherhood\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://showbizchika.net/sue-ramirez-and-gerald-anderson-gear-up-for-upcoming-series-a-soldiers-heart/|title=Sue Ramirez and Gerald Anderson gear up for upcoming series ''A Soldier's Heart''|website=Showbiz Chika}}</ref><ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as 2nd Lt. Lourdes \"Lourd\" Bacalso\n\n===Supporting===\n* [[Sid Lucero]]<ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Saal Alhuraji/Abdul Waajid\n* [[Ariel Rivera]]<ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as BGen. Victor C. Mondejar\n* [[Rommel Padilla]]<ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as BGen. Dante G. Marasigan\n* [[Irma Adlawan]]<ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Yasmin Alhuraji/Amara\n* [[Raymond Bagatsing]]<ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Col. Melicio Adriano\n* [[Mickey Ferriols]]<ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Minda Marasigan\n* [[Mon Confiado]]<ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Maj. Raul R. Lucente\n* [[Nikki Valdez]]<ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Fatima Alhuraji\n* [[Matt Evans]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/07/31/19/with-star-magic-return-matt-evans-feels-his-prayers-were-answered|title=With Star Magic return, Matt Evans feels his prayers were answered|website=ABS-CBN News|date=July 31, 2019|accessdate=November 10, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Rasheed Amad\n* Nor Domingo<ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Col. Virgilio I. Fontiveros\n* Angelo Ilagan as Pvt. Gregorio \"Gorio\" Salud\n* Isay Alvarez<ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Maysam Kamlun\n* Jun Hidalgo as Ahmed Kamlun\n* [[Claire Ruiz]] as Grace Alfonso \n* Royce Cabrera as Pvt. Andy Alfonso \n;Introducing\n* Charlie Dizon as Isabel Gezali<!--stiop adding two spelling for Isabel. It doesn't make sense for one to be a first name and the other a nickname when they are uttered the same way-->\n* Patrick Quiroz<ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Amir Majul\n\n===Guests===\n* Kiko Matos as Akir \n* Zeppi Borromeo as Nassir \n* [[Roxanne Guinoo]] as Mrs. Arguelles \n* [[Pen Medina]] as Mr. Panganiban\n* Ruby Ruiz \n* John Vincent Servilla as Chino Villaverde\n* Kokoy de Jesus\n* Lorenzo Martinez\n* [[Simon Ibarra]]\n* [[Mercedes Cabral]]\n* Bing Davao as [[Secretary of National Defense (Philippines)|Defense Secretary]]\n* [[Mari Kaimo]] as [[President of the Philippines|President]]\n* Richard Quan as Gov. Amer Gezali\n* Sammie Rimando as Chloe Gezali\n* Jerry O'Hara as \n* Levi Ignacio as Congressman Shakiri\n* Marco Masa as young Saal\n* Vash Paras as young Hakeem/Alex\n* [[Ketchup Eusebio]]<ref name=\"ASHCast\"/> as Cpl. Olan Arguelles\n* [[Lito Pimentel]] as Yosef Alhuraji\n* [[Boom Labrusca]]\n* Arnold Reyes as Pinong\n* Teroy de Guzman as Abdul Waajid\n* Minco Fabregas as Jamal\n\n==Broadcast==\nThe series airs on ABS-CBN's ''Primetime Bida'' evening block and worldwide on The Filipino Channel at 9:20 PM (PST).\n\nOn March 16, 2020, the show was put on hiatus due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines|2019-20 Wuhan coronavirus pandemic]]. It's timeslot was temporarily filled by ''[[Wildflower (TV series)|Wildflower]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pep.ph/guide/tv/150320/abs-cbn-wildflower-gma-7-my-husband-lover-new-primetime-line-up-a724-20200323|title=ABS-CBN's Wildflower goes head-to-head with GMA-7's My Husband's Lover in new primetime line-up|last=Anarcon|first=James Patrick|publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal|PEP]]|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> and ''[[iWant#List of original programs|iWant Originals]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/03/14/20/read-abs-cbn-statement-on-special-primetime-programming-amid-metro-manila-quarantine|title=READ: ABS-CBN statement on special primetime programming amid Metro Manila quarantine|publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]]|date=March 14, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> until May 2020, when the quarantine is scheduled to end.\n\n==Reception==\n===Ratings===\n{{Infobox Kantar rating\n| timeslot        = 9:15PM\n| pilot_rating    = 19.8%\n| pilot_date      = {{dts|2020|1|20}}\n| pilot_ref       = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abs-cbn.com/newsroom/tv-ratings/2020/1/22/national-tv-ratings-january-20-21-2020?lang=en|title=National TV Ratings (January 20\u201321, 2020)|work=ABS-CBN Corporate|date=January 22, 2020|accessdate=January 22, 2020}}</ref>\n| finale_rating   = TBD\n| finale_date     = \n| finale_ref      =\n| peak_rating     = TBD <!-- If you add a high rating when the series ends. -->\n| peak_date       =\n| peak_ref        =\n| average_rating  = TBD\n| average_ref     =\n}}\n\n===Controversies===\n====Depiction of Butuan City====\nThe show came under fire early in the show's run for its percieved \"unrealistic\" and \"offensive\" depiction of [[Butuan City]].<ref name=\"PilotBlues\">{{cite news|url=https://amp.rappler.com/entertainment/news/250004-a-soldiers-heart-shows-unreal-depiction-butuan-city-says-agusan-congressman|title=A Soldier\u2019s Heart\u2019 shows \u2018unreal depiction\u2019 of Butuan City, says Agusan del Norte rep|publisher=[[Rappler]]|date=January 23, 2020|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> The scene in question was from the show's pilot episode showing the bombing of a market in the city.<ref name=\"PilotBlues\"/> In a statement, Agusan del Norte 1st District Representative [[Lawrence Fortun]]  asked ABS-CBN \u201cto immediately air an appropriate disclaimer, review and reconsider the content and story elements of the teleserye in order not to further besmirch the reputation of our historic city.\u201d<ref name=\"PilotBlues\"/>\n\nABS-CBN, for its part, apologized on January 23, 2020. Its statement read:  \u201cABS-CBN would like to apologize to Agusan Del Norte Rep. Lawrence Fortun and the people of Butuan City if the scenes in the TV series \u2018A Soldier\u2019s Heart\u2019 have offended them. While the incident portrayed in the series was fictitious, there was mention of the city name.\u201d\n\n\u201cWe would like to assure them that there was no deliberate intention to portray Butuan City negatively in the show. We acknowledge that Butuan is one of the most beautiful and peaceful cities in the country,\u201d it added.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/amp/entertainment/01/23/20/abs-cbn-sorry-after-butuan-solon-complains-against-a-soldiers-heart|title=ABS-CBN sorry after Butuan solon complains against 'A Soldier\u2019s Heart'|publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]]|date=January 23, 2020|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn January 24, 2020, ABS-CBN executives headed by Cory Vidanes and Laurenti Dyogi met with Fortun to further clear the issue. After said meeting, Fortun noted that aside from airing specific disclaimers, ABS-CBN has removed all production elements, scenes, and references that may be offensive to Butuan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pep.ph/guide/tv/148970/abs-cbn-removes-offensive-butuan-scenes-from-a-soldier-s-heart-a771-20200127|title=ABS-CBN removes \"offensive\" Butuan scenes from A Soldier's Heart|publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal|PEP]]|first=Mari-An|last=Santos|date=January 26, 2020|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of programs broadcast by ABS-CBN]]\n* [[List of ABS-CBN drama series]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://asoldiersheart.abs-cbn.com/}}\n\n{{ABS-CBN (current and upcoming original programming)}}\n{{ABS-CBN drama series}}\n\n[[Category:ABS-CBN drama series]]\n[[Category:Philippine drama television series]]\n[[Category:Philippine military television series]]\n[[Category:2020 Philippine television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Filipino-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in the Philippines]]\n", "name_user": "Toweli", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Soldier%27s_Heart"}
{"title_page": "By the Way (Red Hot Chili Peppers song)", "text_new": "{{short description|2002 single by Red Hot Chili Peppers}}\n{{refimprove|date=September 2011}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name = By the Way\n| cover = bythewaysingle.jpg\n| alt =\n| type = single\n| artist = [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]]\n| album = [[By the Way]]\n| B-side     = {{ubl|\"Time\"|\"Teenager in Love\"}}\n| released   = June 10, 2002\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7\" vinyl]], [[Compact Disc|CD]]\n| recorded   = \n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Funk rock]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rockhall.com/blog/post/7404_10-essential-red-hot-chili-peppers-songs/ |title=10 Essential Red Hot Chili Peppers Songs &#124; The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame and Museum |publisher=Rockhall.com |date=April 15, 2013 |accessdate=June 30, 2014}}</ref> [[alternative rock]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Michael Gallucci |url=http://diffuser.fm/2002-alt-rock-videos/ |title=Top 10 Alt-Rock Videos From 2002 |publisher=Diffuser.fm |date=March 2, 2013 |accessdate=June 30, 2014}}</ref>\n| length     = 3:37\n| label      = [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n| writer     = [[Flea (musician)|Flea]], [[John Frusciante|Frusciante]], [[Anthony Kiedis|Kiedis]], [[Chad Smith|Smith]]\n| producer   = [[Rick Rubin]]\n| prev_title = [[Road Trippin']]\n| prev_year  = 2000\n| next_title = [[The Zephyr Song]]\n| next_year  = 2002\n| misc       = \n{{External music video|{{YouTube|YXdOAUKCc0k|\"By The Way\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''By the Way'''\" is a song by American [[funk rock]] band [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]]. It's the title track and first single released from the band's eighth studio album [[By the Way|of the same name]]. The song was the band's sixth number 1 hit on the [[Alternative Songs|Modern Rock Tracks]] chart, staying at the summit for 14 weeks, tying it with \"[[Dani California]]\" as the band's second-longest stay at the top, behind only \"[[Scar Tissue]],\" which was at the top for 16 weeks. It also spent seven weeks at number 1 on the [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Mainstream Rock Tracks]] chart, the band's fourth song to top this chart. The song also reached number 2 in the UK, becoming the band's highest-peaking single there alongside \"Dani California,\" and peaked atop the Italian chart.\n\nRegarding its release, guitarist [[John Frusciante]] noted: \"It wasn't really our decision to put that song out first, but our managers thought it was an exciting song and their enthusiasm convinced us. I guess they thought that it combined the wild part of our sound with the melodic part of our sound.\"<ref name=\"kerrang\">[[Kerrang!]] Yearbook (2002), pg.25</ref> Vocalist [[Anthony Kiedis]] elaborated: \"I thought that single was an \u00fcber-bombastic assault of non-commercialism. For it to be so well-received [in the [[United Kingdom]]] was shocking to me, but thrilling at the same time.\"<ref name=\"kerrang\"/>\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video was directed by [[Jonathan Dayton and Valerie Faris]], a couple who have directed many other music videos for the band.\n\nThe video starts off with Kiedis calling for a taxi. He gets in the taxi and the cabbie (played by [[Dave Sheridan (actor)|Dave Sheridan]]) realizes he has him as his passenger. To please him, the driver puts a copy of the \"By the Way\" single into the taxi CD player, making Kiedis smile slightly. Suddenly, the cabbie begins driving out of control as he lip-syncs the song while driving rambunctiously throughout the streets of Los Angeles. After he locks the car door, an uncomfortable and apprehensive Kiedis attempts to make a call on his cell phone, but the cabbie brakes so hard that Kiedis loses grip of it. The cabbie snatches the phone and throws it out the window, then drives the car in a cloud of dust and backs up under a bridge.\n\nWhile there, the cabbie pulls out flare sticks and begins to torture Kiedis through awkward dancing while the latter finally pages bassist [[Flea (musician)|Flea]] and Frusciante (with a message reading, \"Help! Been kidnapped.\"), who are having lunch in a cafe. At first, they think it's a hoax, so they ignore the first message. When Kiedis pages them for the second time, they set out on Flea's Ford Bronco to find him with the crazy cabbie in the taxi. A wild chase and road rage ensues. Kiedis soon sees Flea and Frusciante, breaks out of the taxi window, and jumps in Flea's truck with a sigh of relief as the three escape the cabbie. At the end of the video, drummer [[Chad Smith]] flags down the taxi, with the cabbie realizing he is also a member of the band, so he lets him in and drives off with him. However, Chad is unaware that this is the same taxi man that kidnapped Kiedis and also ignores the broken glass.\n\nKiedis said of the video:\n\n{{quote|It\u2019s kidnapping\u2026 A cab driver kidnaps me and just goes haywire through the town; he\u2019s a fan, but he\u2019s kind of a [pause] obsessive, compulsive, psychologically misarranged fan, and he sees me and starts enjoying himself a little too much and my friends have to come and rescue me.<ref>The Making of: By the Way; ''[[Greatest Hits (Red Hot Chili Peppers album)|Greatest Hits]]''</ref>}}\n\nThe fast and often jerky camera angles used in the high-speed chase sequences are based on the 2000 Mexican film ''[[Amores Perros]]'' in which all the characters are linked by a car crash at the beginning of the film; before the crash is an almost identical high speed car chase sequence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1454521/red-hot-chili-peppers-new-single-about-joy-car-crashes-playing-dice/ |title=Red Hot Chili Peppers' New Single About Joy, Car Crashes, Playing Dice |publisher=MTV |date=May 23, 2002 |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==\"Waiting 4\" Peter Gelderblom remix==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Waiting 4\n| cover      = \n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Peter Gelderblom]]\n| album      =\n| released   = {{Start date|2007|07|05}} <small>(bootleg)</small><br>{{Start date|2007|12|3}} <small>(official)</small>\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Electro house]], [[electronic rock]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=15}}\n| label      = [[Data Records|Data]]\n| writer     = [[Flea (musician)|Flea]], [[John Frusciante|Frusciante]], [[Anthony Kiedis|Kiedis]], [[Chad Smith|Smith]]\n| producer   = Rene Amesz, Peter Gelderblom\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\nAn [[electro house]] remix of \"By the Way\" by [[Peter Gelderblom]] with co-production by Rene Amesz, was released on 5 July 2007, and became a popular track in clubs worldwide despite being released without the band's knowledge or approval. The song is called \"Waiting 4\", which is a prominently featured lyric in the original song. It reached #29 for one week in late November/early December 2007 in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"PGUKcharts\"/> It is included on the compilation ''Wild Weekends 04'' (2007).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Various-Wild-Weekends-Vol-4/release/6720531 |title=Wild Weekends Vol 4 (2007) |publisher=Discogs |accessdate=October 16, 2019}}</ref> It was C-listed by [[BBC Radio 1]]. A music video was made for the single. It was uploaded on Data Records' official [[YouTube]] account on November 13, 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.com/watch?v=IeNmFhIjGXE |title=Peter Gelderblom - 'Waiting 4' (Official Video) |publisher=YouTube |date=November 13, 2007 |accessdate=June 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Chart (2007)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|29|date=20071209|accessdate=October 16, 2019|refname=PGUKcharts}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKdance|2|date=20071216|accessdate=October 16, 2019}}\n|}\n\n==Live performances==\n\"By The Way\" has been performed over 600 times since 2002, making it the band's fourth most performed song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.setlist.fm/stats/red-hot-chili-peppers-13d68969.html |title=Red Hot Chili Peppers Tour Statistics |website=Setlist.fm |date= |accessdate=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n;CD single / Australia CD1\n# \"By the Way\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:35\n# \"Time\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:47\n# \"[[A Teenager in Love]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:01\n\n;CD version 2 / Australia CD2\n# \"By the Way\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:35\n# \"Search and Destroy\" (Live)&nbsp;\u2013 12:13\n# \"What Is Soul?\" (Live)&nbsp;\u2013 3:58\n\n;CD version 3\n# \"By the Way\"\n# \"Time\"\n# \"Search and Destroy\" (Live)\n\n;CD version 4 / UK CD single / Japan CD single\n# \"By the Way\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:35\n# \"Time\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:47\n# \"Teenager in Love\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:01\n# \"Search and Destroy\" (Live)&nbsp;\u2013 12:13\n\n;7\" single / Canada CD single\n# \"By the Way\"\n# \"Time\"\n\n;DVD single<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Red-Hot-Chili-Peppers-Single/dp/B00006G8KH/ref=sr_1_12?keywords=by+the+way+red+hot+chili+peppers&qid=1571782849&s=music&sr=1-12 |title=By The Way <nowiki>[DVD]</nowiki> |work=Amazon.com |accessdate=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n# \"By the Way\" (music video)&nbsp;\u2013 3:36; directed by [[Jonathan Dayton and Valerie Faris]]\n# \"Obsessive, Compulsive, Psychologically, Misarranged Cabdriver/Fan (aka the making of \"By the Way\")\"&nbsp;\u2013 13:45; directed by Byron Shaw and Bart Lipton for Brown & Serve\n# \"By the Way\" (Performance Version)&nbsp;\u2013 3:36\n\n==Personnel==\n===Red Hot Chili Peppers===\n*Anthony Kiedis \u2013 lead vocals\n*John Frusciante \u2013 guitar, backing vocals\n*Flea \u2013 bass\n*Chad Smith \u2013 drums, tambourine\n<!-- wind machine also audible !-->\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2002)\n!scope=\"col\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|6|song=By the Way|artist=Red Hot Chili Peppers|rowheader=true|accessdate=January 24, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|7|song=