ttp://www.ukchartsplus.co.uk/ChartsPlusYE2002.pdf|title=The Official UK Singles Chart 2002|work=[[UKChartsPlus]]|format=PDF|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|92\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks (''Billboard'')<ref name=\"Billboard Year End 2002\">{{cite book|title=Billboard|date=December 28, 2002|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|pages=YE-48, YE-78, YE-96|edition=114|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=RA0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA52&lpg=PA52&dq=billboard+hot+100+year+end+2002&source=bl&ots=GsBxXRg5Ej&sig=bYtZU5xOxdcCQeKKF1tiNzqnMus&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjkxq7YsPzPAhWm5oMKHTRXD784ChDoAQg0MAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=November 8, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161028155030/https://books.google.ca/books?id=RA0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA52&lpg=PA52&dq=billboard+hot+100+year+end+2002&source=bl&ots=GsBxXRg5Ej&sig=bYtZU5xOxdcCQeKKF1tiNzqnMus&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjkxq7YsPzPAhWm5oMKHTRXD784ChDoAQg0MAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false|archive-date=2016-10-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|10\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US Hot Modern Rock Tracks (''Billboard'')<ref name=\"Billboard Year End 2002\"/>\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Australia|relyear=2002|certyear=2002|award=Gold|artist=Red Hot Chili Peppers|title=By the Way|type=single|accessdate=October 24, 2016}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Italy|relyear=2002|award=Gold|artist=Red Hot Chili Peppers|title=By the Way|type=single|accessdate=January 29, 2018}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|relyear=2002|award=Platinum|artist=Red Hot Chili Peppers|title=By the Way|type=single|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|relyear=2002|certyear=2012|award=Platinum|number=2|artist=Red Hot Chili Peppers|title=By the Way|type=single|accessdate=October 24, 2016}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|streaming=true}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.metrolyrics.com/by-the-way-lyrics-red-hot-chili-peppers.html By the Way] at [[MetroLyrics]]\n\n{{Red Hot Chili Peppers}}\n{{Red Hot Chili Peppers singles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:By the Way}}\n[[Category:2002 singles]]\n[[Category:Red Hot Chili Peppers songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Flea (musician)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by John Frusciante]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Anthony Kiedis]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Chad Smith]]\n[[Category:Billboard Mainstream Rock number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Alternative Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Italy]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Rick Rubin]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Jonathan Dayton and Valerie Faris]]\n[[Category:2002 songs]]\n[[Category:Warner Records singles]]\n[[Category:Data Records singles]]\n", "name_user": "Jamchip", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCertifications", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/By_the_Way_(Red_Hot_Chili_Peppers_song)"}
{"title_page": "Gerry Goldstein", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=April 2018}}\n\n'''Gerald \"Gerry\" Harris Goldstein''' is a criminal defense [[Lawyer|attorney]] in [[San Antonio, Texas]], best known for his civil rights and drug-charge defenses. He is currently a partner of [https://www.goldsteinhilley.com/ Goldstein & Orr] and is Board Certified by the [[State Bar of Texas]] in [[Criminal Law]] and [[Criminal Appellate Law]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nGoldstein was born in Santa Maria, California in 1944.  At the time, his father, Eli Goldstein, was a lawyer working for the Judge Advocate General's Corps (JAG) at the Army Air Force Base in Santa Maria. His parents later moved to [[San Antonio, Texas]], where Goldstein grew up.<ref name=Gordon>Gordon, Stephen H. [http://c.ymcdn.com/sites/www.sanantoniobar.org/resource/collection/A8517B98-12D1-4287-8640-E4709DC69A36/MarApr2013SAL.pdf \u201cGerry Goldstein, for the Defense.\u201d] San Antonio Lawyer. March\u2013April 2013. Pg. 5</ref>  Goldstein has a bachelor's degree in art from [[Tulane University]] and received his law degree from the [[University of Texas at Austin]] in 1968.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n \n==Career==\nGoldstein joined his father's law firm in San Antonio.  After a medical deferment from the Vietnam War, he partnered with [[Maury Maverick, Jr.]], a liberal leader in Texas politics, to defend conscientious objectors and civil rights cases.<ref name=Anderson /><ref name=Swartz>Swartz, Mimi. [http://www.texasmonthly.com/story/high-times-gerry-goldstein?fullpage=1 \u201cThe High Times of Gerry Goldstein\u201d] Texas Monthly. April 1996</ref>\nIn 1970, Goldstein joined the [[National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws]] (NORML), and began building a reputation for defending drug charge cases after he represented the organization's founder, [[Keith Stroup]], after a drug bust.<ref name=Anderson /><ref name=Swartz />\n\nGoldstein represented a newly hired theater operator in San Antonio who had been arrested for showing the x-rated  movie [[Deep Throat (film)|Deep Thoat]] in 1974.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gonzalez|first1=John|title=40 years later, S.A.'s racy Deep Throat case recalled|url=http://www.expressnews.com/news/local/article/40-years-later-S-A-s-racy-Deep-Throat-case-5432579.php#/0|date=April 26, 2014}}</ref> Goldstein won the case before the Supreme Court on appeal.<ref name=Anderson />\n\nGoldstein's 1978 appeal reversed the convictions in the Piedras Negras Jailbreak Case. In that case, the two men, Sterling Davis, Sr. and William McCoy Hill, entered the border city's jail in Mexico and freed fourteen American inmates charged with drug offenses. The U.S. government [[indictment|indicted]] the two men alleging that a [[sawed-off shotgun]] used during the raid violated gunrunning laws. The men went to prison. Goldstein won the appeal by arguing that the two men had unknowingly, as opposed to intentionally, violated the law because neither had known the length at which a sawed-off shotgun was illegal.<ref name=Swartz />\n\nHe represented one of Texas House Speaker [[Billy Clayton]]'s cronies in the kickback scandal known as [[Brilab]] in 1980.<ref name=Swartz />\n\nGoldstein represented a fringe Mormon group that advocates polygamy, regarding a raid of their Texas ranch. He represented the [[Yearning for Zion Ranch]] head [[Frederick Merril Jessop]]'s case.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite news|last1=Neil|first1=Martha|title=Meet Gerry Goldstein, Lawyer for Polygamy Sect in Texas Ranch Raid |url=http://www.abajournal.com/news/article/meet_gerry_goldstein_lawyer_for_polygamy_sect_in_texas_ranch_raid |date=Apr 11, 2008 |publisher=ABA Journal}}</ref>  The [[polygamy|polygamist]] sect was investigated and prosecuted after a massive child-abuse investigation. Goldstein argued in court that although the multiple marriages were not common, the group had the right to their faith and privacy.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nGoldstein was elected president of the [[Texas Criminal Defense Lawyers Association]] (TCDLA) in 1992 and the [[National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers]] (NACDL) in 1994 and 1995.<ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref name=Anderson>Anderson, Patrick. [http://druglibrary.org/special/anderson/highinamerica15.htm \u201cHigh in America: The True Story Behind NORML and the Politics of Marijuana.\u201d] Viking Press. 1981. Chapter 15.</ref>\n\nHe represented Mexican drug lord [[Juan Garc\u00eda Abrego]] after an arrest and extradition in January 1996. Abrego hired Roberto Yzaguirre, and then Yzaguirre brought Goldstein and Tony Canales into the case.\n<ref name=Swartz />  Abrego was accused of presiding over the flow of Colombian cocaine through northern Mexico into the U.S,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cockburn|first1=Alexander|title=Whiteout: The CIA, Drugs and the Press|date=1998|publisher=Verso Publisher|pages=[https://archive.org/details/whiteoutciadrugs00cock/page/361 361]|isbn=1-85984-139-2|url=https://archive.org/details/whiteoutciadrugs00cock/page/361}}</ref> as well as money laundering, attempted bribery, and the murders of numerous individuals. Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego was convicted on all charges. He was sentenced to 11 life terms.<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. Jury Convicts Mexican on Drug Charges|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/10/17/world/us-jury-convicts-mexican-on-drug-charges.html|date=17 October 1996|agency=New York Times}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, he was the defense attorney for an indicted member of the [[Yearning for Zion Ranch]].<ref name=Vine>Vine, Katy. [http://www.texasmonthly.com/story/fundamental-arguments \u201cFundamental Arguments.\u201d] Texas Monthly. November 2009</ref>\n\nGoldstein testified before the Senate Judiciary Committee in 2010 and was critical of [[Patriot Act|the Patriot Act]]. Goldstein's criticism centered around the detainment of his client, Dr. Al-Badr Al Hazmi, a radiology resident, who was arrested the morning after the terrorist attacks on September 11, 2001. Dr. Al Hazmi was later cleared of any wrongdoing but Goldstein highlighted the violation of Dr. Al Hazmi's Fifth Amendment protections in criticizing the Patriot Act and the authorization of the Federal government by the Federal Bureau of Prisons to monitor communications between suspected terrorist and their attorneys.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.goldsteinhilley.com/attorney-testimonies/usa-patriot-act/|title=USA Patriot Act and the Attack on the 5th Amendment Right to Counsel|work=Goldstein, Goldstein, Hilley & Orr|access-date=2018-10-16|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nHe wrote an [[amicus brief]] on behalf of [[Manuel Noriega]].<ref name=Vine />\n\nGoldstein is also a former president of the National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers and a Fellow of the International Academy of Trial Lawyers, American College of Trial Lawyers, and of the American Board of Criminal Lawyers.<ref name=Fellow>[https://lawyers.lawyerlegion.com/texas/gerald-harris-goldstein-28000147 \"International Academy of Trial Lawyers, American College of Trial Lawyers, American Board of Criminal Lawyers\"]</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, Gerry Goldstein was selected as one of five 2019 recipients of the Texas Bar Foundation's Outstanding 50 Year Lawyer Award. The award recognizes attorneys whose practice has spanned 50 years or more and who adhere to the highest principles and traditions of the legal profession and service to the public. In order to honor Mr. Goldstein the Bar Foundation commissioned an oral history to recognize and preserve the accomplishments of Mr. Goldstein's legal career.  \n\n==Personal life==\nHe married Christine Sayre in 1969.<ref name=Swartz /> They live in San Antonio, Texas, and Aspen, Colorado, and have a son, Matthew Goldstein .<ref name=Gordon />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goldstein, Gerry}}\n[[Category:Texas lawyers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Texas alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=April 2018}}\n\n'''Gerald \"Gerry\" Harris Goldstein''' is a criminal defense [[Lawyer|attorney]] in [[San Antonio, Texas]], best known for his civil rights and drug-charge defenses. He is currently a partner of [https://www.goldsteinhilley.com/ Goldstein & Orr] and is Board Certified by the [[State Bar of Texas]] in [[Criminal Law]] and [[Criminal Appellate Law]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nGoldstein was born in Santa Maria, California in 1944.  At the time, his father, Eli Goldstein, was a lawyer working for the Judge Advocate General's Corps (JAG) at the Army Air Force Base in Santa Maria. His parents later moved to [[San Antonio, Texas]], where Goldstein grew up.<ref name=Gordon>Gordon, Stephen H. [http://c.ymcdn.com/sites/www.sanantoniobar.org/resource/collection/A8517B98-12D1-4287-8640-E4709DC69A36/MarApr2013SAL.pdf \u201cGerry Goldstein, for the Defense.\u201d] San Antonio Lawyer. March\u2013April 2013. Pg. 5</ref>  Goldstein has a bachelor's degree in art from [[Tulane University]] and received his law degree from the [[University of Texas at Austin]] in 1968.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n \n==Career==\nGoldstein joined his father's law firm in San Antonio.  After a medical deferment from the Vietnam War, he partnered with [[Maury Maverick, Jr.]], a liberal leader in Texas politics, to defend conscientious objectors and civil rights cases.<ref name=Anderson /><ref name=Swartz>Swartz, Mimi. [http://www.texasmonthly.com/story/high-times-gerry-goldstein?fullpage=1 \u201cThe High Times of Gerry Goldstein\u201d] Texas Monthly. April 1996</ref>\nIn 1970, Goldstein joined the [[National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws]] (NORML), and began building a reputation for defending drug charge cases after he represented the organization's founder, [[Keith Stroup]], after a drug bust.<ref name=Anderson /><ref name=Swartz />\n\nGoldstein represented a newly hired theater operator in San Antonio who had been arrested for showing the x-rated  movie [[Deep Throat (film)|Deep Thoat]] in 1974.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gonzalez|first1=John|title=40 years later, S.A.'s racy Deep Throat case recalled|url=http://www.expressnews.com/news/local/article/40-years-later-S-A-s-racy-Deep-Throat-case-5432579.php#/0|date=April 26, 2014}}</ref> Goldstein won the case before the Supreme Court on appeal.<ref name=Anderson />\n\nGoldstein's 1978 appeal reversed the convictions in the Piedras Negras Jailbreak Case. In that case, the two men, Sterling Davis, Sr. and William McCoy Hill, entered the border city's jail in Mexico and freed fourteen American inmates charged with drug offenses. The U.S. government [[indictment|indicted]] the two men alleging that a [[sawed-off shotgun]] used during the raid violated gunrunning laws. The men went to prison. Goldstein won the appeal by arguing that the two men had unknowingly, as opposed to intentionally, violated the law because neither had known the length at which a sawed-off shotgun was illegal.<ref name=Swartz />\n\nHe represented one of Texas House Speaker [[Billy Clayton]]'s cronies in the kickback scandal known as [[Brilab]] in 1980.<ref name=Swartz />\n\nGoldstein represented a fringe Mormon group that advocates polygamy, regarding a raid of their Texas ranch. He represented the [[Yearning for Zion Ranch]] head [[Frederick Merril Jessop]]'s case.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite news|last1=Neil|first1=Martha|title=Meet Gerry Goldstein, Lawyer for Polygamy Sect in Texas Ranch Raid |url=http://www.abajournal.com/news/article/meet_gerry_goldstein_lawyer_for_polygamy_sect_in_texas_ranch_raid |date=Apr 11, 2008 |publisher=ABA Journal}}</ref>  The [[polygamy|polygamist]] sect was investigated and prosecuted after a massive child-abuse investigation. Goldstein argued in court that although the multiple marriages were not common, the group had the right to their faith and privacy.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nGoldstein was elected president of the [[Texas Criminal Defense Lawyers Association]] (TCDLA) in 1992 and the [[National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers]] (NACDL) in 1994 and 1995.<ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref name=Anderson>Anderson, Patrick. [http://druglibrary.org/special/anderson/highinamerica15.htm \u201cHigh in America: The True Story Behind NORML and the Politics of Marijuana.\u201d] Viking Press. 1981. Chapter 15.</ref>\n\nHe represented Mexican drug lord [[Juan Garc\u00eda Abrego]] after an arrest and extradition in January 1996. Abrego hired Roberto Yzaguirre, and then Yzaguirre brought Goldstein and Tony Canales into the case.\n<ref name=Swartz />  Abrego was accused of presiding over the flow of Colombian cocaine through northern Mexico into the U.S,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cockburn|first1=Alexander|title=Whiteout: The CIA, Drugs and the Press|date=1998|publisher=Verso Publisher|pages=[https://archive.org/details/whiteoutciadrugs00cock/page/361 361]|isbn=1-85984-139-2|url=https://archive.org/details/whiteoutciadrugs00cock/page/361}}</ref> as well as money laundering, attempted bribery, and the murders of numerous individuals. Garc\u00eda \u00c1brego was convicted on all charges. He was sentenced to 11 life terms.<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. Jury Convicts Mexican on Drug Charges|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/10/17/world/us-jury-convicts-mexican-on-drug-charges.html|date=17 October 1996|agency=New York Times}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, he was the defense attorney for an indicted member of the [[Yearning for Zion Ranch]].<ref name=Vine>Vine, Katy. [http://www.texasmonthly.com/story/fundamental-arguments \u201cFundamental Arguments.\u201d] Texas Monthly. November 2009</ref>\n\nGoldstein testified before the Senate Judiciary Committee in 2010 and was critical of [[Patriot Act|the Patriot Act]]. Goldstein's criticism centered around the detainment of his client, Dr. Al-Badr Al Hazmi, a radiology resident, who was arrested the morning after the terrorist attacks on September 11, 2001. Dr. Al Hazmi was later cleared of any wrongdoing but Goldstein highlighted the violation of Dr. Al Hazmi's Fifth Amendment protections in criticizing the Patriot Act and the authorization of the Federal government by the Federal Bureau of Prisons to monitor communications between suspected terrorist and their attorneys.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.goldsteinhilley.com/attorney-testimonies/usa-patriot-act/|title=USA Patriot Act and the Attack on the 5th Amendment Right to Counsel|work=Goldstein, Goldstein, Hilley & Orr|access-date=2018-10-16|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nHe wrote an [[amicus brief]] on behalf of [[Manuel Noriega]].<ref name=Vine />\n\nGoldstein is also a former president of the National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers and a Fellow of the International Academy of Trial Lawyers, American College of Trial Lawyers, and of the American Board of Criminal Lawyers.<ref name=Fellow>[https://lawyers.lawyerlegion.com/texas/gerald-harris-goldstein-28000147 \"International Academy of Trial Lawyers, American College of Trial Lawyers, American Board of Criminal Lawyers\"]</ref>\n\nIn December of 2019, Gerry Goldstein was selected as one of five 2019 recipients of the Texas Bar Foundation\u2019s Outstanding 50 Year Lawyer Award. The award recognizes attorneys whose practice has spanned 50 years or more and who adhere to the highest principles and traditions of the legal profession and service to the public. In order to honor Mr. Goldstein the Bar Foundation commissioned an oral history to recognize and preserve the accomplishments of Mr. Goldstein\u2019s legal career.  \n\n==Personal life==\nHe married Christine Sayre in 1969.<ref name=Swartz /> They live in San Antonio, Texas, and Aspen, Colorado, and have a son, Matthew Goldstein .<ref name=Gordon />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goldstein, Gerry}}\n[[Category:Texas lawyers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Texas alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:Cleanu